<head>
<title>Human Relations</title>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">             
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Human Relations</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Index</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/humanrel.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/humanrel.htm#require">Requirements</a> </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<A NAME="overview"></A>
<h3>Human Relations</h3>

The Human Relations major is a joint program of the departments of Anthropology and Sociology and 
Psychology. Students may pursue either a Bachelor of Arts or a Bachelor of Science degree in Human Relations. 
These studies, complemented by the broad liberal education of all-college requirements, will give the student a 
solid foundation for life in our society and will facilitate graduate study in a broad spectrum of disciplines or 
professional opportunities in personnel management, many social service fields, and other areas involving 
human relations.
<A NAME="require"></A>
<pre>
<h3>Degree Requirements</h3>
<h4>Major requirements (B.A./B.S.) -- 43-44 hours</h4>
A/S 100 Introduction to Cultural Anthropology    4 hours
Psych 100 Introduction to Psychology             4 hours
A/S 150 Introduction to Sociology                4 hours 
A/S 325 Social Science Research Methods          4 hours
A/S 326 Social Science Theory                    4 hours
Psych 333 Social Psychology                      4 hours
A/S 495 Senior Seminar                           4 hours

<h4>At least two of the following:</h4>
A/S 309 Race and Ethnic Relations                4 hours
A/S 310 Social Class in America                  4 hours
A/S 321 Sociology of Religion                    4 hours
A/S 324 Sociology of Mental Illness              4 hours
A/S 351 Urban Anthropology                       4 hours
A/S 352 Political Anthropology                   4 hours
A/S 355 Communication and Culture                4 hours
A/S 357 Witchcraft, Medicine & Religion in Cross-Cultural Perspective     4 hours

<h4>At least two of the following (7-8 hours):</h4>
Psych 215 Survey of Human Development               3 hours
Psych 313 Cognitive Psychology                      4 hours
Psych 320 Industrial and Organizational Psychology  4 hours
Psych 355 Psychology of Personality                 4 hours
Psych 357 Psychological Disorders                   4 hours

NOTE: There is no minor in human relations. Students who major in human relations
may not minor in psychology or anthropology/sociology. Majors in human relations
may minor in Human Development but may not count any course beyond the 
introductory level toward both major and minor. 
</pre>
<hr>
