<html>

<head>
<title>The Military Science Program</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Military Science Program </h1>
<hr>
<h2>Index</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/mili.htm#faculty">Faculty</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/mili.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/mili.htm#programs">Programs</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/mili.htm#eligibility">Eligibility</a></li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/mili.htm#commision">Commision </a></li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/mili.htm#requirements">Requirements</a></li>

<li><a href="/academic/catalog/mili/courses.htm">Course Offerrings</a> </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<A NAME="faculty"></A><h3>Faculty</h3>
<pre>
Major Jann E. Stovall, Chair  Major Ralph Peterson
Capt. Michelle C. Mason       Capt. Jon D. Schlafer
MSG Larry Montgomery          SFC Ronald J. Tucker


</pre>
<A NAME="overview"></A><h3>Overview</h3>
<p><br>
The Reserve Officer Training Corps Unit Program at Rockford College is offered
through a 
cross-enrollment agreement with Northern Illinois University [NIU ROTC
Program--(815) 
753-0574]. Army ROTC is specifically designed to give students training and
experience in 
organization, motivation and leadership, while completing bachelor's degrees in
their majors of 
choice. Completion of the ROTC program leads to a commission in the active U.S.
Army, Army 
Reserves or National Guard. The Reserve Officer Training Corps is open to all
eligible full-time 
students, both male and female. A total of 22 semester hours of academic credit
is available and is 
applicable toward graduation requirements as elective credit. The curriculum is
centered on an 
applied leadership training program, which is designed to develop personal
traits and qualities 
essential to successful leadership in civilian life as well as in the military
environment. There is no 
military service obligation for completing only the first two years of Army
ROTC. <br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
<A NAME="programs"></A><h3>Programs</h3>
<p>Army ROTC offers both four-year and two-year programs. The four-year program
consists of a 
basic course and an advanced course. The basic course, normally taken in the
freshman and 
sophomore years, provides instruction in the fundamentals of leadership,
management and the 
national security structure, with emphasis on leadership development. The
advanced course, which 
normally covers the final two years at the college, includes a six-week Advanced
Camp, usually 
attended the summer following the junior or senior year of college. While
enrolled in the advanced 
program, all students receive $150 per month during the school year and are paid
for attending the 
Advanced Camp. Instruction includes advanced leadership development, group
dynamics, 
organization and management, small unit tactics, and military law and
administration. The program is 
flexible enough to accommodate almost all students who are interested in
participating. The 
two-year program is designed specifically for transfer students or other
students who were unable 
to take Army ROTC during the first year or two of college. To enter this
program, students usually 
attend a six-week Basic Camp the summer before entering the Advanced Course.
Application is 
made in the spring. Students earn more than $700 while attending Basic Camp.
Upon completion of 
the camp, students may enter directly into the Advanced Course and start
receiving $150 per 
month. Students who are military veterans may contact the NIU Army ROTC offices
at (815) 
753-6234 for special information regarding entry into the Advanced Course. <br>
</p>
<A NAME="eligibility"></A>
<h3>Eligibility</h3>
<p>To enroll in the Military Science program leading to an Army officer's
commission, students<br>
must be: <br>
<br>
Citizens of the United States or lawfully admitted to the United States for<br>
permanent residence under applicable provisions of the Immigration and<br>
Naturalization Act and At least 17 years of age or have parental consent.<br>
Full-time students at Rockford College.<br>
Able to complete the ROTC program and receive a bachelor's degree before
reaching<br>
30 years of age. Age requirements may be waived in some cases, especially for
those<br>
with prior military service and those majoring in nursing.<br>
Physically and mentally qualified and of good moral character.<br>
<br>
If these criteria are not met, students may enroll in military science courses
for academic<br>
credit, but will not be eligible for appointments as commissioned officers. <br>
<br>
Entering freshmen should register for Military Science 101 in their first
semester.<br>
Sophomores with no previous ROTC experience may register for both the freshman
and<br>
sophomore courses and become eligible to enter the advanced course at the
beginning of<br>
the junior year. Juniors and seniors who wish to register for the basic program
should<br>
confer with the military science program advisor before enrolling. <br>
</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<A NAME="commision"></A>
<h3>Commissioning requirements</h3>
<pre>To be eligible for a commissions as second lieutenants in the U.S. Army, 
students must have completed all military science advanced program course 
work and be in good academic standing. For other requirements, confer with 
the chair of the Department of Military Science.

Classes are taught on the Rockford College campus when there are ten or 
more students registered during a semester.  Rockford College students attend 
ROTC classes on the Northern Illinois University campus (DeKalb, IL) 
whenever less than ten Rockford College students are enrolled during a 
semester.




<A NAME="requirements"></a><strong>Core Requirements -- 18 hours</strong>

 Mils 101 Basic Military Science I                    2 hours
    Mils 204 Intermediate Military Science II         2 hours
    Mils 301 Military Training and Tactics I          3 hours
    Mils 302 Military Training and Tactics II         3 hours
    Mils 401 Military Leadership and Management I     4 hours
    Mils 402 Military Leadership and Management II    4 hours

<strong>Electives from the following -- 6 hours</strong>

    Mils 350 Practicum in Military Science            3 hours
    Mils 495 Independent Study                        3 hours
    Courses in military history and in management/national security studies. 
    (Consult NIU catalog or Department of Military Science at NIU.)


</pre>
