<html>



<head>

<title>Nursing</title>

<!-created by Ryan Kussner>
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">

</head>



<body>

<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>

Department of Nursing</h1>

<hr>

<h2>Index</h2>

<ul>

<li><a href="/academic/catalog/nurse/nurse.htm#faculty">Faculty</a> </li>

<li><a href="/academic/catalog/nurse/nurse.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>

<li><a href="/academic/catalog/nurse/nurse.htm#career">Career Opportunities</a> </li>

<li><a href="/academic/catalog/nurse/nurse.htm#require">Requirements</a> </li>

<li><a href="/academic/catalog/nurse/courses.htm">Course Offerings</a> </li>

</ul>

<hr>

<A NAME="faculty"></A>

<h3>Faculty</h3>

<pre>

Dr. Rebecca Cohen	Diana Cullen
Marilyn Hartinger	Judie Heinschel
Wealtha Helland      	Cynthia Koroll



</pre>

<A NAME="overview"></A>

<h3>Overview</h3>



  The nursing major at Rockford College prepares students as professional nurse generalists to provide nursing care to individuals, families, groups, and communities with diverse health needs. The major offers a broad scientific base in nursing, related disciplines, and the liberal arts; an introduction to nursing research; an understanding of nursing as a scholarly discipline; practice in multiple settings with diverse clients; and knowledge of the roles and functions of nursing in the health care system and society. 

<P>The Department of Nursing offers a program of study that leads to a Bachelor of Science degree in Nursing (BSN). The BSN completion track is designed for Registered Nurses (RNs) who are graduates of diploma or associate degree programs in nursing. The basic four-year track is for beginning students interested in becoming registered nurses. Successful completion of the basic track qualifies students to apply for the professional nurse licensure examination. The liberal arts education tradition of Rockford College fosters a holistic view of persons, facilitates critical thinking and decision making, provides opportunities for exchanging ideas, stimulates intellectual growth and creativity, and encourages contributions to the nursing profession and society. The integration of professional and liberal arts education at Rockford College ensures that students gain an appreciation for diversity, develop confidence in their own abilities, and apply their talents within a practice discipline.<P>

Students will learn to communicate effectively, think analytically and solve problems, deal with ethical concerns, and collaborate with others in the health care system. Personal and professional growth opportunities promote commitment to students' own health, the care of clients, and enhancement of the profession.<P>

The Rockford College nursing program is accredited by the National League for Nursing and is approved by the Illinois Department of Professional Regulation.

<P>

<A NAME="career"></A>

<h3>Career opportunities</h3>

Registered Nurses with BSN degrees have numerous employment and advanced educational opportunities. Graduates from the Rockford College nursing program have positions as staff nurses in acute care and community health; become nurse managers and staff developers; and practice industrial and home health nursing. In addition, some continue their education to become school nurses. Others enter graduate school to pursue a specialized interest in nursing.

<P>

<A NAME="require"></A>

<h3>Degree requirements</h3>

<P>

  Special requirements include CPR certification for health-care providers, immunizations, nursing uniforms and equipment, and malpractice insurance. Some of these items are at students' expense, and others are included in course fees. Students will be notified in advance of expenses.<P>

<STRONG>Basic BSN Track</STRONG>
<P>The basic BSN track helps students acquire knowledge, skills, values, and attitudes essential to professional nursing. The strong clinical component lets the student apply knowledge and skills in clinical settings. The individualized professional internship in the final semester smoothes the transition from student to practitioner.<P>

An interim internship between junior and senior year is optional. Entering freshmen or transfer students at Rockford College enroll in general education courses and prerequisites for the nursing major. Entering freshmen should have successfully completed high school biology, chemistry, and two years of algebra. Students who do not have this background may not be able to complete the BSN degree in four years. 

<P>Students apply for admission to the nursing major in the fall semester before enrolling in clinical nursing courses. To be accepted into the nursing major students must:

<UL>
<LI>Maintain a minimum cumulative GPA of C+ (2.5).
<LI>Achieve at least a C (2.0) grade in all required social and natural science support courses.
<LI>Provide proof of satisfactory health examination, immunizations, and CPR certification.
</UL>



Students are responsible for their own transportation to clinical experiences and each student must have a car available for community health clinical experience (Nursing 406).<BR>



<P>  

<strong>Major requirements (Basic track)   52 hours</strong>

<PRE>Nurs 203 Nursing Process	                        2 hours
Nurs 216 Introduction to Professional Nursing Practice	6 hours
Nurs 301 Health Assessment	                        3 hours
Nurs 310 Adult Health Nursing I	                        6 hours
Nurs 312 Family Health Nursing	                        4 hours
Nurs 314 Child Health Nursing	                        5 hours 
Nurs 316 Mental Health Nursing	                        4 hours
Nurs 370 Pathophysiology Applied to Nursing	        3 hours
Nurs 403 Nursing Research	                        3 hours
Nurs 406 Community Health Nursing	                4 hours
Nurs 408 Leadership and Management in Nursing	        4 hours
Nurs 410 Adult Health Nursing II	                4 hours 
Nurs 495 Senior Seminar	                                4 hours</PRE>



<strong>Supporting requirements    42 hours</strong>

<PRE>Bio 209 Anatomy and Physiology	                        4 hours
Bio 222 Pharmacology	                                2 hours
Bio 230 Principles of Nutrition	                        3 hours
Bio 308 Microbiology	                                4 hours
Bio 314 Vertebrate Physiology	                        4 hours
Chem 131 Survey of Chemistry	                        4 hours
Chem 132 Aspects of Organic/Biochemistry	        4 hours
A/S 150 Introduction to Sociology	                4 hours
Psych 100 Introduction to Psychology	                4 hours
Psych 215 Survey of Human Development	                3 hours
Phil 256 Biomedical Ethics	                        3 hours
Math 223 Beginning Statistics 	                        3 hours</PRE>

</pre>

<P><STRONG>BSN Completion track</STRONG><P>

To be accepted in the BSN completion track, students must be Registered Nurses in Illinois (or have licenses pending). Validation tests are not required if the RN has graduated within the last five years from a state approved or NLN accredited program, is currently licensed, and has practiced nursing for one thousand hours in the past three years. The NLN Mobility Profile II tests will be used for nurses who do not meet the above criteria. The students must also meet grade point and general requirements for admission to the nursing program. 

<P>Registered Nurses receive advanced placement in nursing based on their current Illinois licensure in nursing.

<P>Rockford College awards 25 semester hours of credit to Registered Nurses who meet current licensure and practice requirements or who have successfully completed validation tests. Courses are designed to meet the learning needs of adult students. The BSN completion track addresses the same program goals as the basic track.<P>



<strong>Major requirements   52 hours </strong>

<PRE>Based on licensure and practice or validation of prior learning 28 hours

Nurs 301 Health Assessment 	                                 3 hours
Nurs 370 Pathophysiology Applied to Nursing	                 3 hours
Nurs 386 Transitions in Nursing	                                 3 hours
Nurs 403 Nursing Research	                                 3 hours
Nurs 406 Community Health Nursing	                         4 hours
Nurs 408 Leadership and Management in Nursing	                 4 hours
Nurs 495 Senior Seminar in Nursing	                         4 hours</PRE>

<P>Supporting requirements<P>

Students' previous education will be evaluated on an individual basis to determine which supporting courses may be required.



<hr>

<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</a> </p>

