<A NAME= faculty ></A>
<H3>Faculty</H3>

<PRE>
Dr. Nalamolu Gopala Rao, Chair
</PRE>

<A NAME= overview ></A>
<H3>Overview</H3>

<PRE>
Two basic courses in physics are provided to complement other scientific
disciplines and to give students in humanities, arts and social studies a
basic understanding of the physical laws which govern our universe. The
calculus-based year of physics courses is for preprofessional majors such
as biology, chemistry, engineering, medicine and dentistry. The
algebra-based physics program is for some science majors and non-science
majors. 

The Department of Physics offers a minor in physics, and one advanced
course is offered every fall and spring for minors in physics. The
concentration of mathematics and physics in the program listed below can
prepare students for graduate school in physics. Additional advanced
courses in physics are offered as required.
</PRE>

<A NAME= career ></A>
<H3>Career opportunities</H3>

<PRE>
Physics is an integral part of preparation for careers in engineering and
other scientific fields. 
</PRE>

<A NAME= require ></A>
<H3>Degree requirements</H3>

<PRE>
<STRONG>Minor requirements -- 22 hours</STRONG>
Phys 201 Introduction to Physics I     5 hours 
Phys 202 Introduction to Physics II    5 hours 
At least three 300-level courses  12 hours
</PRE>

