<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Political Science</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Index</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/polisci/polisci.htm#faculty">Faculty</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/polisci/polisci.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/polisci/polisci.htm#career">Career Opportunities</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/polisci/polisci.htm#require">Requirements</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/polisci/courses.htm">Course Offerrings</a> </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<a name="faculty"><h3>Faculty</h3></a>
<pre>
Dr. Jules Gleicher, Chair    Dr. Zoran Zic
Robert J. Evans




</pre>
<a name="overview"></a><h3>Overview</h3>
<p><br>
The Department of Political Science helps students develop their minds and characters to become 
decent, responsible, informed citizens. Political science shows the relation of politics to human 
nature and examines the basic alternatives in political life. The ordinary citizen has decent opinions 
about justice and the common good. The educated citizen should rise above opinion in the direction 
of truth while maintaining goodwill, sincerity, tolerance, generosity, and fairness. A liberal, political 
education will equip students to analyze and criticize their country without becoming destructive of 
the common good or domestic tranquillity. The department's academic offerings cover the full range 
of essential subjects in the discipline of political science: political philosophy, constitutional law, 
American government and politics, comparative politics and international relations, and diplomacy 
and statecraft. While there is no special pre-law program at Rockford College, most students who 
plan to attend law school major in political science and are advised by its faculty. Certain political 
science courses are required for the criminal justice track of the anthropology/sociology major. The 
department sponsors a Washington and United Nations Semester for upper-division students, as 
well as regular semester and summer internships for appropriate individual students. Students 
interested in political science for the purpose of becoming secondary school teachers should also 
consult the catalog section on the Social Sciences divisional major. The Department of Political 
Science offers the Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science degrees. <br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
<A NAME="career"></a><h3>Career Opportunities</h3>
<p>Governmental work is one of the most extensive areas of opportunity for political science graduates. 
The degree can also lead to positions with private businesses, or in law, politics, journalism, and 
teaching, among others. <br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
<a name="require"></a><h3>Degree Requirements</h3>
<pre><strong>Major requirements (B.A.) -- 45 hours
</strong> 
PS 101 Introduction to Political Science                      4 hours
PS 102 American Government                                    4 hours
PS 241 Comparative Politics or
PS 282 International Relations    }                           4 hours
Four additional courses in Political Science              14-16 hours
PS 495 Senior Seminar                                         4 hours
Econ 101 Principles of Microeconomics or
Econ 102 Principles of Macroeconomics  }                      4 hours

Two courses from the following:
Hist 101 Western Civilization I                               4 hours
Hist 102 Western Civilization II                              4 hours
Hist 103 Western Civilization III                             4 hours
Hist 303 U.S. History to 1789                                 4 hours
Hist 304 U.S. History 1789-1865                               4 hours
Hist 305 U.S. History 1865-Present                            4 hours

One of the following courses:
A/S 100 Introduction to Cultural Anthropology                 4 hours
A/S 115 World Regional Geography                              4 hours
A/S 150 Introduction to Sociology                             4 hours
Math 223 Beginning Statistics                                 3 hours
Math 224 Elements of Statistics                               4 hours
Phil 221 Logic                                                3 hours
Phil 311 Symbolic Logic                                       3 hours


<strong>Major requirements (B.S.) -- 53 hours
</strong> 
All requirements for the B.A. degree plus eight hours of course work in 
mathematics, computer science, appropriate quantitative courses in 
social science, or laboratory science, beyond the college general 
education requirements.


<strong>Minor requirements  -- 18 hours
</strong> 

PS 101 Introduction to Political Science                     4 hours
PS 102 American Government                                   4 hours
Three additional courses in political science            10-12 hours
Transfer students must take at least three of the five required courses at 
Rockford College. A &quot;C&quot; average must be maintained in all 
political science courses.


</pre>
