<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Preprofessional Programs</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Preprofessional Programs</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Index</h2>
<ul><li><a href="/academic/catalog/preprof/preprof.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/preprof/preprof.htm#require">Requirements</a> </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<A NAME="overview"></A>
<h3>Overview</h3>


  Rockford College offers combined programs in engineering, dentistry, law, medicine, pharmacy and the paramedical areas which permit students to transfer 24 to 30 hours for bachelors degrees. Rockford Collegeand most professional schools believe, however, that it is desirable for the student to complete work for the degree before beginning professional training. General requirements for bachelors degrees in these combined programs are:<P>
Completion of three years of study in liberal arts courses, with at least 30 of the last 36 semester hours at Rockford College. Completion of the all-college degree requirements.
Completion, before leaving Rockford College, of at least two thirds of the requirements for the major.  An average of at least C in all the specified work (one to two years) at the professional school.<P>

The specific courses and number of credits required vary with each program. Likewise, entrance requirements for the professional programs may vary with the institution. Therefore students must consult with  the specific program advisor.<P>

Most application procedures begin in the fall, so we are unable to provide proper evaluation
based on two to four weeks of contact if students apply during the first year here.<P>

<strong>Health Professions</strong><BR><P>
Students interested in the allied health professions (i.e. medical technology, physical therapy, occupational therapy, etc.) may obtain a Rockford College degree and then go to the appropriate professional school to complete their education. Students may choose either the B.A. or the B.S. degree but they must complete the foreign language requirement for the B.A.  They may major in any field as long as they fulfill the science and mathematics requirements of the professional school.  For most schools, these requirements include one year of biology, one year of physics, one course in calculus and analytic geometry, and two years of chemistry.  They should also take Mathematics 224 or Mathematics 230.  If 
they major in biology, they should take Biology 101 and Biology 103 and/or Chemistry 105 and Chemistry 106 in the freshman year.  A student's six or eight semester plan will be determined by the major program chosen.<P>

<strong>Premedical and predental programs</strong><BR><P>
Since medical and dental school requirements are undergoing change, students are strongly
urged to be familiar with the specific requirements of the schools to which they intend to apply. Information on the specific requirements of medical schools may be found in Medical School Admission Requirements, available from the premedical advisor. Corresponding information regarding dental schools may be found in Admission Requirements of American Dental Schools, available through the dental advisor.<P>

If students have strong foundations in science, they may major in almost any area. However, a major in chemistry with the addition of Biology 101 and 103, or a major in biology with the addition of Physics 105-106 or 201-202 and Mathematics 130 (required by some medical schools) usually will meet the requirements.<P>
<A NAME="require"></A>
The minimum requirements for almost all medical and dental schools include the following:
<P>
<pre>
Bio 101 Principles of Biology                4 hours
Bio 103 Animal Biology                       4 hours
Chem 105-106 General Chemistry               8 hours
Chem 205-206 Organic Chemistry               8 hours
Phys 105-106 Fundamentals of Physics or
Phys 201-202 Introduction to Physics   }  8-10 hours
</pre>
<P>
Almost all medical schools require applicants to take the Medical College Admission Test
(MCAT), usually in the spring of the junior year or in the fall of the senior year. Applications are available from the program advisor. A basic understanding of statistics is recommended for this exam. It may be obtained by taking Math 224 Elements of Statistics or Math 312 Intermediate Statistical Methods.<P>
Most dental schools require applicants to take the Dental Aptitude Test (DAT). Applications for the test may be obtained from the program advisor. Arrangements for taking these tests are the responsibility of the student.<P>
<strong>Prepharmacy program</strong><P>
If students plan to go into pharmacy, they may take two, three or four years of course work at
Rockford College before going to a college of pharmacy.

Students may take two years of basic mathematics and science courses at Rockford College
and then transfer to a pharmacy program if they have completed the prerequisites. At the University of Illinois Collegeof Pharmacy, students can earn a Doctor of Pharmacy degree after four more years of study. They may need to take some courses in the summer to meet the entrance requirements.<P>

Students may choose to take four years at Rockford College for a bachelor's degree and then go four years to the UIC College of Pharmacy and earn a PharmD. To accelerate this process, students may participate in a three-four program, attending Rockford College for three years of general education courses and the science and mathematics courses needed to study pharmacy. Students would take four additional years at UIC College of Pharmacy, earning a bachelor's degree from Rockford College after one or two years at 
UIC and a PharmD degree at the end of the four years. The three-four program requires students to complete the Rockford College General Education Requirements, including at least one course in sociology or psychology, One in economics or finance, and one in physics. Students also must complete two-thirds of the requirements for a major at Rockford College.<P>

The UIC College of Pharmacy requires that entering students earn at least a 2.5 grade point
average (4.0 scale) with no grades below C and have at least 20 semester hours of general education courses. Students must take at least one course in each of the following five areas (these courses also meet Rockford College General Education Requirements):<P>
<pre>
    Social and behavioral sciences (i.e., sociology, psychology)
    Economics and finance (i.e., economics, banking, finance, accounting)
    Fine arts (i.e., art, music, drama)
    Physical sciences (i.e., physics - recommended, geology, astronomy)
    Humanities (i.e., history, philosophy)</pre><P>

One of the above courses must meet the UIC cultural diversity requirement.<P>
<strong>Preveterinary program</strong><P>
Some schools of veterinary medicine require applicants to complete a course or two in agricultural sciences prior to admission. Students should be familiar with the requirements of the schools to which theywish to apply. Generally, the minimum requirements for admission to veterinary school include:
<pre>
Bio 101 Principles of Biology             4 hours
Bio 103 Animal Biology                    4 hours
Chem 105-106 General Chemistry            8 hours
Chem 205-206 Organic Chemistry            8 hours
Phys 105-106 Fundamentals of Physics      8 hours
Bio 309 Genetics                          3 hours
Bio 308 Microbiology                      4 hours
Chem 308 Biochemistry                     4 hours
</pre>
<P>
<strong>Pre-engineering program</strong><P>
Students with an interest in engineering have two choices in pre-engineering at Rockford
College.  Obtain a bachelor's degree from Rockford College, then go to an engineering school, usually earning a bachelor or master of science in engineering after two more years of study.  Enter the three/two program, taking courses for three years at Rockford College to meet General Education Requirements and take basic mathematics, science, and computer courses required to study engineering. With two additional years of study at an engineering school, students earn a bachelor's degree from Rockford College at the, end of the first year and a bachelor of science degree in the desired field of engineering at the end of the second year.<P>

Each engineering school has specific requirements which generally involve two years of
mathematics, including calculus and differential equations, one year of physics, proficiency in an appropriate computer language (usually Pascal or FORTRAN) and one or two years of chemistry.<P>

Rockford College is affiliated with the College of Engineering of the University of Illinois, Washington University in St. Louis, and the University of Southern California. Further information about the program and its specific requirements are available from the liaison officer at Rockford College.<P>

Rockford College students also have followed three/two programs with a variety of other
engineering schools, including Illinois Institute of Technology.<P>

There are many career advantages in earning both a baccalaureate from Rockford College and an engineering degree. The liberal arts component contributes a broader background in the social sciences and humanities and should enhance the ability to communicate, solve problems and reason. If students earn a bachelor of arts degree, they will learn a second language and become familiar with another culture, which will help them deal with clients and customers from abroad. The dual degree background is viewed as an 
asset by many employers.<P>

Information on other professional programs is available from the program advisors.
<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</a> </p>
