<head>
<title>Psychology</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Psychology</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Index</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/psych/psych.htm#faculty">Faculty</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/psych/psych.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/psych/psych.htm#career">Career Opportunities</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/psych/psych.htm#require">Requirements</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/psych/courses.htm">Course Offerings</a> </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<A NAME="faculty"></A>
<h3>Faculty</h3>
Faculty
<pre>
Dr. Christine Bruun, Chair 
Dr. Anna Chomiak
Dr. Stuart Tousman 
Dr. Belinda Wholeben
</pre>
<A NAME="overview"></A>
<H3>Overview</H3>
<pre>
The Psychology Department seeks to develop understanding of principles of human 
behavior and thought, which are both broadly applicable and deeply explanatory, through 
such scientific methods as observation, measurement, experiment, and theory construction. 
and by examining great themes, great events, and great men and women  just as a 
philosopher, historian, or student of literature would do.<P>

As psychology majors, students will be prepared to benefit from a broad variety of 
experiences. Students will have a deeper understanding of the human condition as it 
applies to them and to their fellow humans. As liberal arts students, they will learn to 
organize and analyze information, to speak and write clearly, and to use numbers 
effectively to make a point.  As psychology majors, students will learn to enrich their 
personal relationships with human understanding and sound social judgment. The 
Department of Psychology offers Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science degrees.  The 
department encourages its majors to enrich their understanding with one or two semesters 
in London at Regent's College.</pre>

<A NAME="career"></A>
<h3>Career opportunities </h3>
<pre>
The Rockford College psychology program will prepare the student well for graduate 
training, and professional careers and opportunities continue to expand for holders of 
graduate degrees: counseling, medical psychology, clinical psychology, industrial 
psychology, school psychology, engineering psychology, academic and research 
psychology, and more.  <P>

Students also can choose course work to prepare for graduate programs outside 
psychology leading to professional specializations in business, social work, law, medicine, 
and education. Many students continue with graduate study in preparation for teaching or 
research careers.  <P>

Many enter career positions in areas such as mental health, educational services, social 
work, and personnel work.  Others obtain positions in conventional business or social 
service settings not directly related to psychology, but in which psychological knowledge 
and skills may be applied.
</pre>
<A NAME="require"></A>
<h3>Degree requirements</h3>
<pre>
Depending on students' career interests, they may be encouraged to take courses in 
anthropology/sociology, biology, economics and business, education, mathematics, 
philosophy and religion. 


Psychology majors seeking secondary school certification are required to take a minimum 
total of 32 credit hours in psychology.

Major requirements (B.A./B.S.) -- 28 hours
    Note: Psychology 100, 200 and 300 should be completed early in the major, if possible.

Psych 100 Introduction to Psychology        4 hours
Psych 200 Scholarly Methods in Psychology   4 hours
Psych 300 Experimental Psychology           4 hours
Psych 495 Senior Seminar                    4 hours

At least one course in experimental Psychology
Psych 212 Biopsychology                     4 hours
Psych 312 Sensation and Perception          4 hours
Psych 313 Cognitive Psychology              4 hours
Psych 338 Psychology of Learning            4 hours
Psych 347 Psycholinguistics                 4 hours

At least one course in Theoretical Perspectives
Psych 215 Survey of Human Development       3 hours
Psych 333 Social Psychology                 4 hours
Psych 335 Psychology of Personality         4 hours
Psych 346 History & Systems of Psychology   4 hours
Psych 357 Psychological Disorders 4 hours

Additional psychology course work to fulfill minimum  4 hours

Supporting requirements (B.A.) --           3-4 hours
Math 223 Beginning Statistics or
Math 224 Elements of Statistics             3-4 hours

Supporting requirements (B.S.) --           6-7 hours
Math 223 Beginning Statistics or
Math 224 Elements of Statistics             3-4 hours
Course work in Computer Science             3 hours

Minor requirements -- 16 hours
Psych 100 Introduction to Psychology        4 hours

At least one course in experimental Psychology
Psych 212 Biopsychology                     4 hours
Psych 312 Sensation and Perception          4 hours
Psych 313 Cognitive Psychology              4 hours
Psych 338 Psychology of Learning            4 hours
Psych 347 Psycholinguistics                 4 hours

At least one course in theoretical Perspectives
Psych 215 Survey of Human Development       3 hours
Psych 333 Social Psychology                 4 hours
Psych 335 Psychology of Personality         4 hours
Psych 346 History & Systems of Psychology   4 hours
Psych 357 Psychological Disorders           4 hours

Additional psychology course work to fulfill minimum  4 hours

At least eight semester hours must be completed at Rockford College for a minor in psychology.
</pre>
