<title>Science and Mathematics</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Science and Mathematics</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Index</h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/scmath/scmath.htm#overview">Overview</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/scmath/scmath.htm#career">Career Opportunities</a> </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<A NAME = "overview"></a><h3>Overview</h3><P>

  The divisional major in Science and Mathematics is an integrated program in which the courses
are intellectually related. It has two main purposes:
   <UL><LI>To give students flexibility in preparing for a career involving diversity of background in the
     sciences.<BR>
    <LI>To allow students to concentrate in areas of specialization which cut across the traditional
    scientific disciplines.</UL><P>

The major provides students an opportunity to concentrate in no more than three related disciplines with not less
than 44 hours of course work appropriately divided among the disciplines. Students must develop the program in
consultation with the appropriate departmental chair and obtain the approval of the division as a
whole. Students must complete a substantial amount of 300-level work in at least two departments in the
division.<P>


<a name ="career"></a><h3>Career Opportunities</h3><P>
     The Science and Mathematics divisional major lends itself to a variety of specific career 
goals or preparationsfor further study. Among the possible careers are science-related business, 
science librarianship, sciencepublishing, secondary school teaching, scientific computer applications, 
environmental protection activities, etc.<P>

<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</a> </p>
