<HEAD>
<TITLE>Master of Arts in Teaching</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College <BR>
Master of Arts in Teaching</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Index</H2>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/mat/mat.htm#faculty">
Faculty</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/mat/mat.htm#overview">
Overview</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/mat/mat.htm#require">
Requirements</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/mat/courses.htm">Course Offerings</A>
</UL>
<HR>

<A NAME="faculty"></A>
<H3>Faculty</H3>

<PRE>
     Winston McKean, Dean of Graduate Education
     Barbara Heal, Chair and MAT Director         
     Dr. Debra Bennett
     Ann Caton                          
     Dr. Lou Ferroli
     Dr. Christy Lendman                     
     Dr. Ronald Reigner  
</PRE>

<A NAME="overview"></A>
<H3>Overview</H3>
<PRE>
The Rockford College Master of Arts in Teaching program is designed to 
help students develop further knowledge in one or more academic 
disciplines, increase understanding of the educational process, and enhance 
various skills involved in teaching.

Rockford College offers several tracks which meet professional requirements 
for elementary and secondary certification in Illinois and in most other states.  
Students may concentrate in elementary education, secondary education in a 
variety of subject areas, remedial reading, or learning disabilities.  There also 
are courses to help meet teacher qualification requirements in reading and 
other areas of special education.  Students may not transfer more than six 
credit hours from other institutions to the MAT.

Rockford College, in cooperation with Performance Learning Systems (PLS), 
also offers several graduate level courses designed to provide practical, up-
to-date teaching strategies for practicing educators.  These courses are acceptable 
as an area of concentration in the instructional strategies track.
</PRE>


<A NAME="require"></A>
<H3>Degree requirements</H3>
<PRE>
<STRONG>The following tracks are available in the MAT program:</STRONG>

     Elementary Education     
     Learning Disabilities
     Secondary Education      
     Certification
     Reading             
     Instructional Strategies


<STRONG>Foundation courses -- 9 hours</STRONG>

Required for all students in all tracks and options of the MAT:

    Ed 605 Philosophical Foundations of Education  - 3 hours
    Ed 615 Introduction to Research - 3  hours
    Ed 620 Psychological Foundations of Education - 3 hours


<STRONG>Research courses -- 3 hours</STRONG>

Thesis option only:

    Ed 625 MAT Seminar - 1 hour
    Ed 626 MAT Research  - 2 hours

<A NAME="eled"></A>
<STRONG>Elementary Education track -- 32-36 hours</STRONG>

    Foundation courses listed above - 9 hours

    Research courses listed above (thesis option only) - 3 hours

    Area of concentration and electives - 20-27 hours

         Students may elect courses from a variety of areas --
         including gifted, special education, reading, instructional
         strategies, or a general elementary education program -- in
         consultation with the advisor to include on their approved
         Plan of Study. A certification track is also available.

<A NAME="seced"></A>
<STRONG>Secondary Education track -- 32-36 hours</STRONG>

Areas of concentration available are English, Social Studies, Art, or 
Mathematics. Students also may pursue a general secondary education 
program. A certification track is also available. 

    Foundation courses listed above - 9 hours

    Research courses listed above (thesis option only) - 3 hours

    Area of concentration and electives - 20 hours
         Select specific courses in consultation with the advisor;
         courses must be listed on the approved Plan of Study. 

<A NAME="read"></A>
<STRONG>Reading track -- 32 or 36 hours</STRONG>

This track offers a thesis option requiring a total of 32 credit hours and 
a non-thesis option requiring a total of 36 credit hours. 

    Foundation courses listed above - 9 hours

    Required core (10-14 hours)

         Ed 511 Reading Methods - 3 hours
         Ed 553 Literature for Children or
         Ed 558 Literature for Adolescents } 2-3 hours
         Ed 556 Reading Diagnosis - 3 hours
         Ed 557 Instructional Support Methods in Reading - 3 hours
         Ed 559 Clinical Experience in Reading - 3 hours

    Approved reading courses (4-13 hours)

         Ed 522 Reading in Content Areas - 3 hours
         Ed 554 Whole Language Methods in Reading - 2 hours
         Ed 555 Remedial Reading: Practicum - 3 hours

    Appropriate electives selected with the advisor - 9 hours

    Non-thesis option supporting courses - 9 hours 

    Thesis option supporting courses (5 hours) 

         Ed 625 MAT Seminar - 1 hour
         Ed 626 MAT Research - 2 hours
         At least two hours of elective course work - 2 hours
         Completion of an approved thesis/project

<A NAME="ld"></A>
<STRONG>Learning Disabilities track -- 36-37 hours</STRONG>

Completion of this sequence meets requirements for certification in 
learning disabilities in the State of Illinois. Approval in behavioral 
disorders and/or mild mental impairments is also available.

    Foundation courses listed above - 9 hours

    Core courses (24-26 hours)

         LD 200/201 Field Experience-LD (undergraduate) - 2 hours
         LD 542 Development & Education of the Exceptional Child - 3 hours
         LD 558 Learning Disabilities: Characteristics - 3 hours
         LD 560 Learning Disabilities: Diagnosis - 3 hours
         LD 562 Learning Disabilities: Methods - 3 hours
         LD 564 Consulting Strategies - 2 hours
         LD 565 Advanced L.D. Diagnosis - 3 hours
         LD 608 Learning Disabilities: Practicum - 3-5 hours
         LD 695 Seminar on Special Education - 2 hours

    Supporting courses, selected from the following:  (3-6 hours)

         Ed 539 Counseling and Guidance - 3 hours
         Ed 556 Reading Diagnosis - 3 hours
         Ed 557 Instructional Support Methods in Reading - 3 hours
         LD 580 Behavior Disorders: Characteristics - 3 hours
         LD 581 Behavior Disorders: Methods - 3 hours
         LD 585 MI (EMH/TMH): Characteristics - 3 hours
         LD 586 MI (EMH/TMH) Methods - 3 hours
         Psych 554 Psychological and Educational Measurement - 3 hours

<A NAME="cert"></A>
<STRONG>Certification track -- 36 hours</STRONG>

Students with undergraduate degrees may enter the certification 
track and complete either elementary certification or secondary 
certification in a variety of content areas (see Education
section of this catalog).

    Foundation courses listed above - 9 hours

    Required courses--to be determined, based on evalu-
    ation by the Dean of Graduate Education or the Chair 
    of the Education/Child  Development Department   }    27 hours

    Electives--to be determined as needed.

Note: Additional general education courses may be required in order 
to meet state certification standards.

<A NAME="is"></A>
<STRONG>Instructional Strategies track -- 32 or 36 hours</STRONG>

A minimum of 32 semester hours of graduate credit is required 
for the Instructional Strategies program under the thesis option, 
including 5 elective hours (with 3 hours credit for the thesis and
MAT seminar). 

A minimum of 36 semester hours of graduate credit is required under 
the non-thesis option, including 5-12 elective hours.

    Foundation courses listed above - 9 hours

    Research courses listed above (thesis option only) - 3 hours

    Area of concentration courses (12-15 hours)

         Ed 580 Project T.E.A.C.H. - 3 hours
         Ed 581 P.R.I.D.E. - 3 hours
         Ed 582 Teaching through Learning Channels - 3 hours
         Ed 583 Patterns for I.D.E.A.S. - 3 hours
         Ed 584 Keys to Motivation - 3 hours
         Ed 585 Peer Coaching - 3 hours
         Ed 586 Cooperative Learning - 3 hours
         Ed 590 Teaching Skills of the 21st Century - 3 hours

    Electives  -- 5-12 hours

         To be determined in consultation with the advisor 
         and indicated on the approved plan of study.

</PRE>

