<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fall Semester 1996 Information &amp; Instructions</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>FALL SEMESTER 1996<BR>
INFORMATION AND INSTRUCTIONS</H1>
</CENTER>

<A NAME="howto"></A>
<H2>Registering for Classes</H2>
Matriculated undergraduate students (those students formally admitted 
to pursue a B.S., B.F.A., B.S., or B.S.N. degree at Rockford College) 
who wish to pursue a course of study during the Fall 1996 Semester will 
pre-register in person at the Office of Registration in Burpee Center 
according to the following schedule. 
<PRE>
	   Seniors Only:    Monday, April 22nd              9 AM-Noon

     Juniors & Remaining
		Seniors:    Monday, April 22nd              1 PM-6 PM

  Sophomores & Remaining
      Juniors & Seniors:    Tuesday, April 23rd             9 AM-Noon

    Freshmen & Remaining
     Sophomores, Juniors
	      & Seniors:    Tuesday, April 23rd             1 PM-6 PM

	 Open to Anyone:    Wed-Thurs, April 24th-25th      9 AM-6 PM
			    Fri, April 26th                 9 AM-3 PM
</PRE>


<H2>To Register:</H2>
<OL>
<LI>Study the schedule and make your tentative course selections prior 
to meeting with your academic advisor.
<LI>Schedule an advising appointment with your advisor prior to the 
registration time.  Sign-up sheets for appointments should be                   
posted on faculty office doors by Friday, March 29th.  If               
necessary, contact your advisor by phone or mail in order to                    
schedule an advising appointment.
<LI>You will receive a signed program card from your advisor                   
listing the courses for which you wish to enroll.
<LI>At the time of registration, you will receive a computer-generated 
sheet which has your personal information on it.  You will need to correct 
or verify the information on that sheet, and sign and date it.  If 
you give your program card to someone else to bring to Registration 
for you, please give them the current information so that they can 
verify it.
<LI>You will need to present the following things in order to                  
register for classes:
<UL>
<LI>A program card with your advisor's signature on it.  You                           
must fill out the back side of the card and sign it.            
(NOTE: All full-time students need the College Forum Series)
<LI>Permission slips for courses requiring permission and/or 
special testing (i.e. math modules, 300-level courses for                          
freshmen, etc.)  ALSO, if an undergraduate is within 8                          
hours of graduation and wants to take a graduate level                          
course, that student must have a signed permission slip for                     
that course.
<LI>Independent Study Forms -- if registering for an independent 
study, those forms must be in the Office of Registration by 
Monday, September 9th at 4 p.m.
<LI>A computer-generated data sheet with the student's signature and 
the date on it.
</UL>        
<LI>Pre-registration is complete when your selection of classes has                    
been entered into the computer and you have received a confirming 
copy of your program of study.  This registration will not be considered 
final until all proper forms (18-hour,independent study, tutorial, 
internship, etc.) have been filed.
</OL>

<A NAME="pay"></A>
<H2>Payment of Bill and Confirmation of Registration</H2>
Your bill must be paid in full or arrangements must have been made 
for payment by 4 p.m., Tuesday, September 3rd (the first day of classes).   
At the time your bill is taken care of, the Business Office will make a         
notation in the computer which will automatically kick out an official  
schedule of your classes.  That schedule will be sent to your campus            
mail box, or home address if you are part-time.  The Business Office            
will validate your ID card after you have taken care of your bill.

<A NAME="drop"></A>
<H2>Drop/Add</H2>
Drop/Add forms will be available beginning Monday, April 29th, and      
may be picked up from the Registration Office in Burpee Center during   
regular office hours.  You only need your advisor's signature to drop or        
add a course at this time, unless the course is closed.  If it has reached 
its limit, you will need the signature of the Department Chair in order 
to have the limit raised to accommodate you.

<A NAME="can"></A>
<H2>Cancellation Policy</H2>
Rockford College reserves the right to cancel any classes where the     
enrollment is fewer than ten (10) students.  A full refund of tuition   
and fees will be made for any cancelled class.

<A NAME="hours"></A>
<H2>Registration Office Hours</H2>
Monday - Friday 8 a.m.-5 p.m. <BR>
[Please Note: Our computer is not up until 9 a.m. each day]

<A NAME="immunize"></A>
<H2>Immunization Policy</H2>
In accordance with the American College Health Association 
Immunization Policy, and in compliance with State of Illinois law, 
the following immunizations are required of all students: tetanus, 
diphtheria, mumps, oral polio, measles, and rubella.  As required 
by Illinois state law, records of proof of immunity are required for 
all students born after January 1, 1957, who are enrolling for the first 
time in a four-year institution of higher education in Illinois.  Students 
who are living in Rockford College residence halls, but who are not 
enrolled in Rockford College classes, must provide immunization records 
before moving into the residence halls.  For more details on this 
policy, please contact the Health Services Office in Lang Health Center 
(226-4083).
	
<A NAME="notice"></A>
<H2>Important Notice Regarding Payment of Your Bill</H2>
All tuition and fees are payable at the Business Office no later than 
4 p.m., September 3, 1996.  You must make contact with the Business 
Office in order to complete your registration.  If we do not receive 
notice of confirmation by the end of the first week of classes (September 
10th), your registration will be canceled.  If you want to re-register 
for your classes, you will have to pay the late fee.
<P>The "Confirmation of Registration" can only be done at the 
Business Office.  If you are waiting for financial aid, you can 
get a "pending aid" form from Financial Aid that will allow the 
Business Office to issue you the confirmation.  Your ID card will 
be validated by the Business Office once you have cleared that office.

<A NAME="tut"></A>
<H2>Tutorial Courses</H2>
($70.00 per credit hour fee beyond tuition)<BR>
Any student who desires to apply to take a course listed in the 
catalog, but not offered in this class schedule, must submit a 
Tutorial Form (available from the Office of Registration), with all 
required signatures.  The tutorial must have the approval of the 
Department Chair, the instructor of the desired tutorial and the Dean 
of the College.  The instructor will meet the student regularly.  An 
examination is given and a grade is assigned.

<A NAME="int"></A>
<H2>Internships</H2>
You must have a minimum cumulative grade point average of 2.5 in order 
to be eligible to take an internship.  If you qualify, the form must be 
in the Registration Office by the last day to add a class (Friday, 
September 13th).
<P>(You must work three hours for each credit hour of an internship.)
					
<A NAME="progchg"></A>
<H2>Program Changes</H2>
<STRONG>FULL SEMESTER COURSES</STRONG><BR>                     
<PRE>
To add a course................................4pm, Sep 13<BR>
To drop a course without transcript notation...4pm, Sep 20<BR>                
To drop with "W"...............................4pm, Nov 8<BR>
</PRE>
You cannot drop a course after Nov 8th.  If you stop attending you
will receive whatever grade you have earned to that point.<BR><BR>
<STRONG>HALF-SEMESTER COURSES</STRONG><BR>                     
<PRE>
To add a course................................4pm, 2nd class day<BR>
To drop a course without transcript notation...4pm, 3rd class day<BR>         
To drop with "W"...............................4pm, 7th class day<BR>
</PRE>
You cannot drop a course after the 7th class. If you stop attending you
will receive whatever grade you have earned to that point.<BR><BR>
<STRONG>MODULAR COURSES</STRONG><BR>                     
<PRE>
To add a course................................4pm, day after 1st class<BR>
To drop a course without transcript notation...4pm, day after 1st class<BR>         
To drop with "W"...............................4pm, day before class ends<BR>
</PRE>
Any modular course dropped on the day the class ends will receive
whatever grade the instructor wishes to give.  In most cases,
it will be an "F".<BR>

<A NAME="inc"></A>
<H2>Incompletes</H2>
<STRONG>ADMINISTRATIVE INCOMPLETE</STRONG><BR>
The Dean of the College, may in exceptional circumstances, approve 
an administrative incomplete ("I") for a student who has carried a 
subject with a passing grade until near the end of the semester and 
then, because of unusual and substantial cause beyond the student's 
control, has been unable to take the final examination or to complete 
some limited amount of work.  An application form is completed by the 
student and must be signed by the instructor and the Dean of the College.  
Failure to appear for a final examination or to complete term work in 
the time allowed is not automatic justification for an incomplete, except 
as indicated above; and in default of such evidence, the test or other 
work will be graded as an "F" and averaged into the student's semester 
or term work.<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>MEDICAL INCOMPLETE</STRONG><BR>
A medical incomplete ("IM") grade may be reported for a student who 
is unable to complete course work and/or take the final examination 
because of illness.  An application form must be completed by the student 
and signed by the instructor of the course and the Dean of the College 
upon receipt of a written statement by a physician.

<P>An "IM" grade must be removed within six months after the official 
ending date of the semester in which the medical incomplete was incurred.  
The student with an "IM" grade may 1) elect to complete the course work 
and thereby receive a standard letter grade, 2) petition the professor 
to receive a "P" in the course if enough work was completed to legitimize 
such a grade,  or 3) petition the Dean of the College to receive an 
"MW" (Medical Withdrawal) from the course.

<P>It is the student's responsibility, in consultation with the instructor, 
to arrange for the removal of the medical incomplete.  There will be 
a $20.00 charge for each medical incomplete granted.

<A NAME="crsnum"></A>
<H2>Course Numbering</H2>
<PRE>
000-099 Special courses, pre-college
100-199 Introductory courses open to all students
200-299 Courses open to sophomores, juniors, seniors
300-399 Courses open to juniors & seniors
400-499 Courses open to seniors
500-599 Courses offered for graduate credit (open to
	enrollment by anyone with a bachelor's degree)
600-699 Courses offered for graduate credit (open only
	to students admitted to one of the Rockford
	College graduate degree programs)
700-799 Unassigned
800-899 Continuing education credit courses (open to
	anyone)
900-999 Non-credit courses (open to anyone)
</PRE>

