<HTML>

<HEAD>
<Title>Rockford College News Media</title>
</head>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#251899" vlink="#870999">
<a NAME ="TOP"></a>

<hr>
<H1 align="center">Rockford College </h1>

<h2 align="center">News Release</h2>
<hr>
<h3>For immediate release</h3>
<p>August 19, 1996</p>
<h3>Rockford College Music Academy students to perform at Jane Addams Memorial Park dedication</h3>

<p>Students from the Rockford College Music Academy will provide the music for a dedication 
ceremony of the new Jane Addams Memorial Park at 11 a.m. Monday, August 26, at Navy Pier in 
Chicago. First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, five female U.S. senators, members of the 
Democratic Womens Caucus, Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley, poet Gwendolyn Brooks and Rockford 
College President William A. Shields are invited to attend. </p>
<p>Jane Addams, a Freeport native, is one of the most distinguished Rockford College alumni, 
graduating from the college in 1882. Founding Hull House on Chicagos near west side in 1889,
 she devoted her life and her efforts towards the improvement of the lives of immigrants and 
youth. For her efforts, she received the Nobel Peace Prize and the worlds admiration. </p>
<p>The Hull House School of Music, the first community school of music in the United States,
 is the model upon which the Rockford College Music Academy was founded. Approximately 21 
Music Academy Suzuki violin students aged eight to 18 will perform a classical repertoire 
during the dedication ceremony. Shields will represent Addams alma mater at the event. </p>
<p>Jane Addams Memorial Park features "A Touch of Jane Addams," the first monument to a 
Chicago woman. The sculpture, commissioned by the B.F. Ferguson Fund of The Art Institute of 
Chicago, was created by internationally renowned artist Louise Bourgeois. The monument, which 
consists of six granite sculptures of carved hands atop massive bases, is located in a peaceful garden setting overlooking Lake Michigan at Ohio Street.</p>
<p>The Jane Addams Memorial is a collaborative effort of the Chicago Department of Cultural 
Affairs, the Chicago Park District, the Chicago Department of Transportation, the B.F. 
Ferguson Monument Fund of The Art Institute of Chicago, the Metropolitan Pier & Exposition 
Authority, the Illinois Department of Conservation, the Chicago Department of Environment, 
the Chicago Department of Planning and Development, the Jane Addams Sculpture Committee, 
the Jane Addams Hull-House Museum, Friends of the Parks, the Lake Michigan Federation, 
Openlands, the Streeterville Organization of Active Residents, and the Lincoln Park Steering 
Committee. </p>

<p>About the Jane Addams Memorial:</p>
<ul>
<li>"A Touch of Jane Addams," a tribute to the Nobel Peace Prize winner, social reformer, 
and Rockford College graduate, was commissioned by the B.F. Ferguson Fund of The Art Institute 
of Chicago, and curated by Mary Jane Jacobs.
<li>Louise Bourgeois created six individual granite sculptures featuring hands of different 
ages in different expressions: the vulnerable child, the able adult, comforting hands, helping 
hands, hands strong in solidarity. The artist arrived at the image of the hand to give visual 
form to the ideals Jane Addams stands for and to express her relationship to the common person.
<li>Set in ornamental prairie grasses native to Jane Addams local origins, the Jane Addams 
Memorial is one of seven parklands honoring a woman. Others are Jane Addams Playlot, Kathy 
Osterman Beach, Madame Curie, Emma Lazarus, Lillian Piotrowski and Almira Simmons parks.
<li>Jane Addams Memorial Park is located at 600 N. Lake Shore Drive and 600 E. Ohio Street, 
linking Lincoln Park, Milton Lee Olive Park, and Navy Pier Park along the Lakefront.
<li>Rockford College is a four-year independent coeducational institution offering a broad 
range of undergraduate degrees in traditional liberal arts and professional fields plus 
masters degrees in teaching and in business administration. Rockford College serves 
approximately 1,500 full- and part-time students. Chartered in 1847, Rockford College is 
celebrating its Sesquicentennial in 1997.
</ul>
<p>#  #  #</p>
<p>For more information, contact the Office of College Relations at (815) 226-4140.</p>

