<HTML>

<HEAD>
<Title>Rockford College News Media</title>
</head>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#251899" vlink="#870999">
<a NAME ="TOP"></a>

<hr>
<H1 align="center">Rockford College </h1>

<h2 align="center">News Release</h2>
<hr>
<h3>For immediate release</h3>
<p>August 21, 1996</p>
<h3>Rockford College Three Penny Theater to produce Neil Simon play</h3>

<p>Rockford College students will stage The Star-Spangled Girl by Neil Simon 
Friday and Saturday, August 30 and 31, as the first play in the Three-Penny 
Theater series for the 1996-97 academic year.</p>
<p>The Star-Spangled Girl is a fast-moving, hilarious comedy that deals with 
two earnest young men struggling to put out a "protest" magazine, and the 
all-American girl who moves in next door and manages to send both of them 
into a romantic tail spin.</p>
<p>The Three-Penny Theater is a long-standing Rockford College tradition. Each production 
is entirely student-produced, and admission is only three cents.</p>
<p>Rockford College sophomore David Rodriguez, a performing arts major, will direct the 
play. Last year, Rodriguez wrote and directed The Specter series as part of the 
Three-Penny Theater.</p>
<p>Senior performing arts major Ryan Landerholm of Rockford is Andy Hobart, and senior 
performing arts major Carlos Landeros from Chicago is Norman Cornell. Kira Dolen is the 
"star-spangled girl," Sophie Rauschmeyer.   </p>
<p>The Star-Spangled Girl runs at 8 p.m. Friday and Saturday, August 30 and 31, in 
Cheek Theatre in Clark Arts Center. General admission for the play is three cents.</p>
<p>Rockford College is a four-year independent coeducational institution offering a 
broad range of undergraduate degrees in traditional liberal arts and professional 
fields plus masters degrees in teaching and in business administration. Rockford 
College serves approximately 1,500 full- and part-time students. Chartered in 1847, 
Rockford College is celebrating its Sesquicentennial in 1997.</p>
<p>#  #  #</p
<p>For more information, contact the Office of College Relations at (815) 226-4140.</p>


