<HEAD>
<Title>Rockford College News Media</title>
</head>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#251899" vlink="#870999">
<a NAME ="TOP"></a>

<hr>
<H1 align="center">Rockford College </h1>

<h2 align="center">News Release</h2>
<hr>
<h3>For immediate release</h3>

<p>July 31, 1996</p>
<h3 align="center">Rockford College Music Academy names four new faculty members</h3>
<p>Martha Frantz, director of the Rockford College Music Academy, today announced the addition of four professional musicians to the staff.</p>
<p>Claire Stagl studied with Laurence Davis and Frances Larimeris at Northwestern University where she earned a master of music degree in piano performance and pedagogy. She will reside in Rockford and is accepting traditional piano students of all ages and abilities. She earned her bachelor of music in piano performance from Ithaca College in Ithaca, N.Y.</p>
<p>Rachel Handlin has joined the string faculty of the Rockford College Music Academy as an instructor of violin and viola. Handlin earned both a bachelor of music degree and a master of music degree in violin performance from Northern Illinois University in DeKalb, where she studied with Pierre Menard and members of the Vermeer Quartet. She received Suzuki training from Dr. Laurel Thurman and Eleanor Stanlis, director of the Suzuki program at the Music Academy. Handlin will remain an active performer with the Chicago Sinfonietta, the Rockford Symphony Orchestra and as a founding member of the Essen Trio.</p>
<p>Tatiana Keriz joined the Music Academy as a Suzuki and traditional violin instructor. Trained in the Ukraine, she has the equivalent of a bachelors degree and a masters degree in violin performance and pedagogy from the Lvov State Music Conservatory. She recently completed Suzuki Teacher Training courses with Eleanor Stanlis and is a member of the Rockford Symphony Orchestra.</p>
<p>Suni Yemiko Clinton joins the Rockford College Music Academy faculty as an early childhood music specialist. A recent graduate of Wheaton College, where she earned a bachelor of music education degree, Clinton will work with Suzuki and traditional piano students in their music readiness and reading curriculum. Her training in a South American music conservatory will help her blend Solfege, Orff and Kodaly methodology into the piano curriculum.</p>
<p>The Rockford College Music Academy is a member of the National Guild of Community Schools of the Arts and is a not-for-profit community school of music designed to provide high-quality musical instruction regardless of age, ability to pay or demonstrated musical talent.</p>
<p>Rockford College is a four-year independent coeducational institution offering a broad range of undergraduate degrees in traditional liberal arts and professional fields plus masters degrees in teaching and in business administration. Rockford College serves approximately 1,500 full- and part-time students. Chartered in 1847, Rockford College is celebrating its Sesquicentennial in 1997.</p>
<p>#  #  #</p>
<p>For more information, contact the Office of College Relations at (815) 226-4140.</p>
<A HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
