<HEAD>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<h1>Rockford College<BR>
DEPARTMENT OF COMPUTER SCIENCE</h1>
<hr> 
<h2> Department Information</h2>


 Computers and computer technology are changing the world as we know it, and the rapid development of this field
shows no signs of slowing. Hardware technology is expanding in power and speed while contracting in size and price.Computer scientists must harness this technology and channel its use for the good of mankind.

Early computer scientists were trained merely as programmers.  With the nineties, however, a new generation of
computer scientists has emerged. Today, these individuals are educated not only in the mechanics and technology
of the computer and its programs but also in the possibilities of applying computers to solving new and more
challenging problems. 

The computer scientist of today and tomorrow is a problem-solver who has a broad educational background in
human needs and drives. The computer scientist understands the various possibilities for applications of computers
to life, and frequently acts as a communication link between man and machine. To help students gain that
understanding, we arrange and supervise internships with a wide variety of businesses and organizations.

The Department of Computer Science offers Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science degrees, with a choice of
Management Information Systems or Mathematics/Computer Science options under either degree. 



<HR>
<h2>FACULTY BACKGROUND</h2>
<HR>
<b>Dr. Gerald Caton -  Department Chair</B><HR><P></P>
Dr. Gerald Caton was born and raised in the Pacific Northwest.
He received his Bachelor of Arts Degree from Western Washington
State University, majoring in Mathematics and minoring in History.
He received a Master of Science Degree in Mathematics from Oregon State University 
and entered the Peace Corps, teaching at the University of the Philippines for two years, 
where he helped to establish the country's first computer research center.  
He received his PhD. in Mathematics from the University of Montana. He has 
taught at Northern Montana State College, and came to Rockford 
College in 1979.  He helped to establish the Computer Science Department, 
and was among 60 mathematicians selected by the 
American Mathematical Society to attend the 15 month Institute for
Retraining in Computer Science.  He was chosen as the first recipient 
of Rockford College's Excellence in Teaching award, and he is presently 
serving as the Chair of the Computer Science & Math Departments.
<P></P>
<BR><HR>
<B>Mary Jeffreson Associate Professor</b><hr><P></P>
Associate Professor Mary Jeffreson joined Rockford College faculty in 1987 to teach both
computer science and mathematics.  She had previously lectured in mathematics in a South 
Australian teacher training college before migrating in the eighties and retraining in computer science.  
She has taught most of the non-business oriented courses in the Computer Science major(which has undergone several 
revisions in the past few years).
She is especially interested in artificial intelligence and its programming languages.  
She is planning a sabbatical in 1997-8 when she will undertake further Computer Science studies at a Chicago-area university.  Her credentials are B.Sc., University of Sydney; B.A., University of New England, Australia; Adv. Dip.Ed, Uni
in July 1996 she informed Rockford College Computer Science alumnae and alumni that a Computer Science newsletter is planned, asking for news from them, either by e-mail or letter. If you are an alum who was not contacted and who has anything to tell us, please contact her by whatever medium you prefer.<P>
<hr>
<B>Kevan Griggs Assistant Professor</b><HR><P></P>
Asst. Prof. Griggs was born in central Illinois.  After serving 6 years in the United States Navy, he received his first Bachelor of Science Degree from Illinois State University in Economics and Geography. He received his Second Bachelor of Science
Degree from Quincy University with a major in Computer Science. From there, he worked
in Industry for the next 7 years as a Systems Analyst for an Electronics firm and a Major
Life Insurance Company.  He received his Masters Degree In Applied Computer Science
from Illinois State University with emphasis in the area of Data Communications.  He has
taught at Lincoln Land Community College, and John Wood Community College and was
instrumental in setting up the internal training program for the Insurance Company in 1990.  
He came to Rockford College in 1994 and teaches departmental courses from
the introductory level to and including the upper level undergraduate courses.  He is 
the advisor to the Rockford College Computing Society.
<p><BR><P>
