<HEAD>
<TITLE>Anthropology and Scoiology Detailed Course Descriptions</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College<BR>
Department of Anthropology and Sociology</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>
 <P> Anthropology courses are 100, 110, 115, 120, 351, 352, 355, 356,
361, and 362.  
 <P> Sociology courses are 150, 303, 304, 305, 306, 307, 308, 309,
310, 311, 312, 313, 315, 317, 318, 320, 321, and 322, 324 and
340.  
<P>  Anthropology and Sociology courses are 228, 325, 326, 330, 331,
and 495.

<A NAME="100"></A>
<H3>100 Introduction to Cultural Anthropology        4</H3>
<P>An introduction to the basic concepts of anthropology and
methods used to study cultures, with emphasis on analyzing
descriptive material about cultures.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>
<A NAME="110"></A>
<H3>110 Introduction to Archaeology			4</H3> 
<P>For students with no previous background in archaeology. This
course has two major emphases: to expose students to
contemporary archaeological methods and the theories underlying
them; and to introduce archaeological materials from the
Americas, northern Europe, sub-Saharan Africa and Asia.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="115"></A>
<H3>115 World Regional Geography			4</H3>
<P>For students with no previous background in geography. After an
initial discussion of the earth as a planet, this
problem-oriented  course will focus on the effect the physical
environment in each part of the world has had on local social,
political, economic, religious and historical developments. The
course stresses the ways environmental factors have helped shape
human activity (e.g. adaptations to marine, plain, mountain
environments, etc.).<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ:
None.  Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="120"></A>
<H3>120 World Ethnography				4</H3>
<P>An introduction to the anthropological methods of studying
culture and the detailed study of several cultures from
different parts of the world. For those students who want to
take only one course in cultural anthropology.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="150"></A>
<H3>150 Introduction to Sociology			4</H3>
<P>Introduction to the scientific point of view in social
relations, including social structure, culture patterns, the
person and social groups, social institutions, social
interaction, social control, stratification and social change.
Analysis of selected social issues and participation in small
study groups to analyze particular social topics. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>
<A NAME="228"></A>
<H3>228 Introduction to Peace and Conflict Studies	4</H3>
<P>(XL: A/S 228) The purpose of this course is to deepen our
understanding of the causes and consequences of war, violence,
and conflict and of the means of conflict resolution and
management. The course will explore the different approaches
taken by the social sciences in the study of conflict resolution
and management. (Note: Course satisfies major and minor
requirements in Political Science, but does not satisfy major or
minor requirements in Anthropology/Sociology.) <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: S; NO in
Political Science. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>
<A NAME="303"></A>
<H3>303 The Family					4</H3>
<P>The study of the family as the basic social institution and its
important functions of procreation and socialization. Emphasis
on the permanence and pervasiveness of this social institution
and the fact that there is no human society in which some form
of the family does not appear; nor, so far as we know, has there
ever been such a society. Cross-cultural description and
analysis of family forms; major focus on the family in the
United States.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S
100 or 150.  Meets: SNO.  Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="304"></A>
<H3>304 Social Problems				4</H3>
<P>Any situation which a significant number of the members of a
group regard as a threat to one or more of the groups basic
values and which they believe to be remediable by collective
action is a social problem. This course is concerned with the
study of such problem areas as crime, war, disease, poverty,
race relations, mental illness, violence, alcohol and drug
addiction. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or
150. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A>
<A NAME="305"></A>
<H3>305 Criminology					4</H3>
<P>Analysis of causes and consequences of criminal behavior in
terms of behavior systems rather than legal classification.
Topics include maturation in crime, criminal associates, police
roles and practices, and functioning of courts. Emphasis on
theoretical approaches, criminal typologies, and empirical
research. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 150.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A>
<A NAME="306"></A>
<H3>306 Juvenile Delinquency 				4</H3>
<P>A study of the history, causes, and consequences of juvenile
misbehavior. Development of a conceptual scheme for classifying
delinquency research. Discussion of institutional efforts to
control, treat, rehabilitate, and prevent juvenile deviance.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 150. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="307"></A>
<H3>307 Corrections 					4</H3>
<P>Study of various programs, social structures, and administrative
organizations for treating criminal offenders, as well as
evaluation of their effectiveness. Analysis of criminal justice
and social processes; punishment and treatment techniques;
probation; parole; diversion; and correctional institutions of
the future. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 150.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="308"></A>
<H3>308 Collective Behavior and Social Movements	4</H3>
<P>Collective behavior encompasses a wide range of group phenomena,
including riots, revolutions, fads, crazes, panics, rumors,
public opinions, and social movements. All are collective
responses to, as well as causes of, social change; and they
emerge when values and institutions are changing. Elementary
forms of collective behavior (panics, rumors) are relatively
spontaneous and unstructured; longer lasting activities, such as
social movements, require more planning and coordination.
Theories, research, and current events are analyzed. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or 150.
Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="309"></A>
<H3>309 Race and Ethnic Relations			4</H3> 
<P>Analysis of the causes and consequences of prejudice and
discrimination. Examination of minority/majority relations in
the economy, political and legal institutions, education, and
religion. Study of anti-Semitism; the black experience in white
society; Americans of Indian, Puerto Rican, Mexican, Oriental,
Hawaiian, and Cuban descent.  Discussions of conflict and
resolution. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100
or 150. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="310"></A>
<H3>310 Social Class in America			4</H3>
<P>An introduction to the principal sociological approaches to
problems of inequality through critical examination of empirical
studies. Topics include theories of social stratification, types
of stratification systems, consequences of stratification and
mobility, and changes in systems of stratification, with
particular focus on American society.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 100 or 150. Meets:
SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="312"></A>
<H3>312 The Criminal Justice System			4</H3>
<P>A survey of the administration of justice in the United States
with a description of the total system, including an analysis of
principles of law and case studies related to the functions of
police, correctional agencies, courts, and probation and parole
agencies.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 150 and
PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Every third semester.</A>
<A NAME="313"></A>
<H3>313 Sociology of Law				4</H3>
<P>The study, through use of sociological concepts, of legal codes;
the social roles of criminal, lawyer, judge, and juror; and
their relation to the general culture and structure of society. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 150 and PS 102.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="315"></A>
<H3>315 Introduction to Population Studies		4</H3>
<P>Numbers, characteristics, and distribution of people throughout
the world, with emphasis on the United States. Nondemographic
factors, such as social, economic, and political variables, are
analyzed for their roles in explaining demographic variables and
processes. Analysis of population theory and empirical research.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or 150.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="317"></A>
<H3>317 Urban Sociology				4</H3>
<P>Deals with the historical development, function, growth, nature,
institutional dynamics and structure of the city, with special
emphasis on social relationships and contemporary urban
problems. Issues of community diversity, processes of
ghettoization and suburbanization, and ecology of the city. The
course includes types of communities and their relation to the
larger social system.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ:
A/S 150. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="318"></A>
<H3>318 Social Change					4</H3>
<P>Study of contemporary changes in rural and urban societies;
analysis of their social institutions, social organizations and
value systems, and their adequacy in meeting needs of peoples.
Theories of social change; social and political movements, and
consequences of their successes and failures. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or 150. Meets:
S. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="321"></A>
<H3>321 Sociology of Religion				4</H3>
<P>Study of interrelationship of society, culture and religion.
Comparative study of religion in different social contexts and
analysis of current religious trends in terms of their relation
to social change. Special topics include religious evolution and
the psychological bases for religious belief. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 150. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="322"></A>
<H3>322 Sociology of Aging				4</H3>
<P>Analysis of the theory and methods of social gerontology.
Attention to the developmental, disengagement, activity,
continuity and age stratification approaches to aging, and to
cohort and maturation explanations of the position and problems
of the aged in urban-industrial societies. Topics include
comparative and historical perspectives of the roles and
statuses of older people in familial, community and
institutional settings and in the economy and political life.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 150. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A>
<A NAME="324"></A>
<H3>324 Sociology of Mental Illness			4</H3>
<P>The study of social norms and processes which have a marked
bearing on the production or course of various forms of psychic
disturbance (especially as such disturbance impairs the
individuals ability to carry out usual roles), or which govern
the ways disturbed persons are perceived, defined, and dealt
with during and after acute disturbance. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 100 or 150. Meets:
SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="325"></A>
<H3>325 Social Science Methods			4</H3>
<P>(XL: Hist, PS 325) A course to familiarize students with social
science research methods including survey techniques,
interviewing, participant observation and linguistic analysis.
B.S. students should take this course before their senior year.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Consent of
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>
<A NAME="326"></A>
<H3>326 Social Science Theory				4</H3>
<P>A close examination of the work of leading classical theorists
from Comte to Parsons  with particular emphasis on Marx,
Durkheim, Weber and Simmel tracing influence on contemporary
sociological thinkers. Analysis of current sociological work
from the functional, conflict, symbolic interactionist,
exchange, and ethnomethodological perspectives. B.S. students
should take this course before their senior year.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Consent of instructor.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A>
<A NAME="330"></A>
<H3>330 Introduction to Social Work 			4</H3>
<P>History and present organization of social work; casework, group
work; community organization, public agencies, administration
and research. This course cannot be used to satisfy the Social
Studies Divisional requirements.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 100 or 150.
Scheduled: Every three semesters.</A>
<A NAME="331"></A>
<H3>331 Methods of Social Work Intervention	4</H3>
<P>Special study of the profession of social work with emphasis on
social casework. Assessing a clients strengths and weaknesses;
analyzing interpersonal relationships; studying interviewing
techniques and using community resources. Cannot be used to
satisfy the Social Studies Divisional requirements. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or 150 and A/S
330. Scheduled: Every three semesters.</A>
<A NAME="340"></A>
<H3>340 The Sociology of War and Peace		4</H3>
<P>This course seeks to examine the complex interrelationships
between war as an historically emergent social institution and
society and culture. Among the topics to be studies are
socialization for warfare, civil-military relations, war and
inequality, war and social change, and the military in a new
environment. The course will provide for the selective
examination of empirical studies and theories in the areas of
social change, social movements, and military sociology.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 150 or consent of
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="351"></A>
<H3>351 Urban Anthropology				4</H3>
<P>Urbanism, the culture of living in cities, and urbanization, the
growth and development of cities and their hinterlands, are
analyzed using cross-cultural perspectives. Particular attention
will be paid to cities in the developing countries. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or 150. Meets:
SNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A>
<A NAME="352"></A>
<H3>352 Political Anthropology				4</H3>
<P>(XL: PS 352) The evolution of political processes and
institutions including bands, tribes, chiefdoms and the archaic
state. Special topics in contemporary non-western societies
include succession to office, conflict resolution, factions, and
brokerage. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or
150. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="355"></A>
<H3>355 Communication and Culture 			4</H3>
<P>Relations between different forms of communication and culture
are explored. Specific topics include how language shapes
reality; the evolution and development of communications in
humans; communications and social class; language change;
psycholinguistics; sociolinguistics; jokes, myths, riddles and
tall tales as communications systems; the communications media
and culture. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="357"></A>
<H3>357 Witchcraft, Medicine & Religion in Cross-Cultural Perspective		4</H3>
<P>An examination of belief systems people use to make sense of the
universe, and the world, in which they live. Using information
from around the world, and from different historical periods,
students will explore how humanity has attempted to deal with
this intractable problem. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100 or consent of
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A>
<A NAME="358"></A>
<H3>358 Medicine and Healing in Cross-Cultural Perspective			4</H3>
<P>An examination of the concept of illness and of the medical,
pharmacological, and healing practices used to combat illness in
different parts of the world. The course will address the
relative efficacy of scientific and traditional medicines and
techniques, and the different ways practitioners address the
whole array of physical, mental, and social problems. The roles
of physician, nurse, shaman, medicine man, witch doctor, and
herbalist will be examined.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: A/S 100 or consent of
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>
<A NAME="361"></A>
<H3>361 People and Cultures of Africa		4</H3>
<P>This is an area  course to familiarize students with the human
diversity in Africa. Topics include Africa's place in human
evolution; the geography, history, and languages of Africa;
economics, kinship; politics and religion in traditional African
cultures; relations with peoples from other areas; slavery and
Africa; modernization and culture change; African liberation
movements; Africa's place in the modern world. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="362"></A>
<H3>362 Peoples and Cultures of the Caribbean 	4</H3>
<P>This is an area course to familiarize students with the human
diversity in the Caribbean. Topics to be discussed include the
Caribbean before Columbus; the arrival of the Europeans; the
introduction of African slaves; African patterns found in the
Caribbean today; Caribbean marriage and kinships; voodoo, shango
and other syncretic cults; Caribbean economic and political
development; emigration from the Caribbean to the United States,
Canada, France and Britain; independence and communism in the
Caribbean. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S 100.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: When staffing allows.</A>
<A NAME="364"></A>
<H3>364 Race and Ethnic Relations in England	4</H3>
<P>Offered only at Regent's College.</A>
<A NAME="495"></A>
<H3>495 Senior Seminar					4</H3>
<P><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Senior standing.
Meets: S. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly</A>

<HR>
<A HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
