<html>

<head>
<title>Classics Detailed Course Descriptions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</head>

<body><h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Classics</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Detailed Course Descriptions</h2>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/class/detail.htm#classics">Classics</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/class/detail.htm#greek">Greek</a> </li>
<li><a href="/academic/catalog/class/detail.htm#latin">Latin</a> </li>

<pre>
<HR>
<A NAME="classics"></A>
<h3>Classics Courses (Also see Greek and Latin listings)</h3>
<HR>
<A NAME="c111"></A>
<h3>111 Mythology of Greece and Rome  3 Hours</h3>
A study of Greek and Roman myths with consideration of the various theories of
their origin anddevelopment and their importance in English literature. Special 
emphasis is put on understanding Greek and Roman religion, their divinities
and religious practices.  PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a>
 Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="c123"></A>
<h3>123 Greek Civilization  3 Hours</h3>
A study of intellectual, artistic, social, and cultural life in Greece during the
 classical period. PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: LNO. </a>Scheduled: Alternate years. 
<A NAME="c124"></A>
<h3>124 Roman Civilization  3 Hours</h3>
A study of intellectual, artistic, social, and cultural life in Rome with particular
attention to the late republic and early empire. PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: LNO.</a>
Scheduled: Alternate years.

<A NAME="c130"></A>
<h3>130 Vocabulary Building and Scientific Terminology    3 Hours</h3>
A study of Greek and Latin roots, prefixes and suffixes, together with English
words derived from them. Practice in analyzing words and discussion of the
principles of deriving scientific and medical terms.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: LNO.</a>
Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
<A NAME="c210"></A>
<h3>210 Archaeology of the Ancient World   3 Hours</h3>
(XL: Art 210) A study of the monuments and other material remains that illustrate
 the historical development of Greece and Rome. Some attention will be paid to the 
topography of Athens and Rome and of other selected sites. Guest lecturers, 
such as those of the Archaeological Institute of America, may present information
in related areas, e.g. on the Egyptians, Phoenicians, etc. Some major archaeologists
will be discussed for their contributions.Non- studio. PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: ALNOS. </a>
Scheduled: Alternate years.
<A NAME="c221"></A>
<h3>221 Greek and Roman Epic in Translation     3 Hours</h3>
A study of the Iliad, the Odyssey, and the Aeneid with possible references to related 
literature. PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: LNO.</a> Scheduled: Alternate years.

<A NAME="c313"></A>
<h3>313 History of Ancient Greece     4 Hours</h3>
(XL: Hist 313) Survey of Hellenic and Hellenistic development from early beginnings
to the Roman conquest. Special attention devoted to ancient Greek historians and
their interpretations of history. Applied to a major in classics or history. PRQ: Hist 101 or 
Clas 123 or consent of instructor. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: LNOS. </a>Scheduled: Alternate years.
<A NAME="c314"></A>
<h3>314 History of Ancient Rome  4 Hours</h3>
(XL: Hist 314) A study of the rise of Rome and its maturity with stress on the political and 
constitutional developments, social and political revolutions, and the conquest of the 
Mediterranean. Study also of the Augustan age, the Pax Romana, and the decline of the 
western Roman Empire. PRQ: Hist 101 or Clas 124 or consent of instructor.
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNOS.</a> Scheduled: Alternate years.
<A NAME="c315"></A>
<h3>315 Roman Britain: An Archaeological & Historical Survey   4 Hours</h3>
(XL: History 315) Offered at Regent's College only.
<A NAME="c322"></A>
<h3>322 Greek & Roman Literature in Translation: Drama & Lyric Poetry    3 Hours</h3>
Classical tragedy (selected plays by Aeschylus, Sophocles, and Euripides), Old Comedy 
(selected works of Aristophanes), and New Comedy (selected plays of Menander and/or
his successors in Roman literature--Plautus and Terence) as well as selections from noted
Greek and Roman lyric poets. PRQ: A  Classics course, 200-level English course,
or consent of instructor. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: LNO.</a> Scheduled: Alternate years.
<A NAME="c495"></A>
<h3>495 Senior Seminar 3 Hours</h3>
PRQ: Senior standing and consent of department chair. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="greek"></A>
<HR>
<h3>Greek courses (Also see Classics and Latin courses)</h3>
<HR>

Students should see the instructor if their class schedule conflicts with the stated meeting 
time of any course listed below.

<A NAME="g101"></A>
<h3>101 Elementary Greek I  3 Hours</h3>
Grammar and reading of simple selections from Greek writers, as well as practice in
pronunciation. PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: FLNO. </a>Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="g102"></A>
<h3>102 Elementary Greek II 3 Hours</h3>
Grammar and reading of simple selections from Greek writers, as well as practice in
pronunciation. PRQ: Gk 101. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: FLNO.</a> Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="g111"></A>
<h3>111 Elementary New Testament Greek I   3 Hours</h3>
<A NAME="g112"></A>
<h3>112 Elementary New Testament Greek II  3 Hours</h3>
Grammar and reading of simple selections based on New Testament literature, as well as
practice in pronunciation and composition of simple sentences. Preparation will be made 
for those desiring to continue with Greek 203, 204. Fulfills part of the foreign
language requirement.To be offered instead of Greek 101, 102 periodically, 
when beginning Greek is offered.

<A NAME="g203"></A>
<h3>203 Intermediate Greek Prose: Plato    3 Hours</h3>
Allows completion of necessary grammar and reading of selections from Apology of Plato
or similar literature. PRQ:  Greek 101 & 102 or consent of instructor. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: FLNO. </a>
Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="g204"></A>
<h3>204 Intermediate Greek Poetry: Iliad or Odyssey  3 Hours</h3>
Selections from Homer's Iliad or Odyssey. PRQ: Gk 203 or consent of instructor. 
 <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: FLNO.</a>
 Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="g495"></A>
<h3>495 Senior Seminar 3 Hours</h3>
PRQ: Senior standing or permission of department chair.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="latin"></A>
<HR>
<h3>Latin courses  (Also see Classics and Greek courses)</h3>
<HR>

Students should see the instructor if their class schedule conflicts with the stated meeting
time of any class listed below.

<A NAME="l101"></A>
<h3>101 Elementary Latin I  3 Hours</h3>
PRQ: None. Meets: FLNO. Scheduled: Yearly.

<A NAME="l102"></A>
<h3>102 Elementary Latin II 3 Hours</h3>
Essentials of grammar, reading of simple selections form Latin literature, and practice in
pronunciation. PRQ: Lat 101.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: FLNO. </a>Scheduled: Yearly.

<A NAME="l203"></A>
<h3>203 Intermediate Latin I     3 Hours</h3>
Reading of selections form Latin prose, authors such as Cicero and Pliny. PRQ: Lat 102.
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: FLNO.</a>
Scheduled: Yearly.

<A NAME="l204"></A>
<h3>204 Intermediate Latin II    3 Hours</h3>
Selections from Vergil's Aeneid. PRQ: Lat 203. Meets:  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">FLNO.</a> Scheduled: Yearly.
<A NAME="l303"></A>
<h3>303 Introduction to Roman Comedy  3 Hours</h3>
Reading of The Menaechmi or another play of Plautus, part of a play of Terence such as 
The Adelphoe, and discussion of Roman drama. PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a>
Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="l304"></A>
<h3>304 Latin Lyric Poetry  3 Hours</h3>
Selections from Catullus and from Horace's Odes and Epodes; their relation to Greek
literature and their influence on modern literature. PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent. 
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a>
Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="l307"></A>
<h3>307 Survey of Latin Literature    3 Hours</h3>
The literature of the republic and the early empire, with special attention to historical and
philosophical writing. PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a> Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="l310"></A>
<h3>310 Silver Latin: Pliny and Martial    3 Hours</h3>
The social life of Rome at the close of the first century as revealed in the letters of Pliny
and the Epigrams of Martial. PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a>
Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="l313"></A>
<h3>313 Roman Satire   3 Hours</h3>
The development of Roman satire as a literary form; the Satires and Epistles of Horace,
Juvenal. PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a> Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="l320"></A>
<h3>320 Latin Composition and Sight Reading     3 Hours</h3>
A thorough review of Latin grammar and sentence structure as well as an introduction to the
composition of Latin paragraphs. Practice in techniques for reading Latin prose at sight.
PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: LNO. </a>Scheduled: On request. 

<A NAME="l333"></A>
<h3>333 The Age of Cicero   3 Hours</h3>
The letters of Cicero and other literature of the period form a basis for this course. 
PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a> Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="l336"></A>
<h3>336 Advanced Vergil     3 Hours</h3>
The less frequently read works of Vergil, including Aeneid 6, 7-12 and/or the Eclogues and
Georgics. Choice of selections will depend on students' previous background in Vergil.
PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO.</a> Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="l338"></A>
<h3>338 Ovid 3 Hours</h3>
The Metamorphoses: Ovid's technique in variation and his influence on later literature and 
art. PRQ: Lat 204 or equivalent.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: LNO. </a>Scheduled: On request.

<A NAME="l495"></A>
<h3>495 Senior Seminar 3 Hours</h3>
PRQ: Senior standing or permission of department chair.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: On request. 

</pre>
<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</a> </p>

