<html>

<head>
<title>Economics Detailed Course Descriptions</title>
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Departments of Economics</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Detailed Course Descriptions</h2>
<hr>

<a name="101"></a><h3>101  Principles of Microeconomics 4</h3>
<p>Production and distribution within the American economy. Topics include the effects of
different market structures on product price and output; determinants of demand for labor
and other resources; history of government regulation; labor history and collective
bargaining; economic determinants of income distribution; international trade; pollution;
poverty; and farm subsidies. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, spring, and summer,
yearly. </a></p>

<a name="102"></a><h3>102  Principles of Macroeconomics 4</h3>
<p>The aggregate level of economic activity in the American economy and determinants of the
national income, employment, and price levels. Topics include fiscal policy, money and
banking, wage-price controls, the Marxian critique of capitalism, limits to growth and
equality, poverty and economic justice.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring and
summer, yearly.</a> </p>

<a name="201"></a><h3>201 Current Microeconomic Issues  2</h3>
<p>Current microeconomic issues in the U.S., including market competition, government
regulation, income distribution, declining productivity, and environmental and consumer
protection.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.
</a> </p>

<a name="202"></a><h3>202 Current Macroeconomic Issues  2</h3>
<p>Current Macroeconomic issues in the U.S., including unemployment, inflation, recession,
public debt, military budget, welfare and social programs, and trade restrictions.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ
102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request. </a> </p>

<a name="203"></a><h3>203 Price Theory   4</h3>
<p>Theories of consumer behavior, of the firm under conditions of competition and monopoly,
allocation of productive resources, and product distribution in a system regulated by
prices and markets.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall and summer, yearly. </a></p>

<a name="208"></a><h3>208 National Income and employment Theory   4</h3>
<p>An examination of aggregate economic behavior; the determinants of national income,
output, employment, consumption, and investment behavior, and the impact of fiscal policy
on aggregate expenditure are the principal topics.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled:
Spring, Yearly.</a> </p>

<a name="280"></a><h3>280 Applied Quantitative Methods for the Social Sciences   4</h3>
<p>Quantitative techniques to conduct and understand social science research. Topics
include mathematics, statistics and other relevant subjects, with special emphasis on
understanding which techniques and tools are appropriate in different situations;
relatively little emphasis will be placed on calculating statistics. You are expected to
master at least one specialized computer program during the semester.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: High school
algebra and sophomore standing. Scheduled: On request.</a></p>

<a name="305"></a><h3>305 Public Policy Analysis   4</h3>
<p>The merit and efficiency of certain governmental programs require renewed examination.
This course attempts to improve our abilities to understand social problems, to identify
policy choices. Specific public policies will be examined as illustrations of general
problems of policy analysis.
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101 or 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.
</a> </p>

<a name="309"></a><h3>309 Public Finance 4</h3>
<p>The role of the public sector and its budget; theories of taxation ]; social goals and fiscal
institutions; the national debt and the impact of fiscal policy on our economy are the
principal topics.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101 or 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</a> </p>

<a name="310"></a><h3>310 Seminar in Policy Analysis    4</h3>
<p>Examines a limited number of topics in some detail, including theoretical and methodological
development in policy issues. You will have an opportunity to pursue research in the field.
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101 or 102, and 305. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</a> </p>

<a name="317"></a><h3>317 Money and Banking   4</h3>
<p>The structure of commercial banking and the Federal Reserve System. Money as a medium
of exchange the quantity theory; money as an asset liquidity preference; theory of
interest and capital markets are the principal topics considered.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101 and 102.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a> </p>

<a name="320"></a><h3>320 International Economics  4</h3>
<p>Introduction to essential economic principles of international economic relationships,
including theoretical and institutional aspects of international trade; effects of trade;
and factor movements on economic welfare; balance of payments; problems of international
disequilibrium; barriers to trade; and the search for economic stability and growth through
international cooperation.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</a> </p>

<a name="321"></a><h3>321 History of Economic Thought   4</h3>
<p>Development of economic thought from the Greek philosophers to the present. Focus will
be on the economic ideas of the mercantilists, classical economists, Karl Marx, neo-
classical economists, Austrian school, John M. Keynes and Milton Friedman.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</a> </p>

<a name="326"></a><h3>326 Alternative Economic Systems  4</h3>
<p>Theoretical and historical developmental patterns of market economics, market socialism,
and centrally planned socialism, with special analysis of leading proponents and opponents
of each system. Some contemporary economies such as China, Soviet Union, Japan, India, and
the United Kingdom are included.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years. </a></p>

<a name="327"></a><h3>327 Economic Growth and Development    4</h3></a>
<p>Economic conditions in developing countries, with a thorough analysis of different
theories of economic growth and development as well as issues and problems of
development, such as income distribution, population growth, health and education,
intersectional resource allocations, and sociopolitical institutions. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101. Meets:
SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years. </a></p>

<a name="329"></a><h3>329 European and the United States Economic History   4</h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 329) European economic development from ancient times, with special emphasis on
those institutions which are associated with United States economic development. United
States economic development is the major emphasis.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101. Meets: SNO. Scheduled:
On request.</a> </p>

<a name="330"></a><h3>330 The European Economic Community    4</h3>
<p>Offered only at Regent's College.
</p>

<a name="335"></a><h3>335 Introduction to Mathematics Economics   4</h3>
<p>Microeconomics and Macroeconomics concepts in a mathematical setting. Basic application
of mathematical concepts to marginal analysis, equilibrium, and optimization. Application
to matrix theory to input-output analysis and the solution of economic equilibrium. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:
Econ 101 and 203. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</a> </p>

<a name="336"></a><h3>336 Econometrics   4</h3>
<p>This course is an introduction to econometric theory. It includes parameter estimation and
simple and multiple equation economic models as well as inferences and hypothesis testing.
Special attention is given to the development of econometric models to be used in economic
forecasting. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101, Econ 203 and Math 224. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</a> </p>

<a name="361"></a><h3>361 Government and Business  4</h3>
<p>D(XL: BA 361) The growth of government influence in the economic sector from both
theoretical and historical viewpoints. Particular emphasis is placed on antitrust activity,
government regulatory agencies, government prohibition of activities, and government
regulatory agencies, government prohibition of activities, and government run economic
enterprises.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</a></p>

<a name="365"></a><h3>365 Managerial Economics and Operations Research 4</h3>
<p(XL: BA 365) Exposition of theoretical and analytical tools of economics which are useful
in managerial decision-making and illustrating applications of managerial concepts.
Different market structures and various government policies also are examined to
evaluate the scope of their influence on business decisions. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Econ 101 and 203. Meets:
NO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a></p>

<a name="398-1"></a><h3>398-1 Internship: Economics  1</h3>

<a name="398-2"></a><h3>398-2 Internship: Economics  2</h3>

<a name="398-3"></a><h3>398-3 Internship: Economics  3</h3>

<a name="398-4"></a><h3>398-4 Internship: Economics  4</h3>
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Junior standing. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a> </p>

<a name="399-1"></a><h3>399-1 Internship: Economics  1</h3>

<a name="399-2"></a><h3>399-2 Internship: Economics  2</h3>

<a name="399-3"></a><h3>399-3 Internship: Economics  3</h3>

<a name="399-4"></a><h3>399-4 Internship: Economics  4</h3>
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Junior standing. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
</a> 

<a name="418"></a><h3>418 Financial Economics 4</h3>
<p>Integrates the fundamental tools of finance, investments and economics to allow you to
apply these concepts to theoretical and real world situations through the case method.
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Acct 223, BA 318, BA 319, Econ 208. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</a> </p>

<a name="495"></a><h3>495 Senior Seminar 4</h3>
<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Senior standing, Econ 203 and 208. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</a> 

