<HEAD>

<TITLE>English Detailed Course Descriptions</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College<BR>
Department of English</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>
<A NAME="098"></A>
<H3>98 Basic Writing for ESL Students     3</H3> 
<P>A bridge course for non-native speakers who are not yet ready
for Eng 110. Although this course does not count toward hours
required for graduation, it is counted when considering
students' semester course loads.  This course does not meet the
Freshman English requirement. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Placement. Classified: X.
 Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="110"></A>
<H3>110 Fundamentals of Writing     3</H3> 
<P>Intensive grammar and composition work.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Meets: E.
Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="111"></A>
<H3>111 Expository Writing and Rhetoric     3</H3>
<P>Writing skills essential for a well-educated person and for
success in  academic and professional life.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 110 or placement.
Meets: E. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="112"></A>
<H3>112 Expository Writing and Literature     3</H3>
<P>An introduction to literature combined with expository
writing and the research paper.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 111 or equivalent.
Meets: E. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="201"></A>
<H3>201 Survey of English Literature I     3</H3>
<P>A survey of major works and authors from the Old English
period to the Restoration (c. 750-1660); includes special
consideration of the historical development of the English
language.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or
equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="202"></A>
<H3>202 Survey of English Literature II     3</H3>
<P>A survey of representative works and authors from the
Restoration to the twentieth century.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meet: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="210"></A>
<H3>210 Survey of American Literature     3</H3>
<P>A survey of American literature from the Colonial period to
the present.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112
or equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="252"></A>
<H3>252 Fiction Writing     4</H3>
<P>Theory and practice in writing prose fiction. .<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meet: NO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="253"></A>
<H3>253 Poetry Writing     4</H3>
Theory and practice in writing poetry.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: NO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="256"></A>
<H3>256 Journalism     4</H3>
<P>(XL: Comm 256) Writing skills necessary in journalism.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: UNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="260"></A>
<H3>260 Practical Criticism     2</H3>
<P>Introduction to theories and methods of literary criticism,
providing a basic vocabulary of critical terms and practice in
writing analyses of works of literature.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: NOU.  Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="300"></A>
<H3>300 Middle English Literature     4</H3>
<P>Introduction to the narrative literature, lyric poetry, and
drama of the Middle English period (c. 1150 to c. 1500). <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="302"></A>
<H3>302 Chaucer     4</H3>
<P>The dream visions, the Troilus and Criseyde, and the
Canterbury Tales.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng
112 or equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A>

<A NAME="310"></A>	
<H3>310 Sixteenth-century Poetry and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Non-dramatic literature from 1485 to 1600; special emphasis
on the works of More, Sidney, and Spenser, and Shakespeare's
poems. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or
equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="312"></A>
<H3>312 Shakespeare: Comedies and Romances     4</H3>
<P>Textual and critical study of Shakespeare's major comedies
and romances.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112
or equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="313"></A>
<H3>313 Shakespeare: Tragedies and History Plays     4</H3>
<P>Textual and critical study of Shakespeare's major tragedies
and history plays.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng
112 or equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="315"></A>
<H3>315 Seventeenth-century British Poetry and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Major writers, especially Donne, Jonson, Jacobean dramatists,
and Milton.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or
equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A>

<A NAME="320"></A>
<H3>320 Restoration/Eighteenth-century British Poetry and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Dryden, Swift, Pope, Johnson, Boswell, Goldsmith, Burke, and
selected dramatists.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ:
Eng 112 or equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, even
years.</A>

<A NAME="322"></A>
<H3>322 Eighteenth-century British Novel     4</H3>
<P>Selected novels by Defoe, Richardson, Austen, Smollett,
Goldsmith, Fielding, Sterne, and others.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A>

<A NAME="330"></A>
<H3>330 Nineteenth-century British Poetry and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Romantic and Victorian poetry and prose;  Wordsworth,
Coleridge, Keats, Shelley, Byron, Tennyson, Browning, Arnold,
and others.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or
equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="332"></A>
<H3>332 Nineteenth-century British Novel     4</H3>
<P>Selected novels of the Brontes, Dickens, Thackeray, Eliot,
Hardy, Conrad, Kipling, and others.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A>

<A NAME="335"></A>
<H3>335 Modern British Poetry and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Selected works of Joyce, Conrad, Woolf, Eliot, Yeats,
Lawrence, Orwell, Golding, Greene, Waugh and others.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Every third year.</A>

<A NAME="337"></A>
<H3>337 Modern Drama     4</H3>
<P>Drama on the Continent and in Britain and America from Ibsen
to the present.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng
112 or equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Every third year.</A>

<A NAME="338"></A>
<H3>338 World Literature     4</H3>
<P>Selected works by Western and non-Western writers.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Every third year.</A>

<A NAME="340"></A>
<H3>340 Nineteenth-Century American Poetry  and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Selected works by Emerson, Hawthorne, Poe, Thoreau, Whitman,
Dickinson, Melville, Twain, James, and others.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="341"></A>
<H3>341 Modern American Poetry and Prose     4</H3>
<P>Selected works by Fitzgerald, Hemingway, Faulkner, Pound,
Bellow, Eliot, Frost, Stevens, Cummings, and others.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A>

<A NAME="347"></A>
<H3>347 Contemporary Literature     4</H3>
<P>Selected works of Percy, Updike, Drabble, Naylor, Erdrich,
Nemerov, Wilbur, Plath, Atwood, and others.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="350"></A>
<H3>350 Advanced Expository Writing     4</H3>
<P>(XL: Comm 350) Techniques of analysis, description and
persuasion common to all good expository prose; includes a
review of English grammar and mechanics.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: NOU. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="352"></A>
<H3>352 Advanced Creative Writing     4</H3>
<P>Continuation of Eng 252.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">
PRQ: Eng 252 or equivalent. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>
<A NAME="357"></A>

<H3>357 Business Communication     4</H3>
<P>(XL: Comm 357) Theory and practice in writing letters, memos,
and reports; oral communication skills most useful to students
intending to pursue careers in business; includes a review of
English grammar and mechanics.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: NOU. Scheduled: Fall and spring yearly.</A>

<A NAME="358"></A>
<H3>358 Scientific and Technical Communication     4</H3>
<P>(XL: Comm 358) Theory and practice in writing skills
appropriate in science and technology; includes a review of
English grammar and mechanics as well as a review of oral
communication skills.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ:
Eng 112 or equivalent. Meets: NOU. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="359"></A>
<H3>359 Rhetorical Theory and Practice     4</H3>
<P>Study of rhetorical theory and practice. Includes and
overview of rhetoric from Aristotle to the present and a review
of grammar and mechanics. Students will learn how to design a
writing course.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng
112 or equivalent. Meets: NOU. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="360"></A>
<H3>360 Aesthetic Theory and Literary Criticism     4</H3>
<P>From Plato and Aristotle to the present, with special
emphasis on British and modern American traditions of
criticism.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 112 or
equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="361"></A>
<H3>361 Innovations in Grammar     4</H3>
<P>(XL: Educ 361) Transformational and structural grammar in the
context of traditional grammar.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Scheduled: Summer.</A>

<A NAME="374"></A>
<H3>374 Women in Literature: Selected Authors     4</H3>
<P>Major women writers of the nineteenth and twentieth
centuries: Jane Austen, the Bronte sisters, George Eliot,
Virginia Woolf, Doris Lessing, Eudora Welty, Flannery O'Connor,
Alice Walker, and others.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">
PRQ: Eng 112 or  equivalent. Meets: LNO. Scheduled: On
request.</A>

<A NAME="379"></A>
<H3>379 Selected Topics in British or American Literature      2-4</H3>
<P>Study of mode, genre, theme, and structure.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent.
Meets: LNO. Scheduled: Occasionally.  May be repeated.</A>

<A NAME="398"></A>
<H3>398 Academic Internship: English     2-4</H3>
<P><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 350 and one
other four-hour writing course. Minimum GPA 2.5 overall; 3.0 GPA
in English.Meets: NO.  Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="399"></A>
<H3>399 Academic Internship: English     2-4</H3>
<P><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Eng 350 plus one
other four-hour writing course. Minimum GPA 2.5 overall; 3.0 GPA
in English.  Meets: NO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="495"></A>
<H3>495 Senior Seminar     4</H3>
<P><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Senior
standing. Meets: N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly. </A>

<HR>
<A HREF ="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
