<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>History Detailed Course Descriptions</TITLE>

<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>

<H1>Rockford College<BR>

 Department of History</H1>

</CENTER>

<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>

<HR> 

<A NAME="101"></A>

<H3>101 Western Civilization I: Sumerians through 13th
Century	4</H3> 

<P>A survey of major formative elements of western civilization.
The first half emphasizes the Hebrews, Greeks, and Romans; the
origins of Christianity; the disintegration of antiquity; and
the generation of modern western civilization after the ninth
century. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets:
SNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly. </A>



<A NAME="102"></A>

<H3>102 Western Civilization II - 1200 through 1750	4</H3> 

<P>An introductory investigation into the major intellectual and
social developments of the western world in the early modern
period, with special emphasis on the making and expansion of
European institutions and culture.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None.  Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>



<A NAME="103"></A>

<H3>103 Western Civilization III - 1750 to Present		4</H3>

<P>The general political structure of modern Europe is examined
against a background of revolutionary movements, cultural and
intellectual developments and social change. The French
Revolution, German unification, the Russian Revolutions, and the
rise of Naziism will be among topics considered.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>



<A NAME="111"></A>

<H3>111 Western Civilization: The Ancient World to 1500	4</H3>

<P>To be offered only at Regent's College.



<A NAME="112"></A>

<H3>112 Western Civilization from 1500 to Present	4</H3>

<P>To be offered only at Regent's College.



<A NAME="205"></A>

<H3>205 American Lives	2</H3>

<P>A biographical approach to American History which considers
the lives and careers of representative Americans from the
Colonial beginnings to the present day.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: SNO. Scheduled:
Alternate years.</A>



<A NAME="210"></A>

<H3>210 History of England Since the Conquest	4</H3>

<P>British civilization from a historical and developmental
perspective. Among the topics that students will be expected to
study are the Norman Conquest, the origin and evolution of the
English Parliamentary  Monarchy, the English Reformation, the
Elizabethan Age, the Industrial Revolution, Imperialism, and the
creation of the English welfare state. An important, though not
exclusive, function of the course will be to prepare students
for life and study at Regent's College. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Alternate years.</A>



<A NAME="300"></A>

<H3>300 The Civilization of London 4</H3>

<P>To be offered only at Regent's College. 



<A NAME="301"></A>

<H3>301 Christianity in Britain	3</H3>

<P>(XL: Rel 301) To be offered only at Regent's College.

<A NAME="302"></A>

<H3>302 Christianity in Britain: Reformation to Modern
Times	3</H3>

<P>(XL: Rel 302) To be offered only at Regent's College.



<A NAME="303"></A>

<H3>303 U.S. History to 1789	4</H3>

<P>Colonial America from the European exploration to the
ratification of the Constitution.  The stress will be placed on
the British colonies in the North America.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Sophomore standing.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Three-semester cycle.</A>

 

<A NAME="304"></A>

<H3>304 U.S. History 1789-1865	4</H3>

<P>The Revolution through the Civil War. Topics include
federalism, Jeffersonian and Jacksonian democracy, the westward
expansion, sectionalism, and slavery.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Sophomore standing.
Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Three-semester cycle.</A>



<A NAME="311"></A>

<H3>311 Medieval History	4</H3>

<P>A consideration of the political, social and intellectual
reorganization of Europe following the fall of the Roman
Empire.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Hist 101 or
102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="312"></A>

<H3>312 Renaissance and Reformation	4</H3>

<P>An analysis of the religious, intellectual and political
turmoil in western Europe between 1350 and 1650, emphasizing the
Renaissance, Christian revival, and formation of the modern
state.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Hist 101 or
102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="313"></A>

<H3>313 History of Ancient Greece	4</H3>

<P>(XL: Classics 313) Survey of Hellenic and Hellenistic
development from early beginnings to the Roman conquest. Special
attention to ancient Greek historians and their interpretations
of history. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Hist 101
or Clas 123 or consent of instructor. Meets: LSNO. Scheduled:
Alternate years.</A>



<A NAME="314"></A>

<H3>314 History of Ancient Rome	4</H3>

<P>(XL: Classics 314) A study of the rise of Rome and its
maturity, with stress on political and constitutional
developments, social and political revolution, and the conquest
of the Mediterranean. Study also of the Augustan age, the Pax
Romana, and the decline of the western Roman Empire. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Hist 101 or Clas 124 or
consent of instructor. Meets LSNO. Scheduled: Alternate
years.</A>



<A NAME="315"></A>

<H3>315 Roman Britain:  An Archaeological & Historical
Survey	4</H3>

<P>(XL: Classics 315) To be offered only at Regent's College.



<A NAME="321"></A>

<H3>321 Classical Political Philosophy	4</H3>

<P>(XL: PS 321) Deals with Plato, Aristotle and the classical
tradition of political philosophy through the Middle Ages.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: PS 101 or consent of
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="322"></A>

<H3>322 Modern Political Philosophy	4</H3>

<P>(XL: PS 322) Treats some of the principal political texts
since the Middle Ages.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">
PRQ: PS 101 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On
request.</A>



<A NAME="323"></A>

<H3>323 American Political Thought	4</H3>

<P>(XL: PS 323) An examination of American political ideas from
the seventeenth century to the present.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102 or Hist 303 or
304 or 305. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="324"></A>

<H3>324 Tudor-Stuart England	4</H3>

<P>Deals predominantly with the political history of the period:
 social and intellectual history, along with some
historiography, also will be considered. The English Reformation
and the English Civil War will be areas of special concern.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Meets: SNO.
Scheduled: Alternate years.</A>



<A NAME="350"></A>

<H3>350 American Historiography	4</H3>

<P>A survey of American mainstream historical writing from
colonial times to the present, with some attention to
contemporary problems in the philosophy of history..<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Hist 303, 304, or 305,
and consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="355"></A>

<H3>355 Ideas and Institutions of the Modern World	4</H3>

<P>The great social and political ideas of the modern era and
their impact on the contemporary world. Topics may include
liberalism, romanticism, socialism, Darwinism, positivism and/or
imperialism. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent
of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="356"></A>

<H3>356 Modern Russia	4</H3>

<P>Internal policies, foreign policies and intellectual
developments in Russia from the early 19th through the mid-20th
century. Possible topics include the reforms of Alexander II,
the Russian peasantry, the emergency of Russian radicalism, the
revolutions of 1905 and 1917, Stalinism, and post-Stalin Russia.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 3 hours in history or
consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Alternate
years.</A>



<A NAME="361"></A>

<H3>361 Modern Germany	4</H3>

<P>This course integrates selected aspects of the political,
social, cultural, and intellectual history of modern German. The
period from 1815 to 1945 will be the primary concern. Topics
include the impact of the French Revolution and Napoleon on
Germany, Hegelianism and Marxism, Bismarck and German
unification, foreign policy in Wilhelminian Germany, the Weimar
Republic and the rise of Naziism, and post-Nazi Germany.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: 3 hours in history or
consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Alternate
years.</A>



<A NAME="362"></A>

<H3>362 Modern France	4</H3>

<P>The political history of France from the mid-18th century to
the early 20th century is the primary focus. Major topics
include the French Revolution of 1789, the Napoleonic era, and
the 19th century revolutionary movements. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 3 hours in history or
consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="363"></A>

<H3>363 Middle East in Modern Times	4</H3>

<P>An historical investigation of the roots of the 20th century
Middle East crisis. Topics include the Balfour Declaration,
League of Nations Mandate, Zionism, emergence of modern Arab
states, and modern Israel. <A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: At least 8 hours in
history. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>



<A NAME="384"></A>

<H3>384 Statesmanship	4</H3>

<P>(XL: PS 384) Consideration of political issues as revealed in
the careers and writings of such practical practitioners as
Cicero, the American founders, Lincoln, Churchill and
DeGaulle.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: PS 101 or
102 or Hist 103 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled:
On request.</A>



<A NAME="385"></A>

<H3>385 History and Politics of the Cold War	4</H3>

<P>(XL: PS 385) An examination of the origins and the successive
phases of the Cold War, including its end following the
dissolution of Soviet Hegemony in East Europe in 1989 and the
unification of Germany in 1990. Based on the general overview of
the U.S. Soviet and East-West relations, the course will include
discussion of NATO and the Warsaw Pact. American and Soviet
strategic doctrines, arms control negotiations, and the
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe.<A
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: PS 282 or consent of
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</A>





<A NAME="495"></A>

<H3>495 Senior Seminar	4</H3>

<P><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Senior standing.
Meets: N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>



<A NAME="498"></A>

<H3>498 History Internship	2-8</H3>



<A NAME="499"></A>

<H3>499 History Internship	2-8</H3>

<P><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent of
department chair. Meets: NO. Scheduled: As needed.</A>

</PRE>

