<html>
<head>
<title>Course Offerings and Descriptions</title>
</head>

<center><H2>Course offerings and descriptions </H2></center><p>
<BODY>

<p>

</A><A NAME="101"><H3>101 Fundamental Concepts of Mathematics           4 </A></H3> <p>
The nature of mathematics, its cultural significance and role in the humanities, arts, and science. Topics are chosen
from number theory, geometry, algebra, logic and the history of mathematics. Meets the prerequisite for statistics
courses. Note: Only one of Math 101 or 117 may be used to satisfy the science and math all-college requirements.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 1 year HS algebra and 1 year HS geometry. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M. Does not meet: N. Scheduled: Spring,
yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="106"><H3>106 Algebra Skills I        1 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include positive and negative numbers, exponents, basic operations with polynomials, factoring, fractions,
radicals and fractional exponents.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: 1 year HS algebra, 1 year HS geometry, pre-test and consent. Classified: 1Y.
Meets: MO. Does not meet: N. Scheduled: Every semester.</A><p>
<A NAME="107"><H3>107 Algebra Skills II            1</A></H3>  <p>
Topics include solving equations and inequalities (involving squares, roots, fractions), and systems of equations. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:
1 year HS algebra, 1 year HS geometry, pre-test and consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MO. Does not meet: N.
Scheduled: Every semester.<p>

<A NAME="108"></A><H3>108 Functions and Graphs         1 </H3> <p>
Topics include graphs of algebraic equations, symmetry, translations, functions, lines, distance formula, parallel and
perpendicular lines.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 107 or equivalent, pre-test and consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MO. Does not meet:
N. Scheduled: Every semester.</A><p>

<A NAME="109"><H3>109 Trigonometry            1 </A> </H3><p>
Topics include trig functions via unit circle and right triangles, identities, graphs, sum and difference formulas.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ:
Math 108 or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MO. Does not meet: N. Scheduled: Every semester.</A><p>

<A NAME="110"><H3>110 Probability and Finite Math            1 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include permutations, combinations, counting techniques, simple probability, mathematical induction. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:
Math 111 or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MO. Does not meet: N. Scheduled: On request.</A><p>

<A NAME="111"><H3>111 Sets and Logic          1 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include sets, Venn diagrams, operations (complement, union, intersection, differences), truth tables
(conjunctions, disjunctions, negation, implications).<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 107 or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MO. Does
not meet: N. Scheduled: On request.</A><p>

<A NAME="117"><H3>117 Math for Elementary Teachers           4</A> </H3> <p>
For students planning to teach in elementary school. It examines in depth such topics as set theory, structural
development of the real number system, informal geometry and measurement. Note: only one of Math 101 or 117 may
be used to satisfy the science and math all-college requirements. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 1 year HS algebra, 1 year HS geometry and
consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M. Does not meet: NO. Scheduled: Fall and summer, yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="129"><H3>129   Discrete Mathematics            3 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include set theory, symbolic logic, mathematical induction, counting techniques, matrix theory, graph theory,
relations and functions.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 106, 107, or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall,
yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="130"><H3>130 Calculus with Analytic Geometry I           4 </A></H3> <p>
Introductory analytic geometry, functions and limits, continuity, differentiation of algebraic functions, applications of
derivatives, antiderivatives, and the definite integral. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 108, 109 or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Spring and summer, yearly.</A><p>

</A><A NAME="223"><H3>223 Beginning Statistics         3 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include measures of central tendency and variability, grouped data and graphical presentations, the normal
distribution, sampling, decision making, t- and chi-square distribution and correlation. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 3 semesters of HS algebra
or Math 101 or 107. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M. Scheduled: Fall, spring, and summer, yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="224"><H3>224 Elements of Statistics            4 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include measures of central tendency and variability, grouped data and graphical presentation, the normal
distribution, sampling, decision making, t- and f-tests, correlation and regression, and chi square and other
nonparametric methods.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: 3 semesters of HS algebra or Math 101 or 107. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MN. Does not
meet: NO. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="231"><H3>231 Calculus with Analytic Geometry II          4 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include the definite integral and applications, differentiation and integration of transcendental functions,
techniques of integration, conic sections, polar coordinates, indeterminate forms and improper integrals. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math
130 or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.  Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="232"><H3>232 Calculus with Analytic Geometry III         4 </A> </H3><p>
Topics include infinite series, solid analytic geometry, vectors in two and three dimensions, partial differentiation,
directional derivatives, line integrals, multiple integration and applications, cylindrical and spherical coordinates, and
Green's theorem.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 231. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A><p>

</A><A NAME="300"><H3>300 Introductory Linear Algebra            4 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include finite dimensional vector spaces, linear transformations and associated matrices, determinants, systems
of equations, and applications. PRQ: Math 231. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="301"><H3>301 Problem Solving Seminar            2 </A> </H3><p>
Many problems are considered, with attention to the problem-solving process. Students will take part in the Putnam
competition. (May be repeated for credit.)<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Invitation. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall,
yearly.</A><p>

<A NAME="305"><H3>305 Mathematical Modeling      3 </A></H3> <p>
(XL: CS 305) This course provides a bridge between calculus and the application of mathematics to various fields.
Topics include graphing and proportionality techniques, model fitting, optimization models, experimental modelling,
and simulation. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 231 and programming experience, or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled:
On request.</A><p>

<A NAME="306"><H3>306 Differential Equations            3 </A></H3> <p>
Introduction to theory and methods of solving ordinary differential equations. Includes first order differential equations,
linear differential equations, applications, series solutions and non-linear equations.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 231. Classified: 1Y.
Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A><p>

<A NAME="310"><H3>310 Numerical Analysis           3 </A> </H3><p>
(XL: CS 310) Includes such topics as finite differences, interpolation, numerical differentiation and integration, least
squares polynomial approximation, error analysis and linear programming. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 231 and programming
experience. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A><p>

<A NAME="311"><H3>311 Symbolic Logic          3 </A></H3> <p>
(XL: Phil 311) Sentential connectives, symbolization of everyday language, quantification, general theory of inference,
theory of definition, formal and informal proof. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 107 or equivalent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: LMNO.
Scheduled: On request.</A><p>

<A NAME="314"><H3>314 Probability Models           3 </A></H3> <p>
(XL: CS 314) This course provides an introduction to mathematical probability and probability models. Topics include
a review of elementary probability axioms and theorems, the theorem of Bayes, random variables, discrete and
continuous probability distributions, expectation and the central limit theorem.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 231 and programming
experience, or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A><p>

<A NAME="315"><H3>315 Operations Research          3 </A></H3> <p>
(XL: CS 315) This course provides an introduction to the field of operations research. Topics include linear
programming, network analysis, dynamic programming, game theory, queueing theory and inventory theory. PRQ:
Math 231 and programming experience, or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: On request.</A><p>

<A NAME="320"><H3>320 Abstract Algebra        3 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include set theory; compositions of functions and permutations; basic theory of groups, rings, and fields;
polynomials.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 300. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A><p>

<A NAME="325"><H3>325 Theory of Numbers            3 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include properties of integers, Euclid's algorithm, divisibility, primes, congruences, quadratic residues and
reciprocity, number theoretic functions, Diophantine equations and Gaussian integers. Emphasis is on rigor; the
theorems of Fermat, Euler, Wilson, Lagrange and Gauss are established.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 300 or consent. Classified: 1Y.
Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A><p>

<A NAME="331"><H3>331 Introduction to Complex Analysis            3 </A></H3> <p>
Topics include analytic functions, convergence, complex differentiation and integration, Cauchy's theorem,
singularities and residues, harmonic functions, and conformal and univalent mappings. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 232. Classified:
1Y. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: On request.</A><p>

<A NAME="333"><H3>333 Advanced Calculus I: Limits and Differentiation            3 </A></H3> <p>
Course provides students with an introduction to theoretical analysis by carefully re-examining the concepts and
properties of limits and derivatives from calculus.  Construction of mathematical proofs heavily emphasized.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:Math 232 or consent of instructor.  Classified: 1Y.  Meets: MNO.  Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A><P>

<A NAME="334"><H3>334 Advanced Calculus II: Series and Integration          3 </A></H3> <p>
Course provides students with an introduction to theoretical analysis by carefully re-examining the concepts and
properties of infinite series and integration from calculus.  Construction of mathematical proofs heavily emphasized. 
HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 232 or consent of instructor.  Classified: 1Y.  Meets: MNO. </A> Scheduled: Spring, even years. </A><p>

  <A NAME="350"><H3>350 Introduction to Higher Geometry        3 </A></H3> <p>
Finite geometries, projective geometry, non-Euclidean geometry.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Math 300. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A><p>

<A NAME="400"><H3>495 Senior Seminar          4   </A></H3><p>
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Sr. math major or consent. Classified: 1. Meets: N. Does not meet: O. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A><p>

<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Rockford College Home Page </a></p>
