<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Political Science Detailed Course Descriptions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Political Science</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Detailed Course Descriptions</h2>
<hr>
<a name="101"></a><h3>101 Introduction to Political Science 4</h3>
<p>Fundamental issues of politics, as perceived by a variety of great minds. Among topics explored are 
the relations of the individual and the family to the political community, the relation between polity 
and economy, citizenship, forms of government, and doctrines of revolution. Selected ancient and 
modern texts are read.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall or spring, yearly.</a></p>
<a name="102"></a><h3>102 American Government 4</h3>
<p>The principles of the American political system as understood by the Framers; organization, 
powers, and operation of the branches of the national government; federal-state relations; political 
parties and national politics.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</a> </p>
<a name="145"></a><h3>145 Introduction to British Politics 4</h3>
<p>Offered only at Regent's College. </p>
<a name="228"></a><h3>228 Introduction to Peace and Conflict Studies 4</h3>
<p>(XL: A/S 228) The purpose of this course is to deepen our understanding of the causes and 
consequences of war, violence, and conflict and of the means of conflict resolution and 
management. The course will explore the different approaches taken by the social sciences in the 
study of conflict resolution and management. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: S; NO in Political Science. 
Scheduled: Fall, yearly. </a></p>
<a name="241"></a><h3>241 Comparative Politics 4</h3>
<p>Analyzes the main types of political regimes, governmental institutions, and political processes in a 
comparative perspective and examines the politics and governments in several Western and 
non-Western nations (e.g., Great Britain, Germany, China, Japan, one or several Latin American 
and/or African nations).<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 101 or 102 or A/S 100, 115 or 150. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: 
Fall, even years. </a></p>
<a name="282"></a><h3>282 International Relations 4</h3>
<p>Theory and practice of international relations. Elements of national power, the balance of power, 
collective security, international law, international organization, and diplomacy. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 101, 102 
or 241. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</a> </p>
<a name="310"></a><h3>310 Seminar in Policy Analysis 4</h3>
<p>(XL: Econ 310) The seminar examines a limited number of topics in some detail. Coverage will 
include theoretical and methodological development in policy issues. Seminar participants will have 
an opportunity to pursue individual research in the field. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102 or Econ 305 or consent of 
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years. </a></p>
<a name="321"></a><h3>321 Classical Political Philosophy 4</h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 321) Deals with Plato and Aristotle and with the classical tradition of political philosophy 
through the Middle Ages. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 101 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On 
request. </a></p>
<a name="322"></a><h3>322 Modern Political Philosophy 4</h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 322) Treats some of the principal political texts during the period since the 
Renaissance.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 101 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request.</a> </p>
<a name="323"></a><h3>323 American Political Thought 4 </h3>
<p>XL: Hist 323) An examination of American political ideas from the Seventeenth through the 
Twentieth Century. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PS 102 or Hist 303, 304 or 305. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request. </a></p>
<a name="325"></a><h3>325 Social Science Methods 4</h3>
<p>(XL: A/S, Hist 325) A survey course to familiarize the student with social science research 
methods, including the use of survey techniques, interviewing, participant observation and linguistic 
analysis.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly. </a></p>
<a name="333"></a><h3>333 Diplomatic History of the United States 1774-1898 4 </h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 333) Continuity and change in historical development of American diplomacy. Emphasis 
on independence, neutrality, expansion, and security: Treaty Plan of 1776; Farewell Address; 
Monroe Doctrine; Manifest Destiny, isolation and empire.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Hist 303, 304, 305 or consent of 
instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years. </a></p>
<a name="334"></a><h3>334 History of American Foreign Policy 1898-Present 4 </h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 334) America as a world power; foreign policy decision-making; American imperialism; 
dollar diplomacy; World War I; the new isolation; World War II; the cold war.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Hist 303, 
304, 305 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Alternate years. </a></p>
<a name="341"></a><h3>341 Topics in British Politics 3-4 </h3>
<p>Offered only at Regent's College. </p>
<a name="342"></a><h3>342 Politics of Russia/the Soviet Union and the CIS 4 </h3>
<p>Analysis of the origins and evolution of the Soviet political and economic system, including the 
historical foundations of Russian revolutionary radicalism and the ideology of Marxism-Leninism, the 
reforms introduced under the leadership of Mikhail Gorbachev, and the collapse of the Soviet 
regime and state in 1991. The basic outline of the systems of government and the political prospects 
of the Soviet successor states within the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), with special 
focus on the Russian Federation.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 241 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: 
On request. </a></p>
<a name="345"></a><h3>345 Topics in European Politics 3-4</h3>
<p>Issues in contemporary European politics, e.g., comparative constitutions, comparative party 
systems, European security arrangements, the politics of economic integration.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 241 or 
282, as appropriate, or consent of department chair. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request; offered 
yearly at Regent's College. </a></p>
<a name="347"></a><h3>347 Latin American Politics 4</h3>
<p>An overview of the politics of South and Central America, including discussion of common elements 
of the region's history, political culture, socio-economic conditions, and political institutions and 
processes. The course also includes a selection of case studies of individual Latin American 
countries.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 241 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNOR. Scheduled: on request. </a></p>
<a name="352"></a><h3>352 Political Anthropology 4 </h3>
<p(XL: A/S The evolution of political processes and institutions including bands, tribes, chiefdoms, and the archaic state. Special topics in contemporary non-western societies will include succession to office, conflict resolution, factions, and brokerage.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"><p>PRQ: Consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request. </p>
<a name="361"></a><h3>361 Constitutional Law: Powers of Government 4 </h3>
<p>An historical and theoretical analysis of the U.S. Supreme Court with emphasis on its relationship to 
the other branches of national government; analysis of landmark cases in judicial review, separation 
of powers, federalism and commerce.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years. </a></p>
<a name="362"></a><h3>362 Constitutional Law: Civil Liberties 4</h3>
<p>History, theory, and case law concerning First Amendment freedoms, the procedural guarantees of 
the Bill of Rights and the civil rights movement.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, even 
years. </a></p>
<a name="363"></a><h3>363 Constitutional Law: Rights of the Accused 4 </h3>
<p>Analysis of the history and principles of certain basic rights pertaining to persons accused of crimes, 
as developed in leading constitutional cases.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Spring, even 
years. </a></p>
<a name="364"></a><h3>364 Public Administration 4 </h3>
<p>Organization and management of the executive agencies of American national government, 
bureaucracy as a problem for liberal democracy, the politics of public administration and its 
relationship to other branches of government, the adequacy of administration to contemporary 
problems.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: Fall, odd years. </a></p>
<a name="365"></a><h3>365 The Presidency 4 </h3>
<p>The creation of the American presidency, its historical development, relations with the other national 
branches, comparison of the office's powers in domestic and foreign affairs, evaluation of the 
compatibility of democracy and a powerful chief executive.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: 
Fall, even years. </a></p>
<a name="366"></a><h3>366 Congress and the Legislative Process 4 </h3>
<p>Examination of the structure, operation and role of Congress with emphasis on its relation to the 
executive and judicial branches and its place within the American political system. Special attention 
will be given to the internal and external influences on Congress, which affect the formation of public 
policy.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request. </a></p>
<a name="367"></a><h3>367 Parties and Interest Groups 4 </h3>
<p>Analysis of the development, function and organization of American political parties with particular 
regard to the role of parties in a representative democracy. Examination of the role of interest 
groups and lobbies in the American political system. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 102. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On 
request. </a></p>
<a name="383"></a><h3>383 National Security Policy 4 </h3>
<p>Examines historical development of U.S. national security policy, nuclear strategy and arms control, 
limited war and NATO, U.S. military preparedness; comparison with Soviet defense strategy; role 
of foreign intelligence.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 241 or 282 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On 
request. </a></p>
<a name="384"></a><h3>384 Statesmanship 4 </h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 384) Consideration of political issues as revealed in the careers and writings of political 
practitioners such as Cicero, the American Founders, Lincoln, Churchill and DeGaulle. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 
101 or 102 or Hist 103 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request. </a></p>

<a name="385"></a><h3>385 History and Politics of the Cold War 4</h3>
<p>(XL: Hist 385) An examination of the origins and the successive phases of the Cold War, including 
its end following the dissolution of Soviet hegemony in East Europe in 1989 and the unification of 
Germany in 1990. Based on the general overview of U.S.-Soviet and East-West relations, the 
course will include discussion of NATO and the Warsaw Pact, American and Soviet strategic 
doctrines, arms control negotiations, and the Conference on Security and Cooperation in 
Europe.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: PS 282 or consent of instructor. Meets: SNO. Scheduled: On request. </a></p>
<a name="386"></a><h3>386 International Security in a Changing World 4</h3>
<p>Examines methods of preserving and restoring international stability and peace through military 
alliances, international organizations, collective security arrangements, arms control and 
disarmament, and conflict resolution and management, including select case analyses of U.N. 
peacekeeping missions.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: A/S-PS 228, PS 282 or consent of instructor. Meets: Scheduled: </a></p>
<a name="495"></a><h3>495 Senior Seminar 4</h3>
<p><a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Senior standing. Meets: N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly. </a></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</a> </p>
