<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Course Offering and Descriptions </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<center><strong><H1>Rockford College Department of Computer Science</H1></strong></center>
<BODY>
<center><strong><H2>Detail Course Descriptions </H2></strong></center>
<HR>

Course offerings and descriptions
A maximum of four hours in computer science may be used to satisfy the Science &
Mathematics Division
requirement.<P>
<A NAME="100"><P>
<H3><A NAME="100"><!anchor for CS 100>100   Basic Programming 3</A></H3><P>
For students with little or no previous programming experience. It introduces problem-solving
algorithms,  flowcharting and structured computer programming, using the language BASIC. Students will spend much of their time composing, debugging, and executing computer programs. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 106, H.S. Algebra, or consent. Classified: 1Z. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: Every fall.
<P>

<H3><A NAME="101">101  Introduction to Word Processing: WordPerfect  1</A></H3><P>
This hands-on course introduces students to word processing, the most widely used type of
microcomputer software. Students will learn to create, edit, format, store and print text using the popular word processor WordPerfect. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: None. Classified: 1Z. Meets: V. </A>Scheduled: Every semester.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="102">102   Introduction to Electronic Spreadsheets: Lotus 1-2-3 1</A></h3>
<P>This hands-on course introduces students to an electronic spreadsheet, a popular type of
personal computer software. Students will learn how to create, edit, format, store and print tables and graphs using the popular electronic spreadsheet Lotus 1-2-3.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: None. Classified: 1Z. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: Every semester.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="103">103   Introduction to Database Management: dBase IV 1   </A></h3>
<P> This course introduces students to database management. Students will learn how to
electronically create, store, update, manipulate and report data using the popular database manager dBase IV. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: None. Classified: 1Z. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="110">110   Introduction to Computer Science  3   </A></h3>
<P>This non-programming course introduces students to the field of computer science. Topics
include the evolution of the computer and the role it has played in the development of our society, a non-technical description of how computers work (hardware and software), and an introduction to personal computers, data communications systems, databases  and word-processing. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: None. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Every semester.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="150">150   Applications Program Development I  3   </A> </h3>   
<P>A beginning computer problem-solving and programming course using COBOL as the vehicle
language. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: None. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="151">151   Computing Laboratory I  1   </A></h3>
<P>A supervised hands-on laboratory experience to be taken concurrently with CS 150. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  Classified:
1Z. Meets: NO.</A> Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="252"><HR>252   Scientific Application Programming: FORTRAN 3   </A></h3>
<P>This course will help the student achieve competency in programming in FORTRAN and in using
the computer as a tool to solve problems in mathematics and science. Problem-solving, flowcharting, pseudo- code, structured programming techniques, and documentation standards will be emphasized. PRQ: Previous programming experience.  Classified: 1Z. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Fall, odd years.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="260">260   Applications Program Development II  3   </A></h3>
<P>An advanced computer problem-solving and programming course using COBOL as the vehicle language. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 150. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="261">261   Computing Laboratory II  1</A></h3>
<P>A supervised hands-on laboratory experience to be taken concurrently with CS 260. Classified:
1Z. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  Meets: NO.</A> Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="270">270   Object-Oriented Programming t 3   </A></h3>
<P>An advanced computer problem-solving and programming course using object-oriented
methodology and C++ as the vehicle language. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 150. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO. </A>Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="271">271   Computing Laboratory III  1   </A></h3>
<P>A supervised hands-on laboratory experience to be taken concurrently with CS 270. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  Classified:
1Z. Meets: NO.</A> Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="305"><HR>305   Mathematical Modelling    3   </A></h3>
<P>(XL:Math 305) This course provides a bridge between calculus and the application of
mathematics to various fields. Topics include graphing and proportionality techniques, model fitting, optimization models, experimental  modelling and simulation. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Math 231 and programming experience or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: On demand.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="310">310   Numerical Analysis  3   </A></h3>
<P>(XL: Math 310) This course may include such topics as finite differences, interpolation,
numerical differentiation and integration, least squares polynomial approximation, error analysis and linear programming. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Math 231 and programming experience. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: Spring, odd years.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="314">314   Probability Models  3   </A></h3>
<P>(XL: Math 314) An introduction to mathematical probability and probability models. Topics
include a review of elementary probability axioms and theorems, the theorem of Bayes, random variables, discrete and continuous probability distributions, expectation and the central limit theorem. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Math 231 and programming experience, or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: Fall, odd years.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="315">315   Operations Research  3   </A></h3>
<P>(XL: Math 315) An introduction to the field of operations research. Topics include linear
programming, network,analysis, dynamic programming, game theory, queuing theory and inventory theory.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Math 231 and programming experience, or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M. </A>Scheduled: On demand.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="320">320   Computer Organization 3   </A></h3>
<P>An advanced computer problem-solving and programming course using object-oriented
methodology and C++ as the vehicle language. The course also introduces students to the theory underlying the design of the fundamental hardware/software components of a computer system. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 270. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="321">321   Computing Laboratory IV  1   </A></h3>
<P>A supervised hands-on laboratory experience to be taken concurrently with CS 320. Classified:
1Z. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  Meets: NO. </A>Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="350">350   Introduction to Management Information Systems  3   </A></h3>
<P>An introduction to the needs for and uses of information systems within business organizations.
Emphasis is placed on information requirements in organizations, history, systems development, and the data
processing cycle as it encompasses hardware, software and operations. Experience with application software packages (e.g. WordPerfect and Lotus 1-2-3) will be included. Intended as an entry point to the M.I.S. curriculum, and as a literacy course for business-oriented students.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Jr./Sr. standing or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Fall, even years.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="352">352   System Analysis and Design 3   </A></h3>
<P>This course uses case studies of actual business situations as the vehicle to develop the
students understanding of MIS and related concepts as applied to business problems. Use of the microcomputer as a tool in the solution of real-world business problems will be emphasized.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 261 or consent.  Classified: 1Z.  Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled:  Spring, odd years.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="354">354   Database Management Systems 3   </A></h3>
<P>This course emphasizes the use of database methods in designing and implementing solutions
to business systems problems. Fourth generation programming techniques will be employed in application
development on both mainframe and microcomputers. Also stressed will be basic knowledge in data structures, normalization of data, data modeling and the theory of database development and utilization. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 261 or consent. Classified: 1Z. Meets: MNO.</A> Scheduled: Fall, odd years. 

<P>
<h3><A NAME="356">356   Data Communications 3   </A></h3>
<P>This course introduces the student to an environment which is undergoing rapid change through such developments as microcomputer-based workstations, digital-voice communications, local area networks,
computer load sharing, decentralized transaction processing, distributed databases, and other evolving technologies. Implications for systems design and development under conditions of distribution, autonomy, centralization and decentralization will be emphasized.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 261 or consent. Classified: 1Y.  Meets: MNO. </A> Scheduled:  Spring, even years.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="364">364   Operating Systems 3   </A></h3>
<P>An introduction to the basic concepts of operating systems. Topics may include processes, interprocess communication and synchronization, management f computer resources, deadlock problems and avoidance,
sharing and protection of processes and data, file systems and implementation. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 261 or consent. Classified: 1Y. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: On demand.
<P><h3><A NAME="365">365 Computer Graphicst 3 
</A></h3>
<P>The study of the fundamental principles of computer-controlled graphics. The student will be
expected to partially implement and use a graphics system in a high-level language (such as C++) in a variety of programs. Other topics may include segmentation of graphic files, windowing and clipping, problems of representation of three-dimensional objects, drawing of curves, shadowing and animation. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 270 or consent. Classified: 1Z. Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: On demand.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="367">367   Programming Languages  3   </A></h3>
<P>This course introduces the formal study of language specification and analysis. Emphasis is on
understanding the organization of programming languages and the run-time behavior of programs. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: CS 270 or consent. Classified: 1Z. Meets: M. </A>Scheduled: On demand.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="376">376   Special Topics in Computer Science  3   </A></h3>
<P>Current topics in the field of Computer Science are discussed. Course content will vary to meet
the needs of students and the expertise of instructors. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Consent. Classified: 1Z Meets: M.</A> Scheduled: On demand.
<P>
<h3><A NAME="398">398   Internship: Computer Science 4   </A></h3>
<P>
<h3><A NAME="399">399   Internship: Computer Science  4   </A></h3>
<P>
<A NAME="400"><HR><h3><A NAME="498">498   Internship: Computer Science  t 4   </A></h3>
<P>
<h3><A NAME="499">499   Internship: Computer Science   4   </A></h3>

<P>A practical experience in which students will have the opportunity to utilize computers in their
areas of study. Depending on the major, students will spend several hours each week in a closely supervised industrial, commercial, business or research environment. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Declared CS major or minor, and consent. Classified: 1. Meets: N. </A> Scheduled: On request. 

<P>
<h3><A NAME="495">495   Senior Seminar  6   </A></h3>
<P>This course is the culmination of students' undergraduate computer science studies. It consists
of a practicum experience (internship), a term project and a series of readings and discussions on the state of the art. In the practicum, students are placed in an industrial, commercial, or research environment for several hours a week to gain practical experience. The term project is a research project extending students' knowledge in some aspect of computer science. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Senior CS major or consent. Classified: 1. Meets: MN.</A> Scheduled: Spring, yearly
<HR>
<A HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
