<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Education/Child Development Detailed Course Descriptions</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<base href="http://www.rockford.edu">
</head>

<body>
<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>
Department of Education/Child Development</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Course offerings and descriptions</h2>

<HR>
<A NAME="200a"></A>
<h3>200A Field Experience: Elementary I      1 hour</h3>
<pre>
To pursue teaching certification, students must take two semester hours of supervised <BR>elementary-level field experience as sophomores and/or juniors to accommodate a <BR>Minimum of 100 clock hours of clinical work before student teaching.<BR><a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ:None. Classified: C. Meets: N. </a>Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
</pre>
<A NAME="200b"></A>
<h3>200B Field Experience: Secondary I            1 hour</h3>
To pursue teaching certification, students must take two semester hours of supervised secondary-level field experience as
sophomores and/or juniors to accommodate a minimum of 100 clock hours of clinical work before student teaching. PRQ:<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">
None. Classified: C. Meets: O.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="201a"></A>
<h3>201A Field Experience: Elementary II          1 hour</h3>
A continuation of supervised elementary-level field experience as sophomores and/or juniors to accommodate a minimum
of 100 clock hours of clinical work before student teaching. PRQ: Ed 200.  <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Classified: C.  Meets: N. </a> Scheduled: Fall and
spring, yearly.
<A NAME="201b"></A>
<h3>201B Field Experience: Secondary II      1 hour</h3>
A continuation of supervised secondary-level field experience as sophomores and/or juniors to accommodate a minimum
of 100 clock hours of clinical work before student teaching. PRQ: Ed 200. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Classified: C.  Meets: O. </a>Scheduled: Fall and
spring, yearly.
<A NAME="301"></A>
<h3>301 Teaching Methods (K-6)                    3 hours</h3>
Introduces various teaching methods, including lesson planning and presentation, discussion skills, classroom management,
evaluation, learning packets, and developing units. PRQ: Junior standing. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: Fall, spring, and summer
yearly.
<A NAME="302"></A>
<h3>302 Teaching Methods (6-12)              3 hours</h3>
Designed to introduce teaching methods, lesson planning, classroom processes, unit development, lesson presentation skills,
and evaluation techniques which are used in the secondary school classroom. PRQ: Junior standing.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: O.</a> Scheduled:
Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="303"></A>
<h3>303 Foundation of Language Arts               3 hours</h3>
Examines elements of a language arts program with emphasis on teaching writing. Includes considerations for LEP students
and history of English. PRQ: Junior standing. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: N. </a>Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly; summer, even years.
<A NAME="311"></A>
<h3>311 Reading Methods                      3 hours</h3>
Provides prospective teachers an array of instructional techniques to teach beginning reading, word recognition,
comprehension, vocabulary and content area reading. PRQ: Junior standing.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly;
summer, odd years.
<A NAME="315"></A>
<h3>315 Special Methods in Physical Education (K-12)   2 hours </h3>
(XL: PE 315) Instructional methodology and classroom management techniques unique to teaching elementary and secondary physical education. Hands-on experiences such as problem solving, peer teaching, videotaping lessons are included. PRQ: Junior standing. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<A NAME="322"></A>
<h3>322 Reading in Content Areas             3 hours</h3>
Provides current theory and techniques for teaching reading in various content areas for middle and high school teachers.
One of three education courses required for middle school endorsement. PRQ: Junior standing. Scheduled: Fall and spring,
yearly; summer, even years.
<A NAME="336"></A>
<h3>336 Educational Psychology                    3 hours</h3>
Child and adolescent development, principles of learning and teaching, memory, and motivation are studied with a special emphasis on meeting the needs of individual differences among students. One of three education courses required for middle
school endorsement. PRQ: None.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: NO. </a>Scheduled: Fall, spring and summer, yearly.
<A NAME="339"></A>
<h3>339 Counseling                           4 hours</h3>
(XL: Psych 339) Explores the helping process from various theoretical perspectives including psychoanalysis, existential psychotherapy, and cognitive-behavioral therapy. Includes practical applications and experiential exercises; addresses research and ethical issues. PRQ: Psych 100. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="342"></A>
<h3>LD 342 Development and Education of Exceptional Children               3 hours</h3>
Survey of exceptional children and educational adaptations: giftedness, retardation, visual, auditory and orthopedic handicaps, speech disorders, learning disabilities, cultural deprivations, social/emotional problems. PRQ: None.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: NO.</a>
Scheduled: Fall, spring and summer, yearly.
<A NAME="351"></A>
<h3>351 Mathematics Methods                  3 hours</h3>
An introduction to various methods for teaching mathematics in elementary schools. A knowledge of underlying mathematical theory is presumed. PRQ: Math 116 and 316, or consent of instructor.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: Fall, spring and summer, yearly.
<A NAME="352"></A>
<h3>352 Secondary Mathematics Methods (9-12) 3 hours</h3>
Introduction to various methods for teaching mathematics at the secondary level. Knowledge of underlying mathematical theory is presumed. PRQ: None. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: O. </a>Scheduled: Spring, even years; summer, odd years.
<A NAME="353"></A>
<h3>353 Literature for Children                   3 hours</h3>
Folklore, fables and fairy tales, poetry, legend, and story materials suitable for children from nursery school through 6th grade. PRQ: None. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.
<A NAME="354"></A>
<h3>354 Whole Language Methods in Reading         2 hours</h3>
This course explores Whole Language philosophy with an emphasis on its application to reading methods. Topics include integrated curricula and use of authentic texts and forms of evaluation. PRQ: Ed 311. Scheduled: Summer, yearly; spring,
odd years.
<A NAME="358"></A>
<h3>358 Literature for Adolescents           2 hours</h3>
Methods of teaching adolescent literature, including poetry, drama and fiction. PRQ: Ed 311. Scheduled: Spring, even years.
<A NAME="361"></A>
<h3>361 Innovations in Grammar                    4 hours</h3>
(XL: Eng 361) Recent innovations in grammar, with specific examination of transformational grammar. (Strongly recommended for teachers who have not taken English 354, Advanced Grammar.) This course can not be used to satisfy any all-college distribution requirement. PRQ: Eng 112 or equivalent. Scheduled: Summer, yearly.
<A NAME="365"></A>
<h3>365 Class Management Style                    2 hours</h3>
Theory and methods of class management and discipline at the elementary and secondary levels. PRQ: None. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="370"></A>
<h3>370 Cooperative Learning                 3 hours</h3>
Rationale and components of the cooperative learning model (Johnson and Johnson). Topics include research review, the teacher's role in cooperative development, lesson plan modification, and quality circle implementation.  PRQ: None. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="405"></A>
<h3>405 Elementary Student Teaching Seminar       3 hours</h3>
To be taken with Ed 407/408, elementary student teaching. A seminar to help student teachers learn techniques for dealing with classroom problems taken from actual cases in the student teachers classroom. PRQ: None.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: N. </a>Scheduled: Fall
and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="406"></A>
<h3>406 Secondary Student Teaching Seminar        3 hours</h3>
Complements the student's concurrent student teaching experience, helps the student develop positive attitudes<BR> toward teaching, and provides presentation techniques the student can put into practice in a continuing teaching experience. <BR>Thestudent must enroll concurrently in Special Methods Seminar(s) for the subject(s) in which he or she <BR>intends to be certified.
PRQ: None.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="407"></A>
<h3>407 Student Teaching in Elementary School I   6 hours</h3>
Classroom observation, assistance to the teacher, and actual teaching supervised by the classroom teacher and the college supervisor. Fee: $100.00. PRQ: Application to teaching semester.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Classified: C. Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring,
yearly.
<A NAME="408"></A>
<h3>408 Student Teaching in Elementary School II  6 hours</h3>
Classroom observation, assistance to the teacher, and actual teaching supervised by the classroom teacher and the college supervisor. Fee: $100.00. PRQ: Application to teaching semester.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Classified: C. Meets: N.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring,
yearly.
<A NAME="409"></A>
<h3>409 Student Teaching in Secondary School I    6 hours</h3>
Classroom observation, assistance to the teacher, and actual teaching supervised by the classroom teacher and the college supervisor. Fee: $100.00. PRQ: Application to teaching semester.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Classified: C. Meets: O.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring,
yearly.
<A NAME="410"></A>
<h3>410 Student Teaching in Secondary School II   6 hours</h3>
Classroom observation, assistance to the teacher, and actual teaching supervised by the classroom teacher and the college supervisor. Fee: $100.00. PRQ: Application to teaching semester.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Classified: C. Meets: O.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring,
yearly.
<A NAME="412"></A>
<h3>412 Philosophy of Education                   3 hours</h3>
Introduces contemporary American philosophers of education and their writings. Requires heavy reading and thinking to become familiar with the main concepts of idealistic, realistic, neo-Thomist, experimental and existential points of view ineducation and to develop personal philosophies of education.  PRQ: Junior standing.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: NO. </a>Scheduled: Spring, yearly.
<A NAME="415"></A>
<h3>415 Middle School Programs                    3 hours</h3>
</pre>
<pre>
Middle School Programs focuses on the curriculum, instruction, and philosophy of <BR>programs designed especially for early adolescents in grades 5-8. This course <BR>emphasizes instructional methods based on the physical, social, emotional, and <BR>intellectual needs and characteristics of early adolescents aged 10-14. Current <BR>research and practice will be used as the foundation for students' understanding of <BR>fundamental knowledge in the development of advisor-advisee programs, teaming, <BR>interdisciplinary teaching, flexible block scheduling, core curriculum, authentic <BR>assessment, interactive homework, and parental involvement. The advisory role of <BR>the middle school teacher in coordinating and referring students to health and social <BR>services will also be addressed. One of three education courses required for middle <BR>school endorsement. PRQ: Junior standing. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly; summer, odd years.</pre>
<A NAME="417"></A>
<h3>417 History of Education                 3 hours</h3>
<pre>
Education in the United States since colonial times, emphasizing leading theories of <BR>education and descriptions of school and teacher performance in the light of major <BR>roblems of an era. Attention will be given to research skills. PRQ: Junior standing. <BR><a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Meets: NO.</a> Scheduled: Fall and summer, yearly.
<A NAME="418"></A>
<h3>418 Teacher Seminar: Physical Education K-12  2 hours</h3>
(XL: PE 418) For student teachers to discuss problems and experiences in the public <BR>schools. Problem-solving techniques and classroom management procedures the <BR>student can use in daily experience and report back what he or she learns. Often <BR>meets off-campus. PRQ: Senior standing and major only and consent of instructor. <BR><a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Classified: C. Meets: O.</a> Scheduled:
Fall, yearly.
<A NAME="420"></A>
<h3>420 Special Methods Seminar: Art              1 hours</h3>
Complements Ed 406, Secondary Student Teaching Seminar. Special methods and t<BR>echniques of teaching the particular subject, taught by appropriately qualified <BR>faculty. PRQ: None.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: O. </a>Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="423"></A>
<h3>423 Special Methods Seminar: Foreign Languages     1 hour</h3>
Complements Ed 406, Secondary Student Teaching Seminar. Special methods and <BR>techniques of teaching the particular subject, taught by appropriately qualified <BR>faculty. PRQ: None.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: O.</a> Scheduled: On request.
<A NAME="495"></A>
<h3>495 Senior Seminar                       3 hours</h3>
Reviews, supplements and integrates previous studies in child development. PRQ: Senior <BR>standing.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Meets: N.</a> Scheduled:Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="498"></A>
<h3>498 Internship                           1-4 hours</h3>
PRQ: Senior standing. Classified: C. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.
<A NAME="499"></A>
<h3>499 Internship                           1-4 hours</h3>
PRQ: Senior standing.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> Classified: C.</a> Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</pre>
<hr>
