<html>



<head>

<title>Nursing Detailed Course Descriptions</title>


<base href="http://www.rockford.edu/">

</head>


<!- Created by Ryan Kussner>
<body>

<h1 align=center>Rockford College<br>

Department of Nursing</h1>

<hr>

<h2>Detailed Course Descriptions</h2>

<hr>

<p>(Note: Only Nurs 128 and 202 are open to non majors.) </p>

<A NAME = "128"></a><h3>128 Women's Health: Biology and Beyond	3</h3>

<p>Basic facts about the structure and functioning of the female body. Adaptations of the body to normal physiological events 

such as menstruation, sexual and reproductive activity, and menopause are covered. The body's responses to selected 

disease processes are included. In addition, this course explores the biopsychosocial issues pertinent to women's health and 

functioning in society. It examines women's relationships both as clients and as practitioners within the health care system. 

(Open to non majors)<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: M. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "202"></a><h3>202 Personal and Group Dynamics	2</h3>

<p>Concepts of intrapersonal and interpersonal dynamics are explored with a focus on self understanding, personal growth, and 

basic relationship skills. Theories of groups are examined, highlighting effective group behaviors. Communication skills 

important for interpersonal effectiveness are integrated throughout. (Open to non majors). <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Scheduled: Fall, 

yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "203"></a><h3>203 Nursing Process	2 </h3>

<p>The concept of health is examined from historical, philosophical, and current perspectives. Biological, psychological, 

environmental, cultural, economic, and societal factors influencing health of individuals are reviewed. Frameworks for health 

and illness are discussed. Society's responses to health needs are studied in terms of policy formation, the health professions, 

the health care delivery system, and the role of persons in society to promote, maintain, and restore health. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Concurrent 

enrollment in or prior completion of Bio 222. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "216"></a><h3>216 Introduction to Professional Nursing Practice	6</h3>

<p>Theories, concepts, values, attitudes, and skills basic to professional nursing practice are introduced, with an overview of 

historical development and contemporary status of nursing. The primary focus is on the older adult, emphasizing application of 

the nursing process to help individuals maintain and restore health. Knowledge and skills are applied in laboratory and clinical 

settings. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 222, 230 and 314; A/S 150; Nurs 203; concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Nurs 301. Meets: 

N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "310"></a><h3>310 Adult Health Nursing I	6</h3>

<p>Theory and practice associated with the nursing care of adults is the focus of this course. The nursing process is used for the 

promotion, maintenance, and restoration of health. Selected strategies such as health education and problem solving are 

explored. Clinical experiences focus on application of knowledge, attitudes, and skills with adult clients experiencing impaired 

health. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 308; Nurs 216, 301, 370, and concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Nurs 312. Meets: N. 

Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "312"></a><h3>312 Family Health Nursing	4</h3>

<p>Family theory is presented within the framework of the nursing process. Knowledge, attitudes, and skills are developed to 

provide nursing care to families. Health maintenance and promotion are emphasized in clinical experiences with child bearing 

families.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Psych 100 and 215; Nurs 216, 301, 370, and concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Nurs 310. 

Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "314"></a><h3>314 Child Health Nursing	5</h3>

<p>Child health theory is presented within the framework of the nursing process. Knowledge, attitudes, and skills are developed 

to provide nursing care to children with a family centered approach. Health maintenance, promotion, and restoration are 

emphasized in clinical experiences with children and their families.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Nurs 310, 312, and concurrent enrollment in or prior 

completion of Nurs 316. Meets: N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "316"></a><h3>316 Mental Health Nursing	4</h3>

<p>Mental health theories and practices associated with the nursing care of psychiatric clients are the focus of this course. The 

nursing process is used as a framework for strategies designed to promote good mental health for those exhibiting psychiatric 

pathology. Various clinical settings provide an opportunity for the application of nursing knowledge and skills across all 

developmental life stages.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ Nurs 310, 312, and concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Nurs 314. Meets: N. 

Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "410"></a><h3>410 Adult Health Nursing II	4</h3>

<p>Theory and practice associated with nursing care of the critically ill adult. Specialized knowledge and interventions will be 

utilized to deal specifically with human responses to life-threatening problems. Caring and healing practices that potentiate 

health will be explored. Practicum experiences focus on application of knowledge, attitudes, and skills with clients and their 

families in a variety of acute care service areas. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Nurs 314, 316, and concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of 

Nurs 403, 406 or 408. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall, yearly. </a>Restricted to BSN Completion students </p>

<A NAME = "386"></a><h3>386 Transitions in Nursing	3</h3>

<p>This course assists students with ADN/Diploma preparation to make the transition to baccalaureate education in practice. 

Course content includes: the RN to BSN student experience, review of articulation documents, the current status of the 

nursing profession, and contemporary professional practice. Prior student learning and practice is valued and used as a 

foundation for future personal and professional career development. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of 

Phil 256, and admission to the nursing major. Meets: N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "301"></a><h3>301 Health Assessment 3</h3>

<p>Provides an overview of health assessment techniques and recording. Develops knowledge and skills in historytaking and 

physical assessment of clients throughout the life span, with emphasis on the adult. Identification of findings within the normal 

range is emphasized and the significance of abnormal findings is explored. Opportunities for practice are provided. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 

209, Psych 100, and concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Bio 314, Psych 215. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall and 

spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "370"></a><h3>370 Pathophysiology Applied to Nursing	3</h3>

<p>The cellular processes of disease and trauma, and the body's adaptive and compensatory mechanisms and their 

manifestations are examined. The principles of pathophysiology as well as selected other biological and physical sciences are 

discussed, using a conceptual approach. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Bio 314; Psych 100 and 215; 

Nurs 216, 301; or by consent of instructor. Meets: N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "403"></a><h3>403 Nursing Research	3</h3>

<p>Introduction to research methodologies with focus on the research process. Concepts include history of research in nursing, 

scientific inquiry, research ethics, communication of research findings, and the nurses role in research. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 223, Nurs 

314, 316 or Nurs 301 and 385. Meets N. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "406"></a><h3>406 Community Health Nursing	4</h3>

<p>Synthesis and application of theories and principles in community health nursing. Specific health needs of populations are 

identified and strategies are planned to promote their health. The utilization of community resources and coordination of 

services within the health care system are explored. The clinical experiences provide opportunities to apply theoretical 

knowledge to nursing practice with families and groups.<a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Nurs 314, 316, or 386; concurrent enrollment in or prior 

completion of Nurs 403 or 410. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly. </a></p>

<A NAME = "408"></a><h3>408 Leadership and Management in Nursing	4 </h3>

<p>The role of the professional nurse as a leader and manager in an ever changing health care environment. Theoretical content 

includes organizational systems and change theory. Leadership and management principles with groups of clients and in 

collaboration with others in the health care system are discussed. Leadership and management in formal and informal systems 

are analyzed. Application of principles occurs in a variety of practicum settings. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Nurs 385, concurrent enrollment in or 

prior completion of Nurs 403 and 410. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</a> </p>

<A NAME = "495"></a><h3>495 Senior Seminar	4</h3>

<p>Contemporary issues and future trends affecting the nursing profession are investigated and analyzed. Discussions focus on 

professional, social, legal, ethical, political, and economic forces which influence nursing. Opportunities are provided to 

synthesize professional knowledge, attitudes, values, and skills into a self selected project or internship experience. <a href="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 

Nurs 410, Phil 256, and concurrent enrollment in or prior completion of Nurs 408 and 406. Meets: N. Scheduled: Yearly.</a> </p>

<hr>

<p><a href="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</a> </p>

