<HEAD>
<TITLE>Master of Arts in Teaching Detailed Course
Descriptions</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College <BR>
Master of Arts in Teaching</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>

<PRE>

<H3>Foundation Courses</H3>
<A NAME="605"></A>
<H3>Ed 605 Philosophical Foundations of Education   3 hours</H3> 
A study of various philosophical perspectives involved in the means and
ends of education within society and in the schools. Scheduled: Spring,
yearly; every third fall and summer.

<A NAME="615"></A>
<H3>Ed 615 Introduction to Research   3 hours</H3>
Historical survey of humans as knowledge-seeking beings with focus on
developing research methods necessary to accumulate reliable knowledge.
A research paper is required. Scheduled: spring, yearly; every third fall
and summer.

<A NAME="620"></A>
<H3>Ed 620 Psychological Foundations of Education   3 hours</H3>
A study of human growth and development, learning theory, and
experimental methodology, with particular emphasis on classroom
applications. Scheduled: spring, yearly; every third fall and summer.

<A NAME="625"></A>
<H3>Ed 625 Master of Arts in Teaching Seminar   1 hour</H3>

<A NAME="626"></A>
<H3>Ed 626 Master of Arts in Teaching Research 
(Thesis)   2 hours</H3>


<H3>Reading Courses</H3>
<A NAME="503"></A>
<H3>Ed 503 Foundation of Language Arts   3 hours</H3>
Examines elements of a language arts program with emphasis on teaching
writing. Includes considerations for LEP students and history of English. 
Scheduled: fall and spring, yearly; summer, even years.

<A NAME="511"></A>
<H3>Ed 511 Reading Methods   3 hours</H3>
Provides prospective teachers an array of instructional techniques to teach
beginning reading, word recognition, comprehension, vocabulary and
content area reading. Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly; summer, odd
years.

<A NAME="522"></A>
<H3>Ed 522 Reading in Content Areas (4-12)   3 hours</H3>
Provides current theory and techniques for teaching reading in various
content areas as well as the reading class for intermediate, middle school,
and high school teachers.

<A NAME="553"></A>
<H3>Ed 553 Literature for Children (K-6)   3 hours</H3>
Folklore, fables and fairy tales, poetry, legend, and story materials suitable
for children from nursery school through sixth grade.

<A NAME="554"></A>
<H3>Ed 554 Whole Language Methods in Reading   2 hours</H3>
This course explores Whole Language philosophy with an emphasis on its
application to reading methods. Topics include integrated curricula and
use of authentic texts and forms of evaluation.

<A NAME="555"></A>
<H3>Ed/LD 555 Remedial Reading Practicum   3 hours</H3>
Lectures, demonstrations, and practice in working with Learning Resource
Center pupils. PRQ: Ed 556, Ed 557, consent of instructor.

<A NAME="556"></A>
<H3>Ed/LD 556 Reading Diagnosis   3 hours</H3>
The diagnosis of reading and spelling ability and disabilities with
emphasis on skillful administration and interpretation of informal reading
inventories.

<A NAME="557"></A>
<H3>Ed/LD 557 Instructional Support Methods 
in Reading   2 hours</H3>
The course provides in-depth knowledge about delivering services to
learners for whom learning to read is difficult. Approaches include clinical
and collaborative interventions and methods in staff development. PRQ:
Ed 311 or equivalent.

<A NAME="558"></A>
<H3>Ed 558 Literature for Adolescents   2 hours</H3>
Methods of teaching adolescent literature, including poetry, drama, and
fiction. 

<A NAME="559"></A>
<H3>Ed/LD 559 Clinical Experience in Reading   3 hours</H3>
This course synthesizes the diagnostic-prescriptive model.  Students work
in a clinical setting in which they conduct diagnosis, provide one-on-one
tutoring to clients experiencing difficulty in reading, and meet in a seminar
format.  PRQ: Ed 556, 557, and consent of instructor.


<H3>General Education Courses</H3>
<A NAME="501"></A>
<H3>Ed 501 Teaching Methods (K-6)   3 hours</H3>
Introduces a variety of teaching methods. Topics include lesson planning,
discussion skills, lesson presentation skills, classroom management,
evaluation, learning packets and unit development.

<A NAME="502"></A>
<H3>Ed 502 Teaching Methods (6-12)   3 hours</H3>
Designed to introduce teaching methods, lesson planning, classroom
processes, unit development, lesson presentation skills, and evaluation
techniques which are used in the secondary school classroom.

<A NAME="503"></A>
<H3>Ed 503 Foundation of Language Arts   3 hours</H3>
Examines elements of a language arts program with emphasis on teaching
writing. Includes considerations for LEP students and history of English.

<A NAME="512"></A>
<H3>Ed 512 Philosophy of Education   3 hours</H3>
Introduces contemporary American philosophers of education and their
writings. Requires heavy reading and thinking to become familiar with the
main concepts of idealistic, realistic, neo-Thomist, experimental and
existential points of view in education and to develop personal
philosophies of education.

<A NAME="515"></A>
<H3>Ed 515 Middle School Programs   3 hours</H3>
Middle School Programs focuses on the curriculum, instruction, and
philosophy of programs designed especially for early adolescents in grades
5-8. This course emphasizes instructional methods based on the physical,
social, emotional, and intellectual needs and characteristics of early
adolescents aged 10-14. Current research and practice will be used as the
foundation for students' understanding of fundamental knowledge in the
development of advisor-advisee programs, teaming, interdisciplinary
teaching, flexible block scheduling, core curriculum, authentic assessment,
interactive homework, and parental involvement. The advisory role of the
middle school teacher in coordinating and referring students to health and
social services will also be addressed. 

<A NAME="517"></A>
<H3>Ed 517 History of Education   3 hours</H3>
Education in the United States from colonial times to the present, with
emphasis on leading theories in education and descriptions of school and
teacher performance in the light of major problems of a given era.
Attention will be given to research skills in this field.

<A NAME="536></A>
<H3>Ed 536 Educational Psychology   3 hours</H3>
Child and adolescent development, principles of learning and teaching,
memory, and motivation are studied with a special emphasis on meeting
the needs of individual differences among students.

<A NAME="539"></A>
<H3>Ed 539 Counseling and Guidance   3 hours</H3>
The rationale behind various techniques used to help individuals make the
best use of their capabilities; includes lectures, discussions and
demonstrations.

<A NAME="551"></A>
<H3>Ed 551 Mathematics Methods (K-6)   3 hours</H3>
An introduction to various methods to teach mathematics in elementary
schools. A knowledge of underlying mathematical theory is presumed.

<A NAME="552"></A>
<H3>Ed 552 Secondary Mathematics Methods (7-12)   3 hours</H3>
Introduction to various methods for teaching mathematics at the secondary
level. A knowledge of underlying mathematical theory is presumed.

<A NAME="561"></A>
<H3>Ed/Eng 561 Innovations in Grammar   4 hours</H3>
A study of recent innovations in grammar, with specific examination of
Transformational grammar. (Strongly recommended for school teachers
who have not taken English 354/554, Advanced Grammar.)

<A NAME="565"></A>
<H3>Ed 565 Class Management Style   2 hours</H3>
Theory and methods of class management and discipline at the elementary
and secondary levels.

<A NAME="570"></A>
<H3>Ed 570 Cooperative Learning   2 hours</H3>
Rationale and components of the cooperative learning model (Johnson and
Johnson). Topics include research review, the teacher's role in cooperative
development, lesson plan modification, and quality circle implementation.


<H3>Learning Disabilities Courses</H3>
<A NAME="539"></A>
<H3>Ed 539 Counseling and Guidance   3 hours</H3>
(See under General Education above.)

<A NAME="542"></A>
<H3>LD 542 Development & Education 
of Exceptional Children   3 hours</H3>
Exceptional children and educational adaptations are surveyed: giftedness,
retardation, visual, auditory and orthopedic handicaps, speech disorders,
learning disabilities, cultural deprivations, social/emotional problems.

<A NAME="556"></A>
<H3>LD 556 Reading Diagnosis   3 hours</H3>
(See under Reading above.)

<A NAME="557"></A>
<H3>LD 557 Instructional Support Methods in Reading   3 hours</H3>
(See under Reading above.)

<A NAME="558"></A>
<H3>LD 558 Learning Disabilities Characteristics   3 hours</H3>
Abilities and disabilities of children with specific learning difficulties,
focused on distinguishing learning disabilities from general mental
impairment and emotional and motivational interference. PRQ: LD 342.

<A NAME="559"></A>
<H3>LD 559 Clinical Experience in Reading   3 hours</H3>
(See under Reading above.)

<A NAME="560"></A>
<H3>LD 560 LD/MI/BD Diagnosis   3 hours</H3>
Differential diagnosis of learning disabilities, mental impairment, and
behavior disorders. Selecting and administering tests of abilities and
school achievement; types of test scores and use of data on validity,
reliability, intercorrelation, and factor analysis; interpreting data patterns
from tests observations, and history. PRQ: LD 542.

<A NAME="562"></A>
<H3>LD 562 Learning Disabilities Methods   3 hours</H3>
A practical application of methods, techniques and materials for teaching
children with learning disabilities; principles underlying  prescriptive
programming, behavior modification, and materials both commercial and
self-made are emphasized. PRQ: LD 558.

<A NAME="564"></A>
<H3>LD 564 Consulting Strategies   2 hours</H3>
The consulting role of the special educator in the regular education
program.  Strategies and services responsive to the needs of handicapped
students or at-risk students in the regular classroom are studied.

<A NAME=""></A>
<H3>LD 565 Advanced LD Diagnosis   3 hours</H3>
Advanced training in the diagnosis of learning disabled individuals. 
Technical aspects of administering, scoring, and interpreting various
assessment instruments are explored. The content primarily focuses on the
application of the Woodcock-Johnson Psycho-Educational Battery and the
Detroit Tests of Learning Aptitude.

<A NAME="580"></A>
<H3>LD 580 Behavior Disorders Characteristics   3 hours</H3>
Identification, etiology, classification, and assessment of behavior
disorders in children and a comparison of several models for construing
disorders of behavior.

<A NAME="581"></A>
<H3>LD 581 Behavior Disorders Methods   3 hours</H3>
Application of interventions to specific case studies and class patterns:
task analysis for prescriptive academic programming, criterion based
evaluation techniques, spatial and temporal organization of classrooms,
techniques of and data collection for applied behavior modification
systems, effective education including socialization experiences and
values clarification activities, and multi-disciplinary approaches through
community resources.

<A NAME="581"></A>
<H3>LD 585 MI (EMH/TMH) Characteristics   3 hours</H3>
Focus on classification, diagnosis and characteristics of the educable
mentally handicapped student; definition, prevalence, etiology, learning
theories and contemporary issues will be discussed.

<A NAME="586"></A>
<H3>LD 586 MI (EMH/TMH) Methods   3 hours</H3>
A practical application of methods, techniques and materials for teaching
children identified as educable mentally handicapped; definition,
prevalence, etiology, learning theories and contemporary issues will be
discussed.

<A NAME="608"></A>
<H3>LD 608 Learning Disabilities Practicum   3-5 hours</H3>
A supervised practicum in teaching children identified as having specific
disabilities in learning. Emphasis is placed on specific analysis of tasks
and relating academic skills to their precursors. An additional 2 semester
hours is required of individuals with no LD experience. PRQ: consent of
instructor.

<A NAME="695"></A>
<H3>LD 695 Seminar on Special Education   2 hours</H3>
Integrative review and an evaluation of current trends and issues in special
education, with emphasis on learning disabilities, behavior disorders, and
general mental impairment in the EMH range.


<H3>Instructional Strategies Courses</H3>
<A NAME="580"></A>
<H3>Ed 580 Project T.E.A.C.H. 
(Teaching Effectiveness and Classroom Handling)   3 hours</H3>
Presents various skills and strategies which can be used to manage the
classroom more effectively. Teachers will learn to create an environment
that increases teaching time while improving student cooperation.

<A NAME="581"></A>
<H3>Ed 581 P.R.I.D.E. 
(Professional Refinements in Developing Effectiveness)   3 hours</H3>
Presents strategies and techniques which can increase classroom
effectiveness through more precise teaching skills, enhancing smooth
classroom operation and reducing stress.

<A NAME="582"></A>
<H3>Ed 582 Teaching Through Learning Channels   3 hours</H3>
Explores how to increase academic success for all students by identifying
and using learning channel strengths. Focuses on developing strategies to
meet the needs of all students.

<A NAME="583"></A>
<H3>Ed 583 Patterns for I.D.E.A.S.   3 hours</H3>
This course reveals patterns by which students of all ages think. Teachers
will experience various activities demonstrating patterns used by the mind
and will learn how to use effective questioning techniques to increase
student thinking.

<A NAME="584"></A>
<H3>Ed 584 Keys to Motivation   3 hours</H3>
Create a motivating environment for all students, understand students who
are not motivated to learn or participate, foster student grouping strategies,
and use encouragement and leadership strategies to enhance motivation.

<A NAME="585"></A>
<H3>Ed 585 Peer Collaboration for 
Instructional Effectiveness   3 hours</H3>
This course develops and models strategies that help teachers share
teaching ideas with one another. Participants will be introduced to
communication and coaching skills which will enable them to talk about
and reflect on their own teaching. Ideal for teachers, mentors, lead
teachers, and peer coaches.

<A NAME="586"></A>
<H3>Ed 586 Achieving Student Outcomes 
Through Cooperative Learning   3 hours</H3>
For teachers who would like to use cooperative strategies as an alternative
to competition and individualization to improve achievement and develop
interpersonal skills. Activities include cooperative simulations, learning
and using cooperative learning models, and creating lesson plans to
implement micro lessons.

<A NAME="590"></A>
<H3>Ed 590 Teaching Skills of the 21st Century   3 hours</H3>
What students need to know and be able to do to live successfully.
Educators will share personal views of various topics on effective teaching
and learning. Participants will also be introduced to a variety of facilitation
skills to help ensure maximum teaching effectiveness.

</PRE>

<HR>
