<HEAD>
<TITLE>Master of Business Administration Detailed Course
Descriptions</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College <BR>
Master of Business Administration</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>

<PRE>

<H3>Prerequisite Courses</H3>
<A NAME="501"></A>
<H3>BA 501 Mathematical Analysis for Management   3 hours</H3>
Basic mathematical concepts used in management for students with little
or no previous work in calculus or in management science. Topics include
a study of mathematical functions commonly arising in management
science, elementary matrix theory, linear systems, linear programming,
and informal introduction to basic concepts of calculus. Application to
management problems is emphasized throughout. PRQ:  College algebra
or consent of instructor.

<A NAME="502"></A>
<H3>BA 502 Survey of the Principles of Economics   3 hours</H3>
An intensive survey of the principles of micro- and macroeconomics
analysis for graduate students who have had little or no recent work in
economics. The course fulfills the prerequisite requirement of Econ 101
and 102 for all MBA students.

<A NAME="518"></A>
<H3>BA 518 Business Finance   3 hours</H3>
Provides insight into the basic conceptual framework within which
financial management occurs. Study of the use of appropriate tools to
derive objective information is integrated with an appreciation for the
necessity of sound judgment within the decision-making process of the
firm. This course fulfills the finance prerequisite. PRQ: Acct 223 and 224
or BA 524 or its equivalent.

<A NAME="524"></A>
<H3>BA 524 Accounting Concepts   3 hours</H3>
A comprehensive introduction to accounting concepts in business. Both
financial and managerial principles are covered. With an emphasis on the
users of accounting information, the development, presentation, and
limitations of accounting, and the use of accounting as a control device
will be discussed. The course fulfills the prerequisite requirement of Acct
223 and 224 for all MBA students.


<H3>Required Courses</H3>
<A NAME="503"></A>
<H3>BA 503 Managerial Economics   3 hours</H3>
Microeconomic theory and analysis useful in managerial decision making
and policy formation. It applies economic principles to the analysis of
production, marketing, and financial issues and development of general
operating strategies. Linear programming, input-output analysis and other
quantitative techniques are introduced.  PRQ: Econ 101 and 102 or BA
502; BA 501 or its equivalent.

<A NAME="504"></A>
<H3>BA 504 Business and the National Economy   3 hours</H3>
Public economic policies that control the price level, employment level,
and economic growth rate and their impact on the firm and the nation. It
includes discussion of national income accounting, factors responsible for
economic fluctuations, and the role of fiscal and monetary policy. The use
of economic indicators and the development of simple forecasting models
are also considered. PRQ: Econ 101 and 102 or BA 502; BA 501 or its
equivalent.

<A NAME="510"></A>
<H3>BA 510 Legal Environment of Business   3 hours</H3>
The legal environment in which business operates through selective
problems of a commercial society and how the laws respond to these
problems. Some topics to be dealt with include how courts, governments
taxation and regulation, administrative law, antitrust law, labor law and
legal trends affect business policy. 

<A NAME="530"></A>
<H3>BA 530 Managerial Accounting and Control   3 hours</H3>
The use of accounting in the management and control of a firm. The use of
financial statements by both managers and outsiders will be covered, with
emphasis on the use of managerial accounting information to report,
evaluate, and control performance.  PRQ: Acct 223 and 224 or BA 524;
BA 518.

<A NAME="540"></A>
<H3>BA 540 Financial Management   3 hours</H3>
The financial framework within which business operates and the principles
governing the operation of financial markets, the choice of capital
investment projects, the sources and uses of short-term and long-term
corporate financing, and valuation problems.  PRQ: BA 501 or its
equivalent; BA 518; BA 530.

<A NAME="550"></A>
<H3>BA 550 Management Theory   3 hours</H3>
Organization and management, with an emphasis on the functional areas
of planning, organizing, directing, coordinating, and controlling the
business enterprise.  Behavioral aspects of management including
leadership, motivation, and organization theory are included.

<A NAME="560"></A>
<H3>BA 560 Marketing   3 hours</H3>
Emphasis on forming marketing policies and strategies. Examines product
planning and development, selection and development of marketing
channels, marketing research, and cost allocation. Includes managerial
aspects of marketing and relationship of marketing to the total business
operation.

<A NAME="580"></A>
<H3>BA 580 Introduction to Business Research   3 hours</H3>
Understanding research purposes and processes from the viewpoint of a
consumer of research. Topics include problem analysis and hypothesis
formulation, research design, implementation of research, and analysis of
research results. PRQ: Math 223, BA 501 or its equivalent.

<A NAME="590"></A>
<H3>BA 590 Business Communication   3 hours</H3>
A study of the skills necessary to communicate effectively in business.
Approaches writing as a process and provides practice writing standard
types of letters, memos, and reports. Includes principles of oral
communication.

<A NAME="696"></A>
<H3>BA 696 Business Planning and Strategies   3 hours</H3>
Integrates and applies knowledge from previous courses while
emphasizing formulation, implementation, and evaluation of strategic
planning within an organization. Focuses on management policy-making
and problem analysis within the framework of the stakeholder concept
which emphasizes the relationship between a business and its owners,
customers, employees, suppliers, competitors, various governments, the
media, and other special interest groups. Develops an understanding of the
business enterprise as a member of a larger social, political, and economic
system. PRQ: BA 510, BA 540, BA 550, BA 560.


<H3>Elective Courses</H3>
<A NAME="641"></A>
<H3>BA 641 Investment Management   3 hours</H3>
Techniques of investment analysis and portfolio management.
Implications of the theories of efficient capital markets and hedging
models are emphasized.  PRQ: BA 540.

<A NAME="650"></A>
<H3>BA 650 Production Management   3 hours</H3>
The decision-making process in production and operational areas.  Topics
include the theoretical foundations for operations management, approaches
to production problems, production processes, plant layout, maintenance,
scheduling, quality control and production control. PRQ: BA 550.

<A NAME="651"></A>
<H3>BA 651 Organizational Behavior   3 hours</H3>
Working concepts of professional human resource management. Reviews
basic motivation theory, interpersonal relationships, and group dynamics
as they apply to management for personal and organizational goals.  PRQ:
BA 550.

<A NAME="652"></A>
<H3>BA 652 International Business   3 hours</H3>
Understanding the markets of multinational firms and the strategies and
practices needed to service and expand in the international market place.
Topics include marketing, research, production, labor costs, distribution
systems, and management strategies.  PRQ: BA 550; BA 560.

<A NAME="654"></A>
<H3>BA 654 Human Resource Management   3 hours</H3>
A systems approach to studying personnel/human resource management.
Analyzes the dynamic interactions of individual needs, personnel
functions, company goals, and environmental factors. PRQ: BA 550.

<A NAME="660"></A>
<H3>BA 660 Consumer Behavior   3 hours</H3>
A survey of this field of buyer behavior, including its theoretical bases and
applications to problems of management. Topics include motivation,
learning, attitude formation, and the relationship between attitudes and
behavior as applied to buyers. Also discussed are innovation, market
communication, and the social and cultural concepts underlying strategies
of market segmentation. PRQ: BA 560.

<A NAME="661"></A>
<H3>BA 661 Promotion Policies and Management   3 hours</H3>
An analysis of promotion problems from management's point of view.
Includes the role of promotion in a firm's total set of strategies and judging
the effectiveness of promotion expenditures. Prerequisite: BA 560.

<A NAME="670"></A>
<H3>BA 670 International Trade and 
Financial Management   3 hours</H3>
An analysis of fundamental economic principles, forces, and governmental
policies which determine economic relations between countries under
changing world conditions. Investigates the theories and practices of
international financial management, including international trade theory,
balance of payments, foreign exchange markets, international capital
budgeting, multinational enterprises, and the international monetary
system.  PRQ: BA 502 or equivalent and BA 540.

<A NAME="680"></A>
<H3>BA 680 Information Systems in Business   3 hours</H3>
A comprehensive presentation of the flow of information in a business.
Topics range from the completely manual system to the most sophisticated
computerized environment. Includes human interaction as well as methods
of choosing, designing, implementing, and evaluating an information
system. PRQ: BA 580.

</PRE>

<HR>
<A HREF="http:///www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
