<HTML>

<HEAD>
<Title>Types of Financial Aid</title>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu">
</head>

<BODY  BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#251899" vlink="#870999">
<a NAME ="TOP"></a>
<hr>

<h1 align="center">
Types of Financial Aid
</h1>
<hr>

<ul>
	<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#FFA">Federal Financial Aid</a>
		<UL>
		<LI><A Href="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Pell">Federal Pell Grant</a>
		<LI><A Href="/finaid/typeaid.htm#FSEOG">Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grant (FSEOG)</a>
		<LI><A Href="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Perkins">Federal Perkins Loan</a>
		<LI><A Href="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Staff">Federal Stafford Loan</a>
			<ul>
			<LI><A Href="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Sub">Subsidized</a>
		       	<LI><A Href="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Un">Unsubsidized</a>
			</ul>
		</ul>				

	<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#ILL">Illinois State Financial Aid</a>
		<ul>
		<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#MAP">Illinois Monetary Award</a>
		</ul>
	<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Other">Other Types of Aid</a>
		<ul>
		<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Emp">Employment</a>
		<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#Sch">Scholarships</a>
		<LI><A HREF ="/finaid/typeaid.htm#PL">Parent Loans</a>
		</ul>
	</ul>

<H2 align =center><A Name="FFA">Federal Financial Aid</a></h2>


<p>
When you file both the Financial Aid Application and the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA), your eligibility for the following three grant and three loan programs will be considered.
</p>
<A Name="Pell"></a>
<p>
Federal Pell Grant - A Federal Pell Grant is an award to help first-time undergraduates pay for their education after high school. A first-time undergraduate is one who has not earned a bachelors degree. To determine if you are eligible, the U.S. Department of Education uses a standard formula, passed into law by Congress, to evaluate the information you report on your FAFSA.
</p>
<A Name="FSEOG"></a>

<p>
Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grant (FSEOG) - The FSEOG is an award to help first-time undergraduates. The amount you may receive depends on your financial need, amount of other aid you receive, and the availability of funds at Rockford College.
</p>
<A Name="Perkins"></a>
<p>
Federal Perkins Loan - A Federal Perkins Loan is a low-interest (five percent) loan for first-time undergraduates. The amount you may receive depends on your financial need, amount of other aid you received, and the availability of funds at Rockford College. You must repay this loan.
</p>
<A Name="Staff"></a>
<p>
Federal Stafford Loan - Federal Stafford Loans are low-interest loans made to both undergraduate and graduate students enrolled at least half-time. Students ineligible for (or ineligible for the full amount of) Subsidized Federal Stafford Loan have an option to borrow an Unsubsidized Federal Stafford Loan.
</p>
<A Name="Sub"></a>
<p>
Subsidized Federal Stafford Loans are based on financial need. The federal government pays the interest during in-school and deferment periods.
</p>
<A Name="Un"></a>
<p>
Unsubsidized Federal Stafford Loans are based on financial need. The student is responsible for paying the interest from the date the funds are disbursed.
</p>

<H2 align =center><A Name="ILL">Illinois State Financial Aid</a></h2>
<A Name="MAP"></a>
<p>
Illinois State Monetary Award Program (MAP) - The MAP award is a grant available from the State of Illinois for Illinois residents who are first-time undergraduates. The Illinois Student Assistant Commission (ISAC) developed a formula to evaluate the information reported on your FAFSA. The maximum award is applied toward tuition and mandatory fees.
</p>
<H2 align =center><A Name="Other">Other Types of Aid</a></h2>
<A Name="Emp"></a>
<p>
Employment - Each year approximately 200 students are employed part-time on campus through the Federal Work-Study Program and non-work-study jobs. The Career Planning & 
</p>
<p>
Placement Office can help you arrange part-time work on campus. They also keep listings of part-time jobs off campus.
</p>
<A Name="Sch"></a>
<p>
Scholarships - Many individuals, organizations, and corporations provide scholarship assistance for students at Rockford College. Preference for endowed scholarships is given to students who have completed at least one year of study at Rockford College. Scholarships may be obtained from industry, service groups, professional organizations, foundations, churches, state government, and academic departments. Application procedures and eligibility requirements are determined by the donor.
</p>
<A Name="PL"></a>
<p>
Parent Loans - The Federal PLUS (Parent Loan for Undergraduate Students) applications are available from the Financial Aid Office. 
</p>

<p>Go back to the <A HREF="/finaid/typeaid.htm#TOP">top</a> of the page.</p>
<p>Go back to the <A HREF="/finaid/finaid.htm">Financial Aid </a>page.</p>


<HR>
<A HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
