<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chemistry Detailed Course Descriptions</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">                      
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College<BR>
Department of Chemistry</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>


<A NAME="101"></A>
<H3>101 Understanding The Nuclear Age      3</H3>
<p>This course is designed to give students background to make informed decisions in our nuclear age. Topics include the
structure of the atom, the nucleus, fission, fusion, nuclear power, nuclear weapons, radioactivity,
radioisotopes, nuclear winter. Visual aids used. Laboratory involves illustrations of concepts as well as data collection, graphics, etc. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Classified: T. Meets: M. Scheduled: On demand.</A> 

<A NAME="102"></A>
<H3>102 Chemistry in Our Environment  4</H3>
<p>Designed and developed especially for non-science majors, this course examines current
societal issues related to chemistry and the
environment. Course topics may include air quality, water quality, ozone depletion, global
warming, alternative energy sources and
conservation, solid waste disposal and recycling, polymers, drugs, and nutrition. Appropriate
chemistry is introduced as topics are
presented. A goal of the course is to enhance critical thinking skills while providing a foundation
of knowledge for making informed
decisions about environmental issues. Laboratory experiments are related to the course content
and emphasize environmental topics.
 <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">Classified: T. Meets: M. Scheduled: On demand.</A>


<A NAME="105"></A>
<H3>105 General Chemistry I       4</H3>
<p>This is a standard introduction to the principles of chemistry, including  atomic theory,
stoichiometry, atomic structure, chemical
bonding and molecular geometry, and thermochemistry. Laboratory experiments emphasize
proper reportage and analysis of scientific
data. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: 1 year of high school algebra; high school chemistry recommended. Classified: T. Meets:
MNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="106"></A>
<H3>106 General Chemistry II     4</H3>
<p>In this second half of the year-long introductory course in chemistry, new topics include kinetics,
chemical equilibrium,
thermodynamics, electrochemistry, nuclear chemistry and transition metal chemistry. Lab
experiments closely follow the material
presented in lecture hours; emphasize quantitative skills as well as proper reporting of
experimental results. Lecture 3 hours; lab
3 hours.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 105. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="131"></A>
<H3>131 Aspects of General and Inorganic Chemistry   4</H3>
<p>This course introduces modern principles of chemistry suitable for nurses and other allied health
students, elementary education
majors, and others who do not need a two-year chemistry sequence. Atomic structure, bonding,
gas laws, solution, acids and bases,
and nuclear chemistry are among the topics studied. The lab consists of varied experiments,
including some analytical techniques.
 <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: High school algebra. Classified: T. Meets: M.  Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="132"></A>
<H3>132 Aspects of Organic and Biochemistry      4</H3>
<p>This course is for those who have had one semester of college chemistry and is designed
especially for nurses, allied health
students, elementary education majors, and others who do not plan to take another year of
chemistry. The first half of the semester
is a survey of organic chemistry including the major functional groups. The second half deals
with carbohydrates, lipids, proteins,
nucleic acids, enzymes and metabolism. The lab includes a variety of experiments from organic
and biochemistry and has both
qualitative and quantitative techniques. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 131 or its equivalent. Classified: T. Meets: M. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="181"></A>
<H3>181 Preprofessional Experience     1-2</H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"></A>

<A NAME="182"></A>
<H3>182 Preprofessional Experience    1-2</H3>
<p>Preprofessional experience provides an opportunity to work in a hospital and become more
knowledgeable about the requirements of
and professional opportunities in medicine. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"> PRQ: Consent of instructor. Scheduled: Fall, spring, and summer, yearly.</A>
 
<A NAME="205"></A>
<H3>205 Organic Chemistry I      4</H3>
<p>We introduce in this first organic course topics covering basic theory, stereochemistry, some
reaction mechanisms, properties,
preparations, and reactions of several functional groups. The lab work covers basic techniques
of organic chemistry and some
reactions. Lecture 3 hours, lab 3 hours.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 106. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="206"></A>
<H3>206 Organic Chemistry II      4</H3>
<p>As a continuation of Chem 205, the course focuses on a number of other important functional
groups and reaction mechanisms. The lab
includes some qualitative analysis and syntheses. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 205. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled:Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="301"></A>
<H3>301 Analytical Chemistry      4</H3>
<p>Analytical chemistry introduces students to the theory and practice of quantitative analysis,
including separation techniques and
some spectrophotometric methods. Laboratory experiments illustrate the application of a variety
of these methods and provides
experience in sample analysis and data interpretation. Lecture 2 hours; lab 6 hours.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 106. Classified: T. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="302"></A>
<H3>302 Instrumental Methods of Analysis    4</H3>
<p>In this survey of modern chemical instrumentation, students develop skills in spectroscopic,
electrochemical, and chromatographic
techniques. The design, operation, and use of each instrument will be discussed. Laboratory
work will emphasize both independent
and group work. Lecture 2 hours; lab 6 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 301 and Phys 106 or 202. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Alternating</A>
 
<A NAME="305"></A>
<H3>305 Physical Chemistry I               4</H3>
<p>This course serves to develop the student s understanding of classical thermodynamics,
chemical potential, chemical and phase
equilibria, electrochemistry and chemical kinetics. Lab consists of several experiments that
serve to illustrate the material covered
in the lectures. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 106, Phys 202, and Math 131. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall,
yearly. </A>
 
<A NAME="306"></A>
<H3>306 Physical Chemistry II              4</H3>
<p>The second course in physical chemistry includes an introduction to quantum chemistry as well
as discussion of atomic and molecular
spectroscopy and statistical mechanics. The lab experiments illustrate the material covered in
lecture. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 305 or consent of instructor. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="308"></A>
<H3>308 Introduction to Biochemistry  4</H3>
<p>The chemistry of biological molecules is introduced in this course. Students will study the
nomenclature, structure, and
stereochemistry of carbohydrates, proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids. Also covered are
biochemical reactions, their kinetics and
energetics, and their relationship to metabolism. The laboratory includes practical experience,
both qualitative and quantitative,
working with these biological systems. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 206.  Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Yearly.
</A>
 
<A NAME="371"></A>
<H3>371 Undergraduate Research 1-4</H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"></A> 

<A NAME="372"></A>
<H3>372 Undergraduate Research 1-4</H3>
<p>Working independently, students conduct both laboratory and literature investigations on
problems chosen from the areas of faculty
expertise and interest. Currently areas include chemical kinetics, laser spectroscopy, synthesis
of organometallic compounds,
ferrocenophane chemistry, and structure/function relationships of enzymes. The experimental
work is designed to develop students'
ability to work independently and to interpret and communicate experimental results. The course
may be repeated for additional
credit. Lab 3 hours/credit hour. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 106 and consent of instructor. Meets: MN. Scheduled: Fall, spring, and summer,
yearly.</A>

<A NAME="398"></A>
<H3>398 Internship: Chemistry 1-8</H3>
<p> <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm"></A> 

<A NAME="399"></A>
<H3>399 Internship: Chemistry 1-8</H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent of instructor. Meets: N. Scheduled: Fall, spring, and summer, yearly.</A> 
 
<A NAME="402"></A>
<H3>402 Principles of Instrumental Analysis     4</H3>
<p>A survey of modern chemical instrumentation with emphasis on spectroscopic, electrochemical,
and chromatographic techniques. The
theory, design, operation, and use of each instrument will be discussed. Laboratory work will
emphasize independent learning as well
as work doing traditional laboratory experiments. Lecture 2 hours; lab 6 hours.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 301 and 306. Classified: T. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Alternating springs.</A> 
 
<A NAME="405"></A>
<H3>405 Advanced Inorganic Chemistry  4</H3>
<p>With the entire periodic table at their disposal, students will explore the divers nature of
inorganic chemistry.  Starting with
atoms, the course explores principles of bonding and chemical reactivity of inorganic
compounds. Also, several special topics may
be covered such as organometallic catalysis, bioinorganic chemistry, and group theory. The
laboratory work will illustrate ideas
covered in the classroom and will include techniques used routinely by working inorganic
chemists. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.
 <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 206 and 306. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Alternating springs.</A>

<A NAME="406"></A>
<H3>406 Special Topics in Chemistry   3</H3>
<p>This course provides students with an intensive advanced study of one aspect of chemistry,
such as organic, physical, or bioinorganic
chemistry. This course may be repeated for credit provided a different topic is covered. Lecture.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent of instructor. Meets:
MNO. Scheduled: On request.</A> 

<A NAME="495A"></A>
<H3>495A Senior Seminar (Research)    1</H3>
<p>This part of senior seminar is a formal introduction to methods of research in chemistry.
Students will use the library extensively in researching a topic of interest, will become familiar
with the use of computers in searching the chemical literature, and will work with one or more
faculty on an independent research project. This project may involve
traditional laboratory research or may relate to chemical education, such as the development of
a new experiment for students.  <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent of instructor. Classified: T. Meets N.  Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A> 

<A NAME="495B"></A>
<H3>495B Senior Seminar (Discussion)          3</H3>
<p>In this second part of senior seminar, the senior majors draw together all that they have learned
over the previous 3 1/2 years. Students conduct library research and present papers to colleagues
on various topics in chemistry, both historical and topical. Guest speakers will also present talks
on a wide range of topics, such as ethics in science, industrial
chemistry, life in graduate school, or chemistry in our environment.<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Previous or concurrent enrollment in Chem 495A. Meets N. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.



<HR>
<A HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A>
