<HTML>
<!--PLEASE NOTE THAT WHERE PHYSICS IS USED, -->
<!-- THIS REPRESENTS THE DEPARTMENT NAME -->
<!--Limited to eight characters -->

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Physics Detailed Course Descriptions</TITLE> 
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">                      
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1 >Rockford College<BR>
Department of Physics</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>

<!-- THE @@@ REPRESENTS THE COURSE NUMBER AND -->
<!-- SHOULD COINCIDE WITH THE NUMBER LISTED IN -->
<!-- THE COURSE.HTM FILE -->


<A NAME="101"></A>
<H3>101 Physics for Poets and Non-Poets 4</H3>

<P> Physics and physical concepts, including motion, heat energy, acoustics,
electricity and magnetism, modern physics, nuclear physics, and light.  For non-science majors. 
Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.  
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:High school algebra.
Classified: T. Meets- MNO.  Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME=" 105"></A>
<H3>105 Fundamentals of Physics I 4</H3>

<P>A beginning course in physics without calculus.  Designed to give a general
understanding of the basic principles of physics.  Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: High school algebra.  Classified:
T.  Meets: MNO.  Scheduled Fall, yearly.</A>



<A NAME="106"></A>
<H3>106 Fundamentals of Physics II 4</H3>

<P>A continuation of Phys 105.  Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.  
<A HREF="/ademic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 105. 
Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>


<A NAME="201 "></A>
<H3>201 Introduction to Physics  I 5</H3>

<P>A basic course in physics for science majors.  Especially recommended for those
majoring in biology, chemistry, computer science, engineering, mathematics, and pre-med. 
Lecture 4 hours; lab 3 hours.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Math 130, 231.  Classified: T. Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>



<A NAME="202"></A>
<H3>202 Introduction to Physics II 5 </H3>

<P>A continuation of Phys 201.  Lecture 4 hours; lab 3 hours. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 201. Classified: T. Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>


<A NAME="205"></A>
<H3>205 Engineering Statics and Dynamics 4</H3>

<P>Analysis of systems of equilibrium forces.  Vector algebra.  Resultant of force
systems.  Free body analysis.  First and second moments of inertia.  Kinematics and
kinematics of translation, rotation, and plane motion.  Introduction  to vibrations.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 201, Math 232.  Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A>



<A NAME="305"></A>
<H3>305 Thermodynamics 4</H3>

<P>Study of the First and Second laws of Thermodynamics as applied to thermal,
mechanical and fluid systems. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 202, Math 232, CS
252/270.  Meets: MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A>



<A NAME="309"></A>
<H3>309 Mechanics 4</H3>

<P>Dynamics of particles, rigid bodies and continual, normal modes, LaGrangian
and Hamiltonian formulations. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 202, Math 232.  Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A>



<A NAME="313"></A>
<H3>313 Modern Physics 4</H3>

<P>A unified treatment of quanta, photons, electrons, atoms, molecules, matter,
nuclei and particles.  Quantum mechanics will be developed at the start and used to
link and explain older and newer experimental phenomena of modern physics. 
Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 202, Math 306. 
Classified: T. Meets: MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A>




<A NAME="315"></A>
<H3>315 Atomic and Nuclear Physics 4</H3>

<P>Elementary particles, radioactivity, atomic models, Bohr's theory of atomic
structure, elementary wave mechanics, quantum theory of solids, properties of
atomic nuclei, nuclear structure and transformers, nuclear instruments and
experimental methods. 
 <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 308, Math 306.  Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A.



<A NAME="317"></A>
<H3>317 Introduction to Quantum Mechanics 4</H3>

<P>The basic concepts of quantum theory which underlie modern theories of the
properties of materials.  Topics covered include elements of atomic and nuclear theory;
kinetic theory of statistical mechanics; quantum theory and simple applications; atomic
spectra and atomic structure; molecular structure and chemical bonding. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 309, Math 306.  Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A>



<A NAME="328"></A>
<H3>328 Electromagnetics 4</H3>

<P>Electric and potential fields due to static charge distributions, concepts of vector
analysis, capacitance.  The magnetic field with applications to magnetic force and
inductance.  Maxwell's equations applied to elementary problems of engineering
significance such as plane waves, radiation, wave guides, cavities, and transmission
lines. 
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Physics 202, Math 306.  Meets:
MNO.  Scheduled on request.</A>



<A NAME="330"></A>
<H3>330 Introduction to Solid State Physics 4</H3>

<P>Bonding and structure of crystals, energy bands in insulators, semiconductors and
metals, electrical conductivity, optical properties, lattice vibrations, elasticity, point
defects, and dislocations.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">  PRQ: Physics 201, 202.  Meets: MNO. 
Scheduled on request.</A>

                               <HR>
<A HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/welcome.html">
Return to the Rockford College Home Page.</A> <HR>
