<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biology Detailed Course Descriptions</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">                      
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College<BR>
Department of Biology</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Detailed Course Descriptions</H2>
<HR>


<A NAME="100"></A>
<H3>100   Biology of the Human Experience       4</H3>
<p>An introduction to principles of biology as they relate to the human organism. Special emphasis is placed on how
humans function, their relationship to the environment, how they acquire hereditary traits and how these traits express
themselves. This course combines traditional introductory topics with current issues of great human interest and
concern, with special appeal to students majoring in the social sciences, language and literature and the arts. Lecture
3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Classified: T. Meets: M. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A> 

<A NAME="101"></A>
<H3>101   Principles of Biology              4</H3>
<p>Basic concepts concerning living organisms as objects which grow, metabolize, reproduce, and interact with other
organisms. Topics include cell biology, genetics, ecology, evolution, and physiology. Laboratory experiments will be
conducted which gather data for subsequent analysis and interpretation. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None;
high school chemistry recommended. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="102"></A>
<H3>102   Plant Biology               4</H3>
<p>An introduction to principles of biology as related to the photosynthetic organisms of the Kingdom Monera, Protesta
and Planta, as well as the non-photosynthetic Kingdom Fungi. Lecture-discussions concentrate on plant chemistry,
physiology, reproduction, growth, taxonomy, genetics, anatomy and structural diversity through a survey of
photosynthetic organisms. Laboratory investigations include some data-generating experiments along with direct
observations of plant structures and the various divisions of photosynthetic organisms. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours.
<A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>


<A NAME="103"></A>
<H3>103   Animal Biology                   4</H3>
<p>Examines diversity of form and function within the animal kingdom through a review of all phyla of animals with
living representatives. In addition, animals will be viewed in light of earth history. Detailed investigations of the
function of most organ systems. Lab includes dissecting preserved animals and some experimentation (animal
behavior). Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="120"></A>
<H3>120 Concepts in Biology                  3</H3>
<p>An introduction to principles of biological science with an emphasis on cellular and organismic biology. Most
disciplines in biology will be surveyed. Emphasis is on features of living things which distinguish them from non-living.
Topics will include cell biology, genetics, physiology, ecology and evolution. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: M. Scheduled:
Summer, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="125"></A>
<H3>125   Aquatic Ecosystems                  3</H3>
<p>A summer session course that introduces the student to biological principles as they apply to freshwater habitats.
Students study the types of organisms and life habitats on lake and stream systems and the interrelationships of these
organisms and their environment. Includes field sampling methods, lab identification, and lab analysis methods. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:
None. Meets: M. Scheduled: Summer, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="128"></A>
<H3>128   Women's Health: Biology and Beyond          3</H3>
<p>The structure and functioning of the female body. Adaptations to normal physiological events (menstruation, sexual
and reproductive activity, menopause) and responses to selected disease processes are covered. Biopsychosocial issues
pertinent to women's health and functioning in society and women's relationships as clients and practitioners in the
health care system. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Meets: M. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="209"></A>
<H3>209   Anatomy and Physiology                                     4</H3>
<p>(XL: PE 209) An introduction to the basic principles of human anatomy and physiology. Gross anatomy will include
skeletal, muscular, cardiovascular, respiratory, gastrointestinal, renal, and nervous systems. Microscopic anatomy will
also be covered and will focus on the structure of both cells and tissues. Laboratory work will include the dissection
of preserved specimens such as cats, and the use of a prosected cadaver, and various organs. Lecture 3 hours: lab 3
hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None. Classified: T. Meets: M. Scheduled: Spring, yearly. </A>

<A NAME="210"></A>
<H3>210   Environmental Biology                                      3</H3>
<p>Provides a basic understanding of biologically significant problems in our environment. Through lecture-discussion,
lecture-demonstration, and outside reading, students become aware of these problems and their importance, of some
of the proposed solutions, and how he or she can help alleviate these problems. Lecture plus lab. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: None.
Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years. </A>
 
<A NAME="222"></A>
<H3>222   Pharmacology                                               2</H3>
<p>Major categories of drugs, focusing on their therapeutic actions and interactions at the systems and cellular levels.
Knowledge of pharmacologic concepts and the role of drugs in health restoration, maintenance, and illness prevention
provides a foundation for participation in drug therapy. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 132 or 205. Meets: M. Scheduled: Spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="230"></A>
<H3>230   Principles of Nutrition                                    3</H3>
<p>An introduction to the composition of nutrients, metabolism, dietary guidelines, nutrition for various age groups, and
basic principles are emphasized. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Chem 132 or 205. Meets: M. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="300"></A>
<H3>300   Comparative Anatomy and Embryology I                       4</H3>
<p>The principles of early vertebrate morphogenesis, establishment of vertebrate body form, and the principles of
organogenesis. The early history of vertebrates is examined in phylogenetic (earth history) time, as well. Early
morphogenetic events such as gametogenesis, fertilization, cleavage and development of primitive body form will be
examined. The adult morphology of certain systems, particularly sense organs and the nervous system, will be
examined. Dissection of an adult shark will be included in the laboratory. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 103
or its equivalent. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Yearly.</A>

<A NAME="301"></A>
<H3>301   Comparative Anatomy and Embryology II                      4</H3>
<p>The evolution (phylogeny) and ontogeny of selected organ systems from earliest embryonic primordial to adult
morphology. Evolutionary trends and adaptive variations amongst vertebrate groups will be discussed. Systems will
include integumentary, skeletomuscular, cardiovascular, respiratory, endocrine, and urogenital. Dissection of an adult
cat. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 103 or its equivalent; Bio 300 recommended. Classified: Y. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Yearly.</A>
 
<A NAME="305"></A>
<H3>305   Evolution                                                  3</H3>
<p>Theories and principles used to explain the mechanics through which present forms of life have developed and are
continuing to develop. Topics include the origin of life, speciation, transspecific evolution, evolutionary genetics and
the ecology of evolution. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101, plus 102 or 103; Bio 309 recommended. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall,
odd years. </A>
 
<A NAME="306"></A>
<H3>306   Mammalogy                                                 4 </H3>
<p>An in-depth look at the biology of vertebrates of the Class Mammalia, including a critical review of the phylogenetic
history of various groups of mammals, as well as the various interpretations of the fossil record of mammals in the
Mesozoic. The main theme is a view of mammals as they represent (as a group) a particular adaptive mode. The
reasons for particular success (or lack thereof) of certain orders or families, etc., of recent mammals will be
considered. Other topics include behavior, communication, ecology, navigation and migration, zoogeography,
locomotion, reproduction, and rare and endangered species. A trip to the Field Museum and several laboratory
projects are planned. Preparation of museum specimens and museum technique will be reviewed. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 103.
Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A>

<A NAME="308"></A>
<H3>308   Microbiology                                               4</H3>
<p>A study of the classification, morphology, physiology, epidemiology, and control of micro-organisms with emphasis
upon bacteria. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101 or 209; Chem 105 and 106 recommended. Classified: T.
Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, yearly. </A>
 
<A NAME="309"></A>
<H3>309   Genetics                                                   3</H3>
<p>A thorough study of the Mendelian laws of genetics and patterns of inheritance. The molecular basis of biological
inheritance, gene manipulation, and DNA analysis is also covered. Three hours of lecture/discussion per week. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ:
Bio 101, plus 102 or 103; Intro to Chemistry recommended. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A> 

<A NAME="310"></A>
<H3>310   Cellular Physiology                                        4</H3>
<p>The study of cellular function and structure, with emphasis on the biochemical nature of cellular physiology. Topics
include cellular energy production, DNA expression and control, cellular organelles, cellular locomotion, and cell
division. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101; Chem 205 and 206 recommended. Classified: T. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Spring, odd years.</A>

<A NAME="314"></A>
<H3>314   Vertebrate Physiology                                      4</H3>
<p>A comprehensive study of the physiological systems of vertebrates, including measurement and analysis of biological
data from physiological and biochemical preparations. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 103 or 209 plus Chem
205 and 206 or 131 and 132 or concurrent enrollment. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, yearly.</A> 

<A NAME="321"></A>
<H3>321   Ecology                                                    4</H3>
<p>A study of reciprocal relationships between animals and plants and their environment with respect to individuals,
populations, communities and ecosystems. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101. Classified: T. Meets: MNO.
Scheduled: Fall, odd years.</A> 
 
<A NAME="325"></A>
<H3>325   Aquatic Biology                                            4</H3>
<p>A survey and study of different types of freshwater systems, the types of organisms found in these different systems,
the various life habitats in each system, the interrelationships between the different organisms and their environment,
and factors which limit the activity of these organisms. Laboratory work will include field sampling methods and
analysis as well as lab analysis methods. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A> 
 
<A NAME="330"></A>
<H3>330   Animal Behavior                                            3</H3>
<p>This course is an introduction to the biological study of animal behavior with emphasis on its adaptive nature. A
consideration of scientific methodology as applied to animal behavior studies is included. Assignments include readings
in the primary and secondary literature. The course includes a class field trip to a zoo and an independent project
involving animal observations. Three hours of lecture per week. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101; Bio 103 recommended. Meets: MNO.</A>

<A NAME="340"></A>
<H3>340   Endocrinology                                              4</H3>
<p>Hormonal control of metabolism, growth and reproduction. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101; Chem
131,132 or Chem 205; Bio 314 recommended. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Spring, even years.</A> 

<A NAME="342"></A>
<H3>342   Principles of Electronic Instrumentation                   4</H3>
<p>An introduction into basic semiconductor electronics followed by an analysis of the basic types of modular
components common to all types of electronic instrumentation. Lecture 3 hours; lab 3 hours. <A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Bio 101 and high
school or college physics. Classified: T. Meets: MNO. Scheduled: Fall, even years.</A> 

<A NAME="350"></A>
<H3>350   Advanced Topics in Plant Biology                           4</H3>
<p>Offered to meet specific student needs, including such topics as plant anatomy, plant physiology and plant taxonomy.

<A NAME="351"></A>
<H3>351   Advanced Topics in Animal Biology                          4</H3>
<p>Offered to meet specific student needs, including such topics as comparative animal physiology, physiological ecology
and neurophysiology.

<A NAME="371"></A>
<H3>371   Undergraduate Research                                   1-2</H3>
<A NAME="372"></A>
<H3>372   Undergraduate Research                                   1-2</H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent of department chair.  Scheduled: Fall and spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="398"></A>
<H3>398   Internship: Biology                                      1-8</H3>

<A NAME="399"></A>
<H3>399   Internship: Biology                                      1-8</H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Consent.  Classified: 1.  Meets: NO.  Does not meet: DM.  Scheduled:
Fall, spring, and summer, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="495a"></A>
<H3>495A Senior Seminar (Research)                                  2 </H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Sr. Classified: 1Z. Meets: N. Does not meet: O. Scheduled: Fall and
spring, yearly.</A>

<A NAME="495b"></A>
<H3>495B Senior Seminar (Discussion)                                 2</H3>
<p><A HREF="/academic/catalog/codes.htm">PRQ: Sr. Classified: 1Y. Meets: N. Does not meet: O. Scheduled: Spring,
yearly.</A> 


