<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biology</TITLE>
<BASE HREF="http://www.rockford.edu/">                      

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H1>Rockford College<BR>
Department of Biology</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Index</H2>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/biology/biology.htm#faculty">
Faculty</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/biology/biology.htm#overview">
Overview</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/biology/biology.htm#career">
Career Opportunities</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/biology/biology.htm#require">
Requirements</A>
<LI><A HREF="/academic/catalog/biology/courses.htm">
Course Offerings</A>
</UL>
<HR>

<A NAME="faculty"></A>
<H3>Faculty</H3>

<PRE>
Dr. David D. Pippitt, Chair    Dr. A. Leon Carley
Dr. G. Lawrence Forman         Dr. Martha Pippitt
</PRE>


<A NAME="overview"></A>
<H3>Overview</H3>

<PRE>
  The effects of oil spills on ecology, deforestation of tropical rain 
forests, biological effects of the hole in the ozone layer, and rapid 
advances in medicine and pharmacology consistently make headlines and are 
some of the concerns of biologists in today's world. As human understanding
of the self and the surrounding world has expanded, we have begun to 
understand the importance of the organisms that inhabit the world in which 
we endeavor to survive.
  Work in the various areas that make up biology (environment, agriculture,
forestry, wildlife management, aquatic biology, medicine, pharmacology, 
molecular biology, etc.) requires highly educated and curious individuals
with backgrounds in the liberal arts, business, chemistry, physics, 
mathematics, and the life sciences. 
  Rockford College biology majors have the opportunity to develop an area of
interest from a variety of disciplines and one day may make significant
contributions to their fields. 
  The Department of Biology offers both the Bachelor of Arts and
Bachelor of Science degrees in biology. 
</PRE>

<A NAME="career"></A>
<H3>Career opportunities</H3>

<PRE>
  Biology graduates have numerous career opportunities in government, such
as wildlife management and environmental research. Private industry uses
trained biologists in areas such as sales, management, research, and
writing. Many additional possibilities exist in the areas of medicine,
medical science, and allied health.  Many of our graduates have chosen 
to continue their education in biology at the graduate school level.
</PRE>

<A NAME="require"></A>
<H3>Degree requirements</H3> 

<PRE>
  Bio 309 Genetics, Bio 305 Evolution, and Bio 314 Physiology are highly
recommended for all majors.
  
<STRONG>Major requirements (B.A.) -- 32 hours</STRONG>
Bio 101 Principles of Biology                    4 hours
Bio 102 Plant Biology                            4 hours
Bio 103 Animal Biology                           4 hours
Bio 495 Senior Seminar                           4 hours
Additional 200- 300- and 400-level courses      16 hours

<STRONG>Supporting requirements (B.A.) -- 25-28 hours</STRONG>
Chem 105 General Chemistry I                     4 hours
Chem 106 General Chemistry II                    4 hours
Chem 205 Organic Chemistry I                     4 hours
Chem 206 Organic Chemistry II                    4 hours
Phys 105 Fundamentals of Physics and     
 Phys 106 Fundamentals of Physics   }            8 hours
{     or Phys 201 Introduction to Physics        5 hours
Math 230 Calculus with Analytic Geometry I or
Math 224 Elements of Statistics     }            4 hours

<STRONG>Major requirements (B.S.) -- 44 hours</STRONG>
 All major and supporting requirements for the B.A. degree and 12 hours
from the following:

Bio 300 Comparative Anatomy & Embryology I or
Bio 301 Comparative Anatomy & Embryology II   }  4 hours
Bio 306 Mammalogy                                4 hours
Bio 308 Microbiology                             4 hours
Bio 330 Animal Behavior                          4 hours
Bio 340 Endocrinology                            4 hours
Bio 342 Principles of Electronic Instrumentation 4 hours
Bio 350 Advanced Topics in Plant Biology         4 hours
Bio 351 Advanced Topics in Animal Biology        4 hours
Math 231 Calculus w/Analytic Geometry II         4 hours
Math 232 Calculus w/Analytic Geometry III        4 hours
Chem 301 Analytical Chemistry                    4 hours
Chem 302 Instrumental Methods of Analysis        4 hours
Chem 305 Physical Chemistry I                    4 hours
Chem 308 Biochemistry                            4 hours
Psych 212 Biopsychology                          4 hours
Computer Science                               2-6 hours

<STRONG>Minor in Biology -- 23 hours</STRONG>
Bio 101 Principles of Biology                    4 hours
Bio 102 Plant Biology                            4 hours
Bio 103 Animal Biology                           4 hours
Bio 309 Genetics                                 4 hours
Two additional 300-level courses in biology 7 to 8 hours

<STRONG>Teacher certification 6-12</STRONG>
Students interested in becoming certified to teach Biology at the secondary
level must complete all Biology major degree requirements, a minor in 
secondary education, and additional general education requirements for
state certification.  For further information, see the Education section
of this catalog.
</PRE>

<HR>
