<A NAME="GENERAL-INTEREST"><H2>GENERAL INTEREST MYSTERY RESOURCES</H2></A>

<A NAME="Gen-A"><H2>A: GENERAL INTEREST</H2> MYSTERY RESOURCES</A>
<A HREF="http://www.ambook.org/bookweb/btw/current/aot">ABA list of Author Tours</A>, 
<A HREF="http://www.nps.gov/alcatraz">Alcatraz</A>, a virtual tour of The Rock
<A HREF="http://www.xensei.com/users/hubcom/police.htm">American Police Hall of Fame and Museum</A>, new
<A HREF="http://sun.soci.niu.edu/~asc/">American Society of Criminology</A>, homepage
<A HREF="http://www.emergency.com/antipolc.htm">"Anti-Police Site"</A>, a.k.a Police Accountability Site
<A HREF="http://www.art.net/Links/litref.html">Art.Net's Online Literature References</A>
<A HREF="http://www.azstarnet.com/~poewar/writer/associations.html">Associations and Organizations of Interest to Writers</A>, currently limited to the U.S., but growing
<A HREF="http://www.imt.net/~gedison/bookbind.html">Authors: Info About</A>, from BookBinders 

<A NAME="Gen-B"><H2>B: GENERAL INTEREST</H2> MYSTERY RESOURCES</A>
<A HREF="http://www.columbia.edu/~sv12/bartlett/">Bartlett's Quotations</A>, Sprinkle these through your writing to look better-read
<A HREF="http://www.greyware.com/bfob/default.htm">Basement Full of Books</A>		
<A HREF="http://www.armory.com/~dstar/write.html">Bay Area Writers Groups</A>, San Francisco
<A HREF="ftp://ftp.std.com/pub/jwenn">Bibliographies</A>
<A HREF="http://s14.bigyellow.com/">Big Yellow</A>, to find companies anywhere in the U.S.
<A HREF="http://www.shadow.net/~noslow/index.html">Blood Splatter Analysis</A>: visit a simulated scene-of-the-crime
<A HREF="http://www.greatworld.com/public/bhound.htm">Bloodhound</A>, for sniffing people out on the internet
<A HREF="http://www.imt.net/~gedison/bookbind.html">BookBinder</A>, information about authors 
<A HREF="http://www.xs4all.nl/~pwessel/">Booklovers: Fine Books and Literature</A>
<A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/bell/review/mystery/index.shtml">Book Reviews</A>, Ed's Internet Book Reviews of Mysteries/Detective 
<A HREF="http://freenet.vcu.edu/education/literature/mwa.html">Books in Print: Mystery Writers of America</A>, not quite up-to-date, but useful
<A HREF="http://www.ambook.org/l">BookWeb</A>, some authors (or their publishers)
     pay to have their book tours listed here 

<A NAME="Gen-C"><H2>C: GENERAL INTEREST</H2> MYSTERY RESOURCES</A>
<A HREF="http://ally.ios.com/~cipi19">California Institute for Professional Investigators</A>
<A HREF="http://members.gnn.com/MGrost/casebook.htm">Casebook Fiction</A> Crime Fiction subgenre
<A HREF="http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu:80/jod/texts/classical.mysteries">Classical Mysteries (Ancient Rome)</A>
<A HREF="http://www.freenet.msp.mn.us/people/norstrem/coplinks.htm">Cop Link</A>, for personal web pages of police
<A HREF="http://police.sas.ab.ca/">Cop Net</A> 
     lists 150+ police departments and law enforcement 
     agencies worldwide (check out Pasadena)
<A HREF="http://www.teleport.com/~peterc">Computer Data Investigators</A>, can get stuff from crashed hard drives
<A HREF="http://www.benedict.com/index.html">The Copyright Website</A>, see also the National Writers Union, 
     which has advice on copyrights in Cyberspace
<A HREF="http://CAPITALNET.com/~reci/crimel.html">Crimelinks</A>
<A HREF="http://www.swifty.com/cwc/cwchome.htm">Crime Writers of Canada</A>
<A HREF="http://www.db.dk/dbaa/jbs/cws.htm">Crime Writers of Scandinavia</A> 
<A HREF="http://www.stpt.usf.edu/~greek/cj.html">Criminal Justice Resources on the Web</A>, perhaps the definitive site
<A HREF="http://broadway.vera.org/pub/ocjs.tes.html">Criminal Justice Links</A>, some overlap with above
<A HREF="http://www.isdoj.gov/criminal-justice-link.html">Criminal Justice Links -- Dept. of Justice</A>
<A HREF="http://sun.soci.niu.edu/~critcrim/">Critical Criminology</A>, courtesy of American Society of Criminology

<A NAME="Gen-D"><H2>D: GENERAL INTEREST</H2> MYSTERY RESOURCES</A>
<A HREF="http://www.vifp.monash.edu.au/people/davidrex.html/">David Ranson's Explorer Page</A> 
     he'll lead you to DeathNet and TraumaNet...
<A HREF="http://www.usdoj.gov/dea/dea-home.html/">DEA</A> 
     But for significant crime data, see instead the Bureau of Justice at 
     gopher://justice2.usdoj.gov:70/1/ojp/bjs
<A HREF="http://www.investigator.com/din">Detective Information Network</A>
<A HREF="http://c/gp.cs.cmu.edu:5103/prog/webster?">Webster's Dictionary</A>, by definition...
<A HREF="http://members.gnn.com/MGrost/doyleera.htm">The Doyle Era</A> Crime Fiction subgenre

<A NAME="Gen-E"><H2>E: GENERAL INTEREST</H2> MYSTERY RESOURCES</A>
<A HREF="http://www.clark.net/pub/bell/review/mystery/index.shtml">Ed's Internet Book Review</A>, Mysteries/Detective 
<A HREF="http://www.columbia.edu/~sv12/strunk/">The Elements of Style</A>, by Struunk & White.  Learn to write real good.

<A NAME="Gen-F"><H2>F: GENERAL INTEREST</H2> MYSTERY RESOURCES</A>
<A HREF="http://www.fbi.gov/">FBI</A> Note the FAQ, Ten Most Wanted, and 
     monthly bulletin
<A HREF="http://eden.telalink.net/zoomst/copcars/copcars.html">Five Oh!</A> describes marked and 
     unmarked police cars
<A HREF="http://www.soton.ac.uk/~jb3/index1.html/">Forensic Archaeology</A>
     you'll need their permission to view human remains graphics 
<A HREF="http://www/uio.no/~mostarke/forens_ent/forensic_entomology.html">Forensic Entomology</A> 
     time of death by maggots
<A HREF="http://www.pds.med.umich.edu/users/amp/path_resources.html">Forensic Medicine and Pathology Sites</A>
<A HREF="http://somt.nu.edu/~jdavis/Forensics/Forensicnet.html">Forensic Psychiatry</A>, they're crazy about this one...
