<A NAME="COUNTRIES-AUSTRALIA"><STRONG><H3>AUSTRALIA</H3></STRONG></A>
Australia is a major player in the world of Science Fiction, Fantasy, and 
Horror.  "A Checklist of Australia Fantasy" by S. L. Lanarch (Sydney, 
Futurian Press, 1950) has a good outline through about 1938.

A more comprehensive Australian bibliography by Sean McMullen is available 
on the Web:
     <A HREF="http://www.midnight.com.au/eidolon/">Sean McMullen's Australian Bibliography</A>

19th Century Australian science fiction seemed, to this compiler, to 
heavily feature "Lost Land" and "Yellow Peril" subgenres.

Erle Cox was the best-known author of the 1920s, especially for "Out of the 
Silence" (1925).  

In the 1930s and early 1940s, a number of authors rose to prominence:
     A. Connell
     B. C. Cronin 
     J. Heming
     Vol Molesworth.  
     
In the late 1940s and 1950s, writers of note appeared, including:
     F. Bryning
     N. Heming
     Wynne Whiteford

The 1960's brought to notice:
     John Baxter
     Damien Broderick
     R. Braddon
     F. Cusak

Some of its best-known authors at some point emigrated to Great Britain, 
including:
     G. Boothby
     F. Hume
     V. Knowles
     J. M. Walsh

Current authors include:    
<A HREF="http://www.magicdragon.com/chrissie.html">Christine Carmichael</A>	
     Arguably the world's leading female scientist/Science Fiction author.
     Ph.D. in Solid State Physics (University of New South Wales, Sydney, 
     Australia), M.Sc. University of Edinburgh, great-grandniece of Sir 
     Walter Scott, who invented the historical novel and was an important 
     early anthologist of fantasy poetry
<A HREF="mailto:jpost@earthlink.net">e-mail Christine Carmichael</A>
Jack Dann (Jack Mayo Dann): no known home page, but CompuServe e-mail
<A HREF="http://www.Catch22.COM/SF/ARB/SFD/Dann,Jack.html">Jack Dann</A> @ AlphaRalpha
<A HREF="http://cu-online.com/avon-bin/exact_author?Jack Dann">Jack Dann: Index to at least 73 publications</A>
Stephen Dedman (Australia): nothing on the Web?
Terry Dowling (Australia): nothing on the Web?
Greg Egan
     John H. Campbell Award, 1995
     <A HREF="mailto:egan@perth.dialix.oz.au">e-mail Greg Egan</A> 
Lee Harding, major SF photographer/journalist/author in Australia, 
     also as "Leo" Harding, cofounder of "Australian Science Fiction 
     Review" (1966-Present)
Sue Isle: no known home page
     <A HREF="mailto:sue@perv.metapro.dialix.oz.au">e-mail Sue Isle</A>
Rosaleen Love
     <A HREF="mailto:lovrl@cougar.vut.edu.au">e-mail Rosaleen Love</A>, Australia
Sean McMullen, of Melbourne, Australia: noted bibliographer/critic/author
     whose 3rd book won Australia's national SF award in 1996.  Besides
     writing and rasing a family, Sean is a Senior IT Officer for the 
     Systems Planning Department of the Bureau of Meteorology, and the 
     Examiner of his Karate club.
     <A HREF="http://www.midnight.com.au/eidolon/02_mcmul/sm_home.htm">Sean McMullen</A>
     <A HREF="http://www.maths.uts.edu.au/eric/ain99/ozwriter/mcmullen.htm.htm">Sean McMullen</A>
     <A HREF="mailto:scm@bom.gov.au">e-mail Sean McMullen</A>, Australia
George Turner: no known home page
James Verran: no known home page
Wynne Noel Whiteford: no known home page
Sean Williams: no known home page

Magazines include:
     American Science Fiction, Australia (Jun 1952-Sep 1955): nothing on the Web?
     Future Science Fiction: nothing on the Web?
     Popular Science Fiction: nothing on the Web?
     The Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction (Quarterly): nothing on the Web?
     Science Fiction Monthly: nothing on the Web?
     Thrills Incorporated: nothing on the Web?
     Vision: nothing on the Web?

<A HREF="http://www.cs.latrobe.edu.au/~agapow/Postviews//">Post Views: Australian experts review SF movies</A>

Australia, by the way, is one of the 16 countries that accesses the 
Magic Dragon web domain every day (or almost every day). 
Australia first "hit" this domain in April 1996.

