<A NAME="COUNTRIES-BRAZIL"><STRONG><H3>BRAZIL</H3></STRONG></A>
According to the "Sao Paulo Letter" of Walter Martins (Amazing Stories, 
Sep 1968), Brazilian science fiction was triggered by Portugese 
translations of Jules Verne in the early 1900s, and H. G. Wells in the 
1930s.

In the 1930s, a Brazilian equivalent of Tarzan appeared: "Terramarear."  
There were also Emilio Salgari's fantastic pirate stories, and space 
fiction by J. Aragon and Gustav Le Rouge.

In the 1950s there was a groundbreaking anthology, "Wonders of Science 
Fiction" edited by Mario da Silva Brito, featuring American authors.
The popularity of this led to the "Colecao Argonauta" series of paperbacks.

Several publishing houses print science fiction, including:
     Cia. Editora Nacional
     Gertrum Carbeiro
     Edameris
     GRD
     Edart
     Von Schmidt
     Brasiliense
     Saraiva
     4 Artes

Brazilian authors include:
     Fausto Cunha
     Clovis Garcia
     Nilson Martello
     Jeronimo Monteiro (also a Mystery/Detective author)
     Dinah Silviera de Queroz

There is one Brazilian member of Science Fiction & Fantasy Writers of 
America: 
     Andre Carniero: nothing on the Web?

Magazines include:
     Galaxia 2000

Brazil, by the way, is one of the 8 countries that accesses the 
Magic Dragon web domain often, at least 10-20 days per month on the average. 
Brazil first "hit" this domain in March 1996.

