<BR><HR><BR>


<CENTER><H1>VTI's Unique Process</H1></CENTER>
<BR><BR>
<OL>

<CENTER>
<H2>The 5 classes of problems and how VTI solves them</H2>
</CENTER>

<BR><BR><BR>
<LI><STRONG>Solve Technical Problems.</STRONG>  VTI's network of scientists and engineers can 
solve problems that you may be having with your new or existing products 
or processes.  The solution may consist of theoretical, analytical, system 
design, detailed design, feasibility demonstration or prototype fabrication 
and testing.  Sometimes groups of technologist together can conceive of 
solutions to a problem that a lesser group could not.  Such a process is 
sometimes referred to as revolutionary-system-engineering.  Most companies 
are able to perform evolutionary-system-engineering, sometimes called 
"step-by-step development".  VTI can assist in solving specific problems 
that arise in disciplines that are not available to clients own 
technologists.  VTI technologists are skilled in capturing the 
intellectual property rights that may issue from such solutions.</LI>  
<BR><BR>
<LI><STRONG>Invent New Products or Processes.</STRONG>  In many instances 
VTI's technologists 
can invent new or improved products or processes that maintain a company's 
intellectual-property-monopoly position in the market. </LI> 
<BR><BR>
<LI><STRONG>Invent Around or Beyond Competitor's Patents.</STRONG> They can invent 
improvements based upon new technology not known at the time the previous 
patents were filed. </LI>  
<BR><BR>
<LI><STRONG>Find Patent Prior Art.</STRONG>  They can find prior art that can not be found by 
conventional searches and investigations by using technologists that find 
and consult with other technologists that may have special knowledge.  </LI>
<BR><BR>
<LI><STRONG>Evaluates Patents.</STRONG> They can provide independent technical evaluations of 
patents and/or suites of patents by technologists skilled in the art of 
the particular science or engineering discipline. </LI> 
</OL>
<BR><HR>
<BR><BR>

<CENTER><H2><STRONG>VTI's Unique Capabilities</STRONG></H2></CENTER>
<BR><BR>

<H2><STRONG>VTI's Technologists Do It Themselves.</STRONG></H2>
<P> VTI and its pool of independent 
consulting technologists (scientists and engineers) have developed a 
unique process to solving the five classes of problems listed above.  One 
or more of this unique network, of 85 technologists, may already be the 
best available technologist and may know how to solve the problem.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>VTI's Technologists Find Other More Skilled.</STRONG>  But usually, they locate
 a specific technologist by calling other technologists that they 
already know that may be sufficiently skilled in the discipline.  
Sometimes they search for specific authors of technical papers, articles 
or patents that they find in libraries and computer data bases.  The VTI 
scientist or engineer communicates with the specific technologist in his or 
her native language and in the language of the technology.  There is 
usually a trade of information between both technologists.  Such 
technologists are more willing to communicate under such circumstances.  If 
some work is involved, the new technologist is offered a fixed fee or an 
hourly rate with a not-to-exceed-limit.  Such rates and limits are 
pre-approved by the client.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Nondisclosure Agreement.</STRONG>  VTI's or the client's nondisclosure agreement 
should be used when business or technically sensitive information (the 
nature of the problem) is to be communicated between the parties.  
Business information should not be communicated without a good reason, and 
if communicated, it should be limited to the specific information on a 
need to know basis.  Technical information is almost always sensitive, and 
should be protected for two reasons.  Technical information can give 
competitors an advantage immediately.  Not identifying sensitive technical 
information that may lead to the development of intellectual property in 
the form of a patent may jeopardize the patent in the future.  One of the 
ways a patent can be challenged is by showing that the concept was made 
public before the patent was filed.  A nondisclosure agreement signed by 
the technologists that received the information that specifically 
identified the concept is the best protection.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Coordinators.</STRONG>  VTI's coordinator works with the client's coordinator, they 
handle the programmatic (non-technical) parts of the relationship; 
nondisclosure agreement, statement of work, and billing.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Statement of Work & PERT Charts.</STRONG>  The statement of work may be a simple 
description of the task, milestones, deliverables, cost and completion 
date.  The SoW may require a more complete definition of the task in the 
form of a set of PERT charts.  These standard task planning charts allow 
the scheduling and resources of a task to be dynamically integrated.  
Their best use is in updating the charts and using them to inform all 
parties as to the changes and consequences of the changes.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Task Manager & Monitor.</STRONG>  VTI's task manager works with the client's task 
monitor, they handle the technical parts of the relationship; statement of 
work, problem definition and solution design and reports.  Depending on 
which of the 5 classes of problems, the problem solution and reports are 
designed to fit.  
<BR><HR><BR>
