<BR><HR><BR>

<H1>VTI Remuneration for Services </H1> 
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Fees for Services.</STRONG>  VTI bills the client for the total of hourly cost and 
out-of-pocket expenses of each independent technologists and for the 
hourly cost and out-of-pocket expenses of the owners of VTI.  These 
management and marketing costs are itemized in the same way the 
technologist's invoices are handled.  Technologists with advanced degrees 
command about $100 per hour.  Technicians, searchers, librarians and are 
paid less.  The basis for payment of hourly rates is 150% of burdened cost 
to his or her employer.  Weekends, evenings and leave time should be paid 
as if it is a form of overtime, and since the consultant is an 
independent 1099 self employed consultant that must maintain his or her 
tools and office, such rates are justified.  As such consulting work is 
discontinuous these cost are justified.  The client saves in the end 
because the client does not have to support such expensive technologists 
after the task is competed.   
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Itemized Billing and Reporting.</STRONG>  Each technologist must submit an itemized 
bill/invoice and a report that clearly describes the work that was 
performed for the client.  The date, location, tasks performed and time 
and expenses spent must be contemporaneously recorded.  An example is set 
forth below.  These invoices/reports may be sent to the client as reports 
only and at the end of the problem solving task they can be re submitted 
as part of a VTI Summary Invoice.  The client can have the reporting and 
billing in any way they choose.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>No Payment to VTI by Consultants.</STRONG>  The independent consulting 
technologists do not pay a percentage of their hourly costs to VTI.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Ringer Award.</STRONG>  If the technologists finds prior art that is used in a 
patent infringement settlement or judgement, the technologist must be paid 
$1000 in addition to his or her fees for the time expended.  Such awards 
motivate the searcher to examine each useful document completely.  
Searching literature and patents with understanding of the technology 
requires some real incentive over and above the hourly rate.  For most 
very intelligent technologists, searching through literature by hand or by 
aid of computers is tedious and requires this additional incentive.  
<BR><BR>
<STRONG>Royalty for Inventors.</STRONG>  If the technologist invents a solution to the 
client's problem, the inventor must receive a reasonable royalty.  Without 
such an incentive the client may not obtain the best solution to his or 
her problem.  Like an orphaned baby, orphaned technology and especially 
intellectual property technology needs long term nurturing to obtain 
optimum long term value.  Such royalty maintains the interest of the 
technologist in obtaining and maintaining the monopoly rights in many 
ways.  Helping the patent attorney get the maximum intellectual property 
rights, creating additional suites of patents to block competitors from 
using alternative solutions and filing second and third generation patents 
using technology not yet discovered.  

