<HTML>
<TITLE>Euterpe History</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>About Euterpe Opera Theatre</H2>

<P>Euterpe Opera Theatre, founded in 1924, is now producing chamber opera. 
Our most recent production was of two comic operas, Mozart's <I>Impresario</I> 
and Pergolesi's <I>La Serva Padrona,</I> performed Jan. 8, 1995, at Van Nuys High 
School Auditorium.   In Summer, 1993, Euterpe produced Mozart's <I>Za&#239;de </I>
 at the John Anson Ford Amphitheater as part of the Summer Nights At The Ford 
Festival.  The previous year (1992), Euterpe Opera produced Haydn's 
delightful <I>Infidelity Foiled.</I>     All Euterpe Opera productions are 
dramatically staged and sung in English.</P>

<P>Euterpe Opera produced the first opera performed on the stage of the new 
Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in 1964.  Since that date, Euterpe has presented 
over 100 operas at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion.</P>

<P>Over the years many singers have benefited from the experience of taking 
part in Euterpe productions early in their career.  Euterpe alumnae and 
alumni include:  Nadine Conner, Jerome Hines, Mary Costa, Jonathan Mack,  Karen 
Armstrong, Carole Neblett, Heinz Bankenburg, and Marvelee Cariaga.</P>

<UL>

<LI>1924:	Gounod's Romeo and Juliet opened our first season.</LI>
<LI>1928:	After its third successful season, Euterpe was incorporated 
		under California Law.</LI>
<LI>1932:	Euterpe opened productions in the new Biltmore Theatre</LI>
<LI>1939:	With war on the way in Europe, Euterpe's season was devoted to
		all American operas.</LI>
<LI>1946:	National Council of Music in America honored Euterpe for 
		distinguished wartime effort for war bond sales </LI>
<LI>1951:  	Diva Mary Costa sings "Norma" in Euterpe production at the 	
		Wilshire Ebell Theatre</LI>
<LI>1960: 	Euterpe Opera presents $5000 to the Music Center, thus
		joining the Founders' Circle</LI>
<LI>1962:	Henrietta Pelta joins Euterpe as Artistic Director</LI>
<LI>1964:	Euterpe Opera produces the <STRONG>first opera</STRONG> on the stage of the
		new Dorothy Chandler Pavillion:  "La Traviata", starring 
		Marilin Niska.</LI>
<LI>1988:	Euterpe opens the '88 - 89 Season with "The Elixer of Love" 
		at the Japan America Theate.</LI>
</UL>

<HR>

For <STRONG>further information</STRONG> about Euterpe Opera,
<P>
<STRONG>
Contact </STRONG> Robert Frampton, President of Euterpe Opera Theatre.<BR>
<STRONG>Telephone:</STRONG> 818-794-7835<BR>
<STRONG>Write:</STRONG> P.O. Box 40018, Pasadena, CA. 91114.<BR>
<STRONG>E-mail:</STRONG> euterpe@mcimail.com<BR>
<!-- e-mail reference -->
<A HREF="mailto:euterpe@mcimail.com">Send e-mail to Euterpe Opera 
Theatre</A>
<P>
