<TITLE>Berlin to Broadway</TITLE>
<META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Clyde E. Collins">
<META NAME="Keywords" CONTENT="opera theatre Euterpe musical drama comedy">
<BODY>

<CENTER>
<STRONG>
<H1>Berlin To Broadway</H1>

<H2>With Kurt Weill</H2>

<H3>text and format by Gene Lerner</H3></STRONG>
</CENTER>

<P>About Berlin to Broadway...</P>
<P>"Considered by major music critics as the greatest theatre composer of 
this century, Kurt Weill has written melodies and music with the finest 
array of lyricists and poets ever to write for the theatre of the Western 
World, including Bertold Brecht, Maxwell Anderson, Paul Green, Langston 
Hughes, Ira Gershwin, Ogden Nash, Alan Jay Lerner and others.  Through his 
art and theirs, Berlin to Broadway with Kurt Weill, encompassing 40 songs, 
gives us a panorama of twenty extraordinary years--from von Hindenburg and 
Hitler in the Germany where Weill was born, to Roosevelt and Truman in the 
America to which Weill emigrated.  A musical spectacle blending cavalcade 
and cabaret, commentary and tin-pan-alley, Berlin to Broadway with Kurt 
Weill inevitably becomes a tribute to theatre itself, an entertainment in 
salute to show business."</P>

--from the original Broadway program

<UL>

<LI><A HREF="MusicalNumbers.html" TARGET="_blank">
 <STRONG>Musical Numbers</STRONG> </A><BR></LI><BR>
<LI> Production Dates (autumn of 1996)</LI><BR><BR>
<LI> Cast (auditions to be held in May of 1996)</LI><BR><BR>
<LI><A HREF="ProStaff.html"> <STRONG>Production Staff</STRONG></A></LI><BR><BR>
<LI><A HREF="Booking.html"> <STRONG>Booking Information</STRONG></A></LI><BR><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.kwf.org/">
 <STRONG>Kurt Weill</STRONG></A> and Bertold Brecht Information</LI><BR>
</UL>
