<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Euterpe 1997 Production</TITLE>
<META NAME="Author" CONTENT="Clyde E. Collins">
<META NAME="Keywords" CONTENT="opera theatre Euterpe musical comedy">
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<H2><CENTER>
1997 OPERA PRODUCTION BY <BR>
EUTERPE OPERA THEATRE
</CENTER></H2>


<CENTER>
<H3>Two One-Act Comic Operas: <BR>
"La serva padrona"   by Pergolesi<BR>
"Impresario"   by Mozart<BR>
 Offered for September thru November, 1997<BR></H3>
</CENTER>

<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="framed.html"><STRONG>Return to Euterpe home page.</STRONG></A>
</P>
</CENTER>

These two operas will be fully staged, with string quintet and piano, and sung in 
English.  
<P>
One of the works for which Giovanni Pergolesi (1710-1736) is best remembered 
is his intermezzo, <EM>La serva padrona. </EM>  Composed in 1733, the work was one of 
two intermezzi presented between the three acts of his opera seria, <EM>Il prigionier 
superbo.  La serva padrona</EM> was so well received in Italy, that it was soon 
performed in Dresden, Vienna, and Paris as well.  This lighthearted work is 
generally considered to be the beginning of the opera buffa genre.  In one act 
with two parts, the plot revolves around two characters: Serpina, a clever 
servant, and Umberto, her master.  Through her sharp wit and ingenuity, 
Serpina is able to elevate her station in life and achieve equality with her 
master.  The cast consists of soprano and baritone for the lead roles, and a non-
singing role for another servant.  
<P>
Mozart's singspiel, <EM>Der Schauspieldirektor (Impresario)</EM>,  K486, is a one-act 
comedy.  Composed in 1786, at the request of Emperor Joseph, for the royal 
occasion of a state visit by the Governor General of the Austrian Netherlands, 
Mozart's <EM>Impresario,</EM> was billed on a program with Antonio Salieri's <EM>Prima la 
musica, e poi le parole,</EM> or <EM>First the music, and then the words.</EM>  The librettist for 
the Mozart work was Gottlieb Stephanie, with whom the composer had 
collaborated previously  on <EM>The Abduction from the Seraglio.</EM>  The plot centers 
on the efforts of an Impresario to put together a theater group which could 
successfully perform plays, ballet, and opera in Salzberg.  In two parts, the first 
deals with auditions of actors and actresses, while in the second, two "dueling 
divas" attempt to out-do each other, each wanting to be the prima donna of the 
troupe.  Reason is restored when the troupe's composer reminds the embattled 
sopranos that, while artists must strive to achieve excellence, it is more 
important that the combined efforts please the audience than to be self serving.  
The cast consist of 2 sopranos, tenor and bass.  The Impresario is a spoken 
role.
<P>
These two charming works lend themselves well to an evening of delightful 
entertainment.
<CENTER>
<P><A HREF="framed.html"><STRONG>Return to Euterpe home page.</STRONG></A>
</P>
</CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>

